th = 900\n | height = 250\n | type = rect\n | yGrid =\n | xGrid =\n | xAxisAngle = -65\n | x = 12/3, 13/3, 14/3, 15/3, 16/3, 17/3, 18/3, 19/3, 20/3, 21/3, 22/3, 23/3, 24/3, 25/3, 26/3, 27/3, 28/3, 29/3, 30/3, 31/3, 1/4, 2/4, 3/4, 4/4, 5/4, 6/4, 7/4, 8/4, 9/4, 10/4, 11/4\n | y = 1, 14, 11, 23, 8, 25, 21, 9, 7, 17, 22, 11, 1, 0, 2, 10, 15, 0, 4, 5, 3, 1, 5, 10, 13, 2, 1, 7, 0, 2, 10\n | legend=Legend\n |y1Title = Cases per day\n | showValues=offset:2\n | xAxisTitle=Date (day/month)\n | yAxisTitle=No. of new cases\n | colors = orange\n}}\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== March 2020 ===\nOn 12 March 2020, Sabah reported its first positive case involving a male resident from [[Tawau District]] who is one of the participant in the Muslim religious gathering at [[Sri Petaling]] in [[Kuala Lumpur]]. He began to developed symptoms after returning and was subsequently transferred to Tawau Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148672/sabah-s-first-covid-19-case-found-in-tawau/|title=Sabah's first Covid-19 case found in Tawau|work=New Straits Times|via=Daily Express|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318052110/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148672/sabah-s-first-covid-19-case-found-in-tawau/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A second positive case was reported the following day in Benoni's [[Papar District]] which is also originated from the religious gathering where he was then transferred to [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital, Kota Kinabalu|Queen Elizabeth Hospital]] for further treatment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148674/exclusive-sabah-s-second-positive-covid-19-case-in-papar/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Sabah's second positive Covid-19 case in Papar|work=Daily Express|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318052110/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148672/sabah-s-first-covid-19-case-found-in-tawau/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A total of 14 new confirmed cases were recorded within the day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148680/14-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-total-15/|title=14 new Covid-19 cases in Sabah, total 15|work=Daily Express|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318054827/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148680/14-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-total-15/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 14 March, the Sabah State Health Department reported that another 11 new cases were confirmed in the state which bringing the total to 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148755/11-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-total-26/|title=11 new Covid-19 cases in Sabah, total 26|work=Daily Express|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318055027/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148755/11-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-total-26/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A further spike to 82 positive cases has been reported which making Sabah the third most affected by the virus after [[Selangor]] and Kuala Lumpur.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148946/25-new-cases-in-sabah-make-it-82/|title=25 new cases in Sabah make it 82|work=Daily Express|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318054427/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148946/25-new-cases-in-sabah-make-it-82/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Earlier since the first positive case was reported, the State Health Department has warned there will be more positive cases to be detected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/expect-more-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-says-state-health-director|title=Expect more Covid-19 cases in Sabah, says state Health Director|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319064439/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/expect-more-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-says-state-health-director|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148679/possibly-more-sabah-covid-19-cases-but-stay-calm-/|title=Possibly more Sabah Covid-19 cases, but stay calm|work=Daily Express|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320041320/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148679/possibly-more-sabah-covid-19-cases-but-stay-calm-/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 18 March, the total positive cases has risen to 103.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/18/21-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-bringing-total-to-103/|title=21 new Covid-19 cases in Sabah, bringing total to 103|last=Santos|first=Jason|work=Free Malaysia Today|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319064601/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/18/21-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-bringing-total-to-103/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A further seven infections were recorded on 20 March, raising the total infected to 119 with the first death caused by the virus was reported in Tawau involving a 58-year-old man who is one of the participant of the religious gathering.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320124355/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149149/tawau-s-first-covid-19-case-dies/|title=Sabah's first Covid-19 case in Tawau dies|work=Daily Express|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320124355/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149149/tawau-s-first-covid-19-case-dies/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/21/seven-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-total-119/|title=Seven new Covid-19 cases in Sabah, total 119|last=Lajiun|first=Jenne|work=Borneo Post|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321065216/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/21/seven-new-covid-19-cases-in-sabah-total-119/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The religious gathering also causing the closure of [[palm oil]] plantations in three districts of Tawau, [[Lahad Datu District|Lahad Datu]] and [[Kinabatangan District|Kinabatangan]] in late March after several plantation workers who had participate in the gathering were found positive with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia-palmoil/malaysias-biggest-palm-oil-state-shuts-some-estates-after-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN21B1BW|title=Malaysia's biggest palm oil state shuts some estates after virus outbreak|last1=Chu|first1=Mei Mei|last2=Sipalan|first2=Joseph|last3=Ananthalakshmi|first3=A.|last4=Elgood|first4=Giles|last5=Gopalakrishnan|first5=Raju|last6=Goodman|first6=David|agency=Reuters|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411072207/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia-palmoil/malaysias-biggest-palm-oil-state-shuts-some-estates-after-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN21B1BW|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nUntil early April, a total of 7,173 coronavirus tests have been conducted by Sabah with the results of positive cases rising to 209.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/02/covid-19-sabah-has-tested-7173-people-identified-209-positive-cases|title=Covid-19: Sabah has tested 7,173 people, identified 209 positive cases|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410024451/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/02/covid-19-sabah-has-tested-7173-people-identified-209-positive-cases|archive-date=10 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Within the same month, more than 90 people have recovered from the virus with three deaths have been reported since March; the latest involving a 66-year-old man in [[Tambunan District|Tambunan]] with a medical history of [[diabetes]], [[high blood pressure]] and [[kidney disease]] on 5 April along with a 62-year-old retired senior Sabah government official and tabligh worker who died in [[Kota Kinabalu]] on 10 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/06/second-death-in-sabah/|title=Second death in Sabah|last=Sim Yee|first=Chok|work=Borneo Post|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411051110/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150577/two-new-covid-19-cases-nine-more-recover-in-sabah/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150577/two-new-covid-19-cases-nine-more-recover-in-sabah/|title=Two new Covid-19 cases, nine more recover in Sabah|work=Daily Express|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411051618/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/06/second-death-in-sabah/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The State Health Department has explained that further positive cases will only be known once 4,600 samples are cleared in the next two days by a special task force set up on 8 April, which previously ridden with backlog following the shortage of [[reagent]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150522/sabah-s-real-situation-to-be-known-soon-dept/|title=Sabah\u2019s real situation to be known soon: Dept|last1=Peter|first1=Anthea|last2=Into|first2=Ricardo|last3=Chok|first3=Christy|work=Daily Express|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411085647/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150522/sabah-s-real-situation-to-be-known-soon-dept/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Implications ==\n=== Masks and hand sanitiser shortages ===\nSabah's capital city of [[Kota Kinabalu]] have reported shortages on both [[surgical masks]] and [[hand sanitiser]] since January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/01/28/face-masks-hand-sanitiser-sold-out-in-jb-kk/|title=Face masks, hand sanitiser sold out in JB, KK|agency=Bernama|via=The Malaysian Reserve|date=28 January 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223030553/https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/01/28/face-masks-hand-sanitiser-sold-out-in-jb-kk/|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There were reports that some businesses in the state taking advantage of the situation by selling overpriced masks during the period which led them being fined by the [[Ministry of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs (Malaysia)|Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Ministry]] branch of Sabah.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/07/three-businesses-in-sabah-selling-overpriced-masks-compounded-rm30500|title=Three businesses in Sabah selling overpriced masks compounded RM30,500|work=The Star|date=7 February 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318062534/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/07/three-businesses-in-sabah-selling-overpriced-masks-compounded-rm30500|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Panic buying ===\nMany of the state residents in each districts rush to stock up [[goods|essential items]] once the first positive case were reported among netizens even before the official announcement of the first case was made by the [[Government of Sabah|state government]] of Sabah.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/panic-buying-hits-sabah-after-first-covid-19-case-announced|title=People starting to stock up goods in parts of Sabah after first Covid-19 case announced|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318060210/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/panic-buying-hits-sabah-after-first-covid-19-case-announced|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/panic-buying-hits-sabah-after-first-coronavirus-case-in-the-state|title=Panic-buying hits Sabah after first coronavirus case in the state|work=The Star/Asia News Network|via=The Straits Times|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> With the rising number of positive cases been reported, residents in one of Sabah's district of [[Kunak District|Kunak]] are reportedly buying large quantities of rice to stock up foods.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148947/panic-buying-continues/|title=Panic buying continues|last=Tabir|first=Ibrahim|work=Daily Express|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318060657/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148947/panic-buying-continues/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Deputy Chief Minister of Sabah [[Christina Liew]] also called on the community in her constituency of [[Tawau (federal constituency)|Tawau]] from panic buying caused by the quick spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/13/covid-19-sabah-dcm-urges-tawau-community-to-avoid-panic-buying-essential-it/1845981|title=Covid-19: Sabah DCM urges Tawau community to avoid panic buying essential items|work=Bernama|via=The Malay Mail|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321062644/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/13/covid-19-sabah-dcm-urges-tawau-community-to-avoid-panic-buying-essential-it/1845981|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Counter-measures by state government and other parties ==\nSince the earlier several suspected cases in Sabah's capital of Kota Kinabalu, all direct flights between the state with [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|mainland China]] have been stopped indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/01/30/wuhan-coronavirus-all-flights-from-china-to-sabah-suspended-as-state-govt-imposes-travel-ban/|title=Wuhan coronavirus: All flights from China to Sabah suspended as state govt imposes travel ban|work=Borneo Post|date=30 January 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201050803/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/01/30/wuhan-coronavirus-all-flights-from-china-to-sabah-suspended-as-state-govt-imposes-travel-ban/|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Further [[travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|travel restrictions]] were imposed by the state government towards the three most affected countries by the virus; comprising [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]] by March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/10/sabah-bans-travellers-from-iran-and-italy|title=Sabah bans travellers from Iran and Italy|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=10 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314064405/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/10/sabah-bans-travellers-from-iran-and-italy|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/147905/sabah-extends-covid-19-travel-restrictions-to-s-korea/|title=Sabah extends Covid-19 travel restrictions to S Korea|work=Daily Express|date=29 February 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314062724/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/147905/sabah-extends-covid-19-travel-restrictions-to-s-korea/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Annual cultural events in Sabah such as the [[Kaamatan]] ([[Kadazan-Dusun|Kadazan-Dusun festival]]) and Kalimaran ([[Murut people|Murut festival]]) have been cancelled,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148676/kaamatan-festival-2020-cancelled-due-to-covid-19/|title=Kaamatan Festival 2020 cancelled due to Covid-19|work=Daily Express|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314021932/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148676/kaamatan-festival-2020-cancelled-due-to-covid-19/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/03/554452/dua-pesta-tahunan-sabah-dibatalkan|title=Dua pesta tahunan Sabah dibatalkan|trans-title=Two annual Sabah festivals are cancelled|last=Dahali|first=Rafiqah|language=Malay|work=Harian Metro|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315044826/https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/03/554452/dua-pesta-tahunan-sabah-dibatalkan|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> while [[Mass in the Catholic Church|Catholic Masses]] and [[Good Friday]] in the state were observed through a [[live broadcast]] online.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148682/suspension-of-catholic-masses-and-gatherings/|title=Suspension of Catholic Masses and gatherings|work=Daily Express|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320040624/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574582/masses-sabah-go-online|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574582/masses-sabah-go-online|title=Masses in Sabah go online|last=Geraldine|first=Avila|work=New Straits Times|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314023506/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148682/suspension-of-catholic-masses-and-gatherings/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/10/sabah-and-sarawak-to-observe-good-friday-online|title=Sabah and Sarawak to observe Good Friday online|last1=Then|first1=Stephen|last2=Lee|first2=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411063811/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/10/sabah-and-sarawak-to-observe-good-friday-online|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The state government has released several guidelines to curb the spread of the virus and assured the public that [[goods|essential goods]] will be sufficient despite the ongoing increase of infections and panic buying.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/sabah-comes-up-with-steps-to-curb-spread-of-covid-19|title=Sabah comes up with steps to curb spread of Covid-19|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320041616/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/sabah-comes-up-with-steps-to-curb-spread-of-covid-19|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/15/sufficient-supply-of-essential-goods-in-sabah|title=Sufficient supply of essential goods in Sabah|last=Vanar|first=Muguntan|work=The Star|date=15 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320041138/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/15/sufficient-supply-of-essential-goods-in-sabah|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn line with the announcement of the [[2020 Malaysia movement control order|movement control order]] (MCO) made by the [[Government of Malaysia|federal government]] of Malaysia since the growing number of infections within the country, non-Sabahans are barred from entering the state with immediate effect as additional efforts to counter the increase in the number of positive cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148950/non-sabahans-barred/|title=Non-Sabahans barred|work=Daily Express|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318061532/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148950/non-sabahans-barred/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Sabahan university students in Peninsular Malaysia with settlement problem during the order period may stay at Sabah House, Cheras with food provided by the state government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/covid-19-mahasiswa-sabah-di-semenanjung-boleh-tinggal-di-rumah-sabah-cheras-234220|title=COVID-19: Mahasiswa Sabah di Semenanjung boleh tinggal di Rumah Sabah Cheras|last=Zulkepli|first=Ruzaini|work=Astro Awani|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322084051/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/covid-19-mahasiswa-sabah-di-semenanjung-boleh-tinggal-di-rumah-sabah-cheras-234220|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Malay|trans-title=COVID-19: Sabah University Students in Peninsular may stay at Sabah House Cheras}}</ref> Civil servants across the country are exempts from the ban despite each of them still must showing valid confirmation letters that are issued by their heads of departments for each specific task.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsabahtimes.com.my/nstweb/fullstory/37647|title=State govt allows exemption for civil servants|last=Ebit|first=Jason Jack|work=New Sabah Times|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321064249/http://www.newsabahtimes.com.my/nstweb/fullstory/37647|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Following reports of poor compliance to the MCO in the state capital of Kota Kinabalu, the [[Royal Malaysia Police]] (PDRM) has imposed citywide round-the-clock roadblocks aimed at warning obstinate individuals who go against the order until the end of the two week period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/18/poor-compliance-to-movement-control-order-in-sabah|title=Poor compliance to movement control order in Sabah|last1=Vanar|first1=Muguntan|last2=Lee|first2=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321063147/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/18/poor-compliance-to-movement-control-order-in-sabah|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsabahtimes.com.my/nstweb/fullstory/37652|title=Round-the-clock roadblocks by police in Kota Kinabalu|last=Nicholas|first=Jonathan|work=New Sabah Times|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321063323/http://www.newsabahtimes.com.my/nstweb/fullstory/37652|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> With the increasing enforcement being conducted, city folks are getting better at complying the order.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/mco-compliance-improving-in-kota-kinabalu|title=MCO compliance improving in Kota Kinabalu|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321063551/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/mco-compliance-improving-in-kota-kinabalu|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The state government also sealed off coronavirus hotspots in major towns such as in several areas in Kota Kinabalu, [[Sandakan]] and Tawau to minimise movement amid a growing number of cases in these areas including ordering some factories and plantations in [[Kalabakan]] and Lahad Datu with detection of cases to cease their operation as well as stopping [[barter|barter trading]] between east coast of Sabah and the neighbouring [[Philippines]] and [[Indonesia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/24/sabah-covid-19-039hotspots039-sealed-off-to-reduce-movement-exposure|title=Sabah Covid-19 'hotspots' sealed off to reduce movement, exposure|work=The Star|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411062733/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/24/sabah-covid-19-039hotspots039-sealed-off-to-reduce-movement-exposure|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite the second extension of the MCO announced on 10 April, the Sabah government has give relaxation to palm oil plantations and mills in six eastern Sabah districts of Kalabakan, Kinabatangan, [[Kunak District|Kunak]], Lahad Datu, [[Semporna District|Semporna]] and Tawau to operate under certain conditions that need to be complied.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150579/oil-palm-estates-can-operate-on-conditions-cm/|title=Oil palm estates can operate on conditions: CM|last=Dzulkifli|first=Hayati|work=Daily Express|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411121304/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150579/oil-palm-estates-can-operate-on-conditions-cm/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, Sabah Assistant Minister of the local government and the Ministry of Housing Hiew Vun Zin said that there are a total of nine buildings in the People's Housing Program (PPR) Batu Putih in [[Sandakan District]], three of which are blocks H, I and G will be serving as isolation centres.<ref name=\"Sabah PPR quarantine centre\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sinchew.com.my/content/content_2237106.html|title=\u5168\u56fd\u9996\u95f4\u00b7\u4eba\u6c11\u7ec4\u5c4b\u5145\u9694\u79bb\u4e2d\u5fc3|trans-title=The first PPR Isolation Centre in Sabah|language=Chinese|work=Sinchew+|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"self-quarantine\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/18/30-self-quarantine-at-sandakan-ppr/|title=30 self-quarantine at Sandakan PPR|work=Borneo Post|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320024309/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/18/30-self-quarantine-at-sandakan-ppr/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Each building has 100 units and each unit has 3 bedrooms. As long as they are tested as [[Patient Under Investigation|patients under investigation]] by the Health Bureau and [[Duchess of Kent Hospital]], the authorities will send them and their families to the isolation centre for 14 days of isolation. At the time there is more than 30 people were being quarantined at the centre, including six families.<ref name=\"Sabah PPR quarantine centre\"/><ref name=\"self-quarantine\"/> The State Health Department has put a total of 350 beds on standby for coronavirus infected patient.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149152/350-beds-on-standby-for-sabah-cases-dept/|title=350 beds on standby for Sabah cases: Dept|last=Ralon|first=Larry|work=Daily Express|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321065604/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149152/350-beds-on-standby-for-sabah-cases-dept/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> With the reports that there is another Muslim religious gathering to be held at [[Gowa]], [[South Sulawesi]] in neighbouring Indonesia, the Sabah state government implements immediate action to ban the entry of those who attended the gathering.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149153/sabah-bans-indonesia-tabligh-attendees/|title=Sabah bans Indonesia Tabligh attendees|work=New Straits Times|via=Daily Express|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321065827/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149153/sabah-bans-indonesia-tabligh-attendees/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Shortage of coronavirus test kits ===\nFollowing reports of the shortage of [[COVID-19 testing|coronavirus test kits]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/29/test-kit-shortage-hampers-sabahs-anti-virus-efforts/|title=Test kit shortage hampers Sabah\u2019s anti-virus efforts|last=Santos|first=Jason|work=Free Malaysia Today|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411052528/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/29/test-kit-shortage-hampers-sabahs-anti-virus-efforts/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the Sabah government has acquired an immediate supply of 5,000 reagents from [[Singapore]] on 4 April through a joint efforts between the state government and [[non-governmental organisation]] (NGOs) with another 5,000 arrived the following day.<ref name=\"test kits supply\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150135/sabah-decides-not-to-wait/|title=Sabah decides not to wait|work=Daily Express|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411052635/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/150135/sabah-decides-not-to-wait/|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"test kits with medical supplies\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/03/sabah-gets-much-needed-covid-19-test-kits-medical-supplies-flown-in|title=Sabah gets much-needed Covid-19 test kits, medical supplies flown in|last=Vanar|first=Muguntan|work=The Star|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411054023/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/03/sabah-gets-much-needed-covid-19-test-kits-medical-supplies-flown-in|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The reagents along with critically low medical supplies donated by the federal government including 200,000 face masks, 50,000 gloves, 10,000 litres of [[sanitiser]]s and a variety of medical equipments specifically for medical frontliners in Sabah were flown through a [[Royal Malaysian Air Force]] (RMAF) flight.<ref name=\"test kits supply\"/><ref name=\"test kits with medical supplies\"/>\n\n== Aid to Sabah on the pandemic ==\n=== Local aid ===\nThe Sabah state government has announced a total of RM670 million aid to help ease the burden of the people affected by the outbreak with 15 measures had been formulated under the package, involving three categories including assistance to frontliners staffs and the affected people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/business/news.php?id=1824877|title=Sabah announces RM670 million COVID-19 aid package|agency=Bernama|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Foreign aid ===\n[[China]]'s Consulate-General in Kota Kinabalu has announced that medical aid to be dispatched to Sabah to aid their struggle against the virus and reciprocate the people's of Sabah recent assistance to [[Mainland China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149233/china-to-send-medical-aid-to-sabah/|title=EXCLUSIVE: China to send medical aid to Sabah|work=Daily Express|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321070223/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149233/china-to-send-medical-aid-to-sabah/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/china-to-reciprocate-sabahs-kindness-liang/|title=China to reciprocate Sabah's kindness \u2013 Liang|work=Borneo Post|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324032130/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/china-to-reciprocate-sabahs-kindness-liang/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first aid came to Sabah on 29 March, which consists of 83 boxes of face masks with 2,000 pieces before a further 170,000 boxes of face masks, personal equipments and sanitisers delivered directly to the Sabah state government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2020/03/670760/sabah-terima-170000-kotak-topeng-muka-ppe-dari-china|title=Sabah terima 170,000 kotak topeng muka, PPE dari China|trans-title=Sabah received 170,000 boxes of face masks, PPE from China|last=Dahali|first=Rafiqah|language=Malay|work=Berita Harian|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406015201/https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2020/03/670760/sabah-terima-170000-kotak-topeng-muka-ppe-dari-china|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/29/sabah-gets-fresh-boost-of-medical-masks-supplies-from-china/1851448|title=Sabah gets fresh boost of medical masks, supplies from China|last=Chan|first=Julia|work=The Malay Mail|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405151732/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/29/sabah-gets-fresh-boost-of-medical-masks-supplies-from-china/1851448|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149813/china-sends-masks-and-sanitisers/|title=China sends masks and sanitisers|last=Ralon|first=Larry|work=Daily Express|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405160213/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149813/china-sends-masks-and-sanitisers/|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Another 20,000 [[surgical mask]]s destined for Sabah's healthcare frontliner workers were delivered in early April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/region/news.php?id=1828245|title=Sabah receives additional 20,000 surgical masks from China|agency=Bernama|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sarawak]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Malaysia|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://jknsabah.moh.gov.my/V8/index.php/en/ Sabah State Health Department website] \u2013 Further details on the coronavirus outbreak in Sabah\n* [http://sabahoutbreak.com/ Covid-19 Cases in Sabah on Sabah Outbreak] \u2013 Current updates on the coronavirus outbreak in Sabah\n* [https://www.sabahalert.com/ Covid-19 Cases in Sabah on Sabah Alerts] \u2013 SabahAlerts Covid-19 online tracker\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:History of Sabah]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia by state|Sabah]]\n", "name_user": "Zabivaka", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Sabah"}
{"title_page": "Helcion concolor", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Taxobox\n| name = ''Helcion concolor''\n| image = Patella variabilis concolor 002.jpg\n| image_caption = ''Helcion concolor'' shell\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Mollusca]]\n| classis = [[Gastropoda]]\n| unranked_superfamilia = clade [[Patellogastropoda]]\n| superfamilia = [[Patelloidea]]\n| familia = [[Patellidae]]\n| subfamilia =\n| genus = ''[[Helcion]]''\n| species = '''''H. concolor'''''\n| binomial = ''Helcion concolor''\n| binomial_authority = ([[Christian Ferdinand Friedrich Krauss|Krauss]], 1848)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"WoRMS\" />\n| synonyms =\n* ''Patella concolor'' <small>Krauss, 1848</small>\n* ''Patella concolor'' f. ''polygramma'' <small>Tomlin, 1931</small>\n* ''Patella farquhari'' <small>Turton, 1932</small>\n* ''Patella helena'' <small>Turton, 1932</small>\n* ''Patella rietensis'' <small>Turton, 1932</small>\n* ''Patella variabilis'' <small>Krauss, 1848</small>\n* ''Patella variabilis'' var. ''concolor'' <small>Krauss, 1848</small>\n* ''Patella variabilis'' var. ''constellata'' <small>Sowerby III, 1921</small>\n* ''Patella variabilis'' var. ''fasciata'' <small>Krauss, 1848</small>\n* ''Patella variabilis'' var. ''fasciolata'' <small>Tomlin, 1931</small>\n* ''Patella variabilis'' var. ''helvola'' <small>Turton, 1932</small>\n* ''Patella variabilis'' var. ''polygramma'' <small>Tomlin, 1931</small>\n* ''Patella variabilis'' var. ''radiata'' <small>Krauss, 1848</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Helcion concolor''''', [[common name]] the '''variable limpet''', is a [[species]] of [[sea snail]], a [[true limpet]], a marine [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Patellidae]], one of the families of true limpets.<ref name=\"WoRMS\">{{WRMS species|224957|''Helcion concolor'' (Krauss, 1848)||10 JUly 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThis species occurs in the Indian Ocean off [[Mozambique]] and [[South Africa]].\n\n==Description==\nThe size of the shell varies between 30&nbsp;mm and 60&nbsp;mm.\n{|\n|[[File:Patella variabilis polygramma 002.jpg|left|thumb|Dorsal view.]]\n|[[File:Patella variabilis polygramma 001.jpg|left|thumb|Ventral view.]]\n|}\n{{Expand section|date=June 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Kalk, M. (1958). ''The fauna of the intertidal rocks at Inhaca Island, Delagoa Bay''. Ann. Natal Mus. 14: 189\u2013242.\n* Kilburn, R. N. 1972. ''Taxonomic notes on South African marine Mollusca (2), with the description of new species and subspecies of Conus, Nassarius, Vexillum and Demoulia''. Annals of the Natal Museum 21(2):391\u2013437, 15 figs.\n* Kilburn, R.N. & Rippey, E. (1982) ''Sea Shells of Southern Africa''. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg, xi + 249 pp. page(s): 37\n* Steyn, D.G. & Lussi, M. (1998) ''Marine Shells of South Africa. An Illustrated Collector\u2019s Guide to Beached Shells''. Ekogilde Publishers, Hartebeespoort, South Africa, ii + 264 pp. page(s): 16\n* Koufopanou et al. (1999). ''A molecular phylogeny of the patellid limpets (Gastropoda: Patellidae) and its implications for the origins of their antitropical distribution'' Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 11(1):138\u2013156\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=W_2QB8ftLgcC  Branch, G.M. et al. (2002). ''Two Oceans.'' 5th impression. David Philip, Cate Town & Johannesburg]\n* Nakano & Ozawa (2007). ''Worldwide phylogeography of limpets of the order Patellogastropoda: Molecular, morphological and palaeontological evidence.'' Journal of Molluscan Studies 73(1) 79\u201399. \n* Petit R.E. (2009) ''George Brettingham Sowerby, I, II & III: their conchological publications and molluscan taxa''. Zootaxa 2189: 1\u2013218\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gastropods.com|key=6|id=6226|title=''Helcion (Helcion) concolor''|access-date=16 January 2019}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5701550}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Helcion Concolor}}\n[[Category:Patellidae]]\n[[Category:Gastropods described in 1848]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Christian Ferdinand Fri