01384)|Tulsa Oilers]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-12) text:[[Central Professional Hockey League|CHL]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-12) text:[[Central Professional Hockey League|CHL]]\n  bar:CHL  color:red from:01/07/1973 till:01/07/1976  shift:(40,-4) text:[[Oklahoma City Blazers (1965\u201377)|Oklahoma City Blazers]]\n  at:01/07/1973 mark:(line,white)\n  bar:CHL2  color:red from:01/07/1981 till:01/07/1982 text:[[Cincinnati Tigers (ice hockey)|Cincinnati Tigers]]\n  bar:NLA  color:red from:01/08/1968 till:01/01/1969 text:[[Toronto Maple Leafs (NLA)|Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-4) text:[[National Lacrosse Association|NLA]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-4) text:[[National Lacrosse Association|NLA]]\n  bar:CFL  color:red from:01/01/1978 till:01/01/1989 text:[[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]]\n  bar:CFL2  color:red from:19/01/2018 till:end shift:(-28,-4) text:[[Toronto Argonauts]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,4) text:[[Canadian Football League|CFL]]\n  at:end shift:(20,4) text:[[Canadian Football League|CFL]]\n  bar:NBA  color:red from:01/02/1998 till:end text:[[Toronto Raptors]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-4) text:[[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-4) text:[[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n  bar:MLS  color:red from:01/01/2007 till:end text:[[Toronto FC]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-4) text:[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-4) text:[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n  bar:USLPRO  color:red from:01/05/2015 till:end shift:(-5,-4) text:[[Toronto FC II]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-4) text:[[USL League One|USL]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-4) text:[[USL League One|USL]]\n  bar:NBAGL  color:red from:01/09/2015 till:end shift:(-5,-4) text:[[Raptors 905]]\n  at:start shift:(-21,-4) text:[[NBA G League|NBAGL]]\n  at:end shift:(26,-4) text:[[NBA G League|NBAGL]]\nLineData =\n  from:start till:end atpos:327\n  from:start till:end atpos:309\n  from:start till:end atpos:290\n  from:start till:end atpos:272\n  from:start till:end atpos:234\n  from:start till:end atpos:216\n  from:start till:end atpos:178\n  from:start till:end atpos:160\n  from:start till:end atpos:122\n  from:start till:end atpos:104\n  from:start till:end atpos:85\n  from:start till:end atpos:66\n  from:start till:end atpos:49\n  at:01/07/1931\nScaleMajor = gridcolor:line unit:year increment:5 start:01/01/1930\n\n</timeline>\n\n==Ownership==\n\n===Conn Smythe===\n[[File:Conn smythe.jpg|thumb|Conn Smythe, founder of Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n\nAlthough Conn Smythe was the face of MLGL from its founding in 1931, he did not acquire majority ownership of the company until 1947, following a power struggle between directors who supported him as president and those who wanted him replaced with [[Frank J. Selke]]. With the help of a $300,000 loan from Toronto stockbroker and MLGL shareholder Percy Gardiner, and the support of minority partner Jack Bickell, Smythe was able to buy 30,000 shares in MLGL from Gardiner<ref name=powerplay>{{cite news|title=Gardens power plays|date=April 3, 1995|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> and installed himself as president on November 19, 1947, replacing Edward Bickle.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baseball's bankroll gone |last=Dunnell|first=Milt|authorlink=Milt Dunnell|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=July 5, 1965}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Hunter |first=Douglas |year=1997 |title=Champions: The Illustrated History of Hockey's Greatest Dynasties. |location=Chicago, Illinois |publisher=Triumph Books |isbn=1-57243-213-6 |page=50}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Smythe is elected Gardens' president|date=November 20, 1947|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]}}</ref>  The loan was paid off in 1960.<ref>{{cite book |title=Centre Ice: The Smythe Family, the Gardens, and the Toronto Maple Leafs Hockey Club |last1=Smythe |first1=Thomas Stafford |last2=Shea |first2=Kevin Shea |publisher=Fenn Publishing Co. |year=2000 |location=Bolton, Ontario, Canada |isbn=1-55168-250-8 |ref=harv|pages=156\u2013167}}</ref>  In November 1961, Smythe sold 45,000 of his 50,000 shares to a three-person partnership formed by his son [[Stafford Smythe]], [[Harold Ballard]], and John Bassett (owner of the ''[[Toronto Telegram]]'' and part-owner of the Canadian Football League's Toronto Argonauts) for $2.3 million.  When combined with their own holdings, this gave the Stafford-Ballard-Bassett partnership 87,000 shares, representing 60% of the company.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|217}}<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=death>{{cite news|title=Ballard's death laid groundwork|date=December 1, 2010|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref name=bassettsells/> Ballard fronted Stafford most of the money for the purchase though a loan he obtained.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=shakeup>{{cite news|title=Ballard president in shakeup at Gardens|last=Beddoes|first=Dick|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=October 21, 1971}}</ref>  According to several sources, Conn thought the sale was only to his son,<ref name=thoughages/> and was furious when he learned that Ballard and Bassett were his partners. He had hoped that Stafford would keep MLGL for his son, Tommy.<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|217\u2013218}} However, it is unlikely that Stafford could have raised the millions needed for the deal on his own. Stafford became president of MLGL and governor of the Maple Leafs, with Ballard becoming executive vice president and Bassett chairman of the board.<ref name=powerplay/>\n\n===Harold Ballard, John Bassett, and Stafford Smythe===\nIn March 1966, Conn sold his remaining MLGL shares and resigned from the board of directors after a [[Muhammad Ali]] boxing match was scheduled for MLG. He found Ali's refusal to serve in the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] during the [[Vietnam War]] to be offensive,<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|232}} and said that by accepting the fight, MLGL owners had \"put cash ahead of class.\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Cash rated over class' Conn quits |author=McKee, Ken |work=Toronto Star |date=March 8, 1966}}</ref>  Within three years under the new owners, profits had tripled to just under $1 million. Ballard negotiated lucrative deals to place advertising throughout the building, and greatly increased the number of seats in the arena.<ref>''Ballard: A Portrait of Canada's Most Controversial Sports Figure'', William Houston, Summerhill Press, 1984, p. 60.</ref>\n\nFollowing a [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] raid at MLG in 1968, Stafford was charged with income tax evasion, and he and Ballard were accused of illegally taking money from MLGL to pay for home renovations and other personal expenses. Just before the charges were laid, Bassett argued to the board of directors that Stafford and Ballard should be removed from their posts. On June 26, 1969, following an 8\u20137 vote of the board, Stafford and Ballard were both fired, and Bassett was appointed president of MLGL. However, Bassett did not force Stafford and Ballard to sell their shares, and both men remained on the board.  This proved to be a serious strategic blunder; Stafford was the largest single shareholder in MLGL, and he and Ballard controlled almost half the company's stock between them.  They were thus able to regain control of the board in 1970, and Stafford was once again appointed president.<ref name=powerplay/>  Facing an untenable situation, Bassett sold the 196,200 MLGL shares he controlled to Stafford and Ballard in September 1971 for $5.4 million, which he used to buy out his partners in the Argonauts.<ref name=death/><ref name=bassettsells>{{cite news|title=Bassett sells Gardens stock, buys control of Argos|first=Dick|last=Beddoes|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|date=September 2, 1971|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=shakeup/> Combined with their 306,295 jointly controlled shares, the transaction gave the Stafford-Ballard partnership 78% of the stock.<ref name=bassettsells/><ref name=shakeup/>  Stafford died in October 1971 of a bleeding ulcer at only 50 years of age, just before his trial was scheduled to begin.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/> Under the terms of Stafford's will, of which Ballard was an [[executor]],<ref name=repeats>{{cite news|title=History repeats itself&nbsp;... almost|date=March 22, 1999|last=Tedesco|first=Theresa|newspaper=[[National Post]]}}</ref> each partner was allowed to buy the other's shares upon their death. Stafford's brother and son tried to keep the shares within the family,<ref>{{cite news|title=MLG control at stake: Smythe bid for Ballard stock rejected|first=Dick|last=Beddoes|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|date=January 5, 1972|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> but in February 1972 Ballard bought all 251,545 of Stafford's shares for $7.5 million, valuing the company at $22 million.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=death/><ref name=rinkrat/><ref name=buyscontrol/><ref name=gardensprez/> Stafford's brother Hugh also sold his shares to Ballard, ending the Smythe family's 45-year involvement in the company. Combined with Ballard's 262,162 shares, this gave him majority ownership of about 70%.<ref name=rinkrat>{{cite news|title=Harrold Ballard: From rink rat to Gardens' boss|date=February 5, 1972|newspaper=Toronto Star|last=Orr|first=Frank}}</ref><ref name=buyscontrol>{{cite news|title=Ballard buys Gardens control for $7,546,350|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=February 4, 1972|first=Milt|last=Dunnell|authorlink=Milt Dunnell}}</ref><ref name=gardensprez>{{cite news|title=Gardens' president Harold Ballard to buy Smythe shares|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=February 5, 1972|last=Lutsky|first=Irvin}}</ref>  Six months later, Ballard was convicted of 47 charges, including fraud and theft of money and goods, and sentenced to three years in a federal penitentiary.<ref name=howherold/><ref name=MLH70>{{cite web|url=http://mapleleafs.ice.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=42187|title=Maple Leafs History - 1970s|publisher=Maple Leafs Sports & Entertainment|accessdate=June 27, 2017}}</ref>{{sfn|Shea|Wilson|2016|p=212}}\n\n===Harold Ballard===\nIn 1966, Ballard set up a family [[holding company]] named Harold E. Ballard Ltd. (HEBL) for his assets, including his shares in MLGL, as part of an [[estate freeze]].<ref name=assulttrial>{{cite news|title=Son of a Ballard: Assault trial a rehearsal for family fight for fortune|date=September 23, 1989|last=McDonald|first=Archie|newspaper=[[Vancouver Sun]]}}</ref><ref name=follies>{{cite news|title=The Maple Leaf Follies: Who needs hockey? With a team of lawyers fighting for ambitious corporations and the feuding Ballard clan, nothing can compare with the faceoff for Maple Leaf Gardens|newspaper=[[Financial Post]]|date=October 1, 1991|last=Johnson|first=Arthur}}</ref> Ballard distributed 103 [[common shares]] in HEBL, with his three children (Bill, Harold Jr., and Mary Elizabeth) each receiving 34 which were held in [[Trust law|trust]], and his wife Dorothy receiving 1, which Harold would inherit upon her death three years later.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=assulttrial/><ref name=familyaffair>{{cite news|title=Ballard money a family affair Daughter gets $15.5 million as Harold buys her shares|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=January 25, 1989}}</ref><ref name=missdeadline/> Harold retained 308,000 [[preferred shares]] in HEBL.<ref name=follies/><ref name=faceoffbrewing>{{cite news|title=Faceoff brewing over Ballard's fortune|last=Hurst|first=Lynda|newspaper=[[Montreal Gazette]]|date=February 25, 1990}}</ref>  While the equity of the company was vested in the common stock, both common and preferred shares each received a single vote, ensuring that Harold retained control of the company.<ref name=follies/>\n\nAfter getting into financial difficulty, Ballard reached an agreement in November 1980 with [[Molson Brewery]] (who at the time owned the Montreal Canadiens) for the company to cover his debt financing charges on a loan of $8.8 million for 10 years in exchange for an option to purchase a 19.9% block of shares in MLGL from HEBL and a right of first refusal on the rest of HEBL's shares.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=molsonnets/><ref name=molsonpurchase/>  The NHL did not learn of the deal until the late 1980s.<ref name=molsonnets/> In 1982, he offered to sell the company for $50 million, with the arena alone reportedly valued at $11 million, though a stockholders' report the following year placed the value of MLGL at $23.5 million.<ref name=bigmoney/><ref name=price/> When Harold transferred ownership of his personal real estate holdings, which were valued at $2.52 million, to HEBL in January 1989, he acquired 4 newly issued common shares in the company plus a promise of a further $896,472 rather than cash.<ref name=howherold/><ref name=follies/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> Mary Elizabeth sold her stake in HEBL to her father for $15.5 million in January 1989,<ref name=familyaffair/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> after originally having a deal to sell the stake to Don Giffin,<ref name=follies/> while Harold Jr. sold his back to HEBL for $21 million in June of the same year.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=follies/><ref name=missdeadline/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> Harold secured a loan from Molson for the full amount of his buyout of Mary Elizabeth, using the 34 acquired shares in HEBL as security.<ref name=missdeadline>{{cite news|title=Harold E. Ballard Ltd. misses Molson loan deadline|date=January 3, 1991|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]}}</ref> Harold Jr.'s shares were subsequently retired.<ref name=faceoffbrewing/> Bill sued his father for $170 million over HEBL's acquisition of Harold Jr.'s stake,<ref name=assulttrial/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> claiming that he and partner [[Michael Cohl]] had acquired a right of first refusal to purchase the shares for $20 million that February.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> Shortly thereafter, HEBL issued Harold 32 common shares and $125,216 in exchange for ownership of his 350,200 personally held MLGL shares and $125,000.<ref name=howherold/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> Two more new common shares would be granted to Harold to repay the $911,000 debt HEBL owed him from his two transactions with the company.<ref name=howherold/> This gave Harold, who feared that Bill was positioning himself to take over the holding company, control of HEBL.<ref name=powerplay/> Harold did not want his bickering children to inherit MLGL because he feared they would destroy it.<ref name=howherold>{{cite news|title=How Harold Ballard got the Gardens|last=Tyler|first= Tracey|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=November 25, 1990}}</ref>\n\nThough Ballard ran up significant amounts of personal debt during his ownership of MLGL, he made the company very profitable, so much so that MLG became known as the \"Cashbox on Carlton Street,\" referring to the address of the arena.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4tlXuNrwjsYC&pg=PT416&lpg=PT416|title=The Lives of Conn Smythe|first=Kelly|last=McParland|year=2011|publisher=[[Random House]]}}</ref> Upon Harold's death on April 11, 1990,<ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/>{{sfn|Shea|Wilson|2016|p=275}} most of his estate, which was worth less than $50 million, was left to charitable organizations.<ref name=deepdebt/> The executors of Harold's will were supermarket tycoon [[Steve Stavro]], Giffin, and [[Donald Crump]]. In November 1990 Molson exercised their option on 19.9% of the company, paying $10,000 for 735,575 of HEBL's MLGL shares, which at the time were valued at $20 million.<ref name=molsonnets/> Due to restrictions against cross-ownership in the NHL, the company set up a trust to hold their stake,<ref name=molsonnets>{{cite news|title=Molson nets share of Maple Leafs|date=November 2, 1990|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]}}</ref><ref name=molsonpurchase>{{cite news|title=Molson to purchase $20 million in Gardens shares for $10,000|newspaper=[[Kitchener-Waterloo Record]]|date=November 1, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Molson puts shares of Gardens in trust|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=November 1, 1990}}</ref> and the league instructed them to sell the shares within an \"adequate amount of time.\"<ref name=missdeadline/><ref name=cantpay/><ref name=Molsondeal/> Shortly after the estate, which had limited income due to HEBL still owing [[Toronto-Dominion Bank]] $15.8 million on its loan to acquire Harold Jr's HEBL stock, missed a January 1991 deadline to repay its $20 million loan (including interest) from Molson,<ref name=missdeadline/><ref name=cantpay>{{cite news|title=TD payments left Ballard with no cash for Molson|date=January 4, 1991|newspaper=Toronto Star|last=Van Alphen|first=Tony}}</ref> Stavro personally loaned the estate the funds to pay off the debt,<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=death/><ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Ballard loses in court to Stavro|newspaper=[[Windsor Star]]|date=April 13, 1991}}</ref> and in exchange, he received an option to purchase the estate's HEBL shares before January 1996.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=death/><ref name=deepdebt>{{cite news|title=Ballard's estate deeper in debt despite Leafs season|date=June 25, 1993|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]}}</ref><ref name=deepdebt/><ref name=Molsondeal/> Bill challenged the transaction, but it was approved by the court.<ref name=billjoins/> In early 1991, Molson offered to buy the estate's shares for $40 each.<ref name=billjoins/> In September 1991, Bill sold his HEBL stock to his father's estate for $21 million, giving it ownership of the entire company.<ref name=Molsondeal>{{cite news|title=Molson deal gives Stavro total control of Gardens|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=September 24, 1991}}</ref> Shortly thereafter it was announced that Stavro had reached a deal with Molson on an option to purchase their MLGL shares until April 1994 and for Molson to waive their option on the estate's shares.<ref name=deepdebt/><ref name=Molsondeal/>\n\n===Steve Stavro===\n{{chart top|width=100%|Ownership structure prior to privatization in 1998}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart| | | | | MLGL | | | | |MLGL=MLGL}}\n{{chart| | |,|-|-|^|.| | | | }}\n{{chart| | PUBLIC | | MLGV | | | | PUBLIC=Outstanding public stock|MLGV=MLGV}}\n{{chart| | | | | |,|^|-|-|.| }}\n{{chart| | | | | MLGH | | OTPP |MLGH=MLGH<br/>51%|OTPP=OTPP<br/>49%}}\n{{chart| |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.| }}\n{{chart| TD | | SS | | KILMER | TD=TD Bank<br/>20%|SS=Steve Stavro<br/>55%|KILMER=Kilmer Sports<br/>25%}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | |!| }}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | LT | LT=Larry Tanenbaum<br/>100%}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\nStavro founded MLG Ventures (MLGV) in March 1994 with partners Toronto\u2014Dominion Bank and [[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]].<ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=osc>{{cite web|url=https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/en/10823.htm|title=In the matter of the Securities Act, R.S.O. 1990, Chapter S.5|publisher=[[Ontario Securities Commission]]|accessdate=March 8, 2014}}</ref>  MLG Holdings Ltd. (MLGH), of which Stavro owned 80% and TD Bank controlled the remaining 20%, held a 51% ownership stake in MLGV, with the remaining 49% owned by Teachers'.<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=rubber/><ref name=bigwins>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2007/1126/103.html|title=Big Wins - At the Bank|date=November 26, 2007|accessdate=March 16, 2014|work=[[Forbes]]|first=Christina|last=Settimi}}</ref>  The following month MLGV announced that they had reached an agreement to purchase the 60.3% of MLGL held by Harold's estate for $34 a share or $75 million total, valuing the company at $125 million.<ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=faceoff>{{cite news|title=The face-off at Maple Leaf Gardens|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=August 13, 1994}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Date-by-Date Story of Gardens Takeover Fight|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/512622201.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+11%2C+1994&author=&pub=The+Spectator&edition=&startpage=C.15&desc=Date-by-date+story+of+Gardens+takeover+fight|newspaper=[[The Hamilton Spectator]]|date=November 11, 1994|page=C15}}</ref><ref name=slow>{{cite news|title=Slow speed of probe into sale angers Gardens shareholders|date=August 4, 1994|newspaper=Toronto Star|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen}}</ref><ref name=settotake/> The estate still owned Stavro $23 million at the time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stavro's Gardens bid enjoys the rink to itself|date=April 11, 1994|newspaper=Toronto Star|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen}}</ref>  Molson also sold its 19.9% of MLGL to MLGV in April 1994 for $25 million.<ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=faceoff/><ref name=settotake/> Larry Tanenbaum's company Kilmer Sports purchased a 25% share of MLGH from Stavro in 1996 for a reported $21 million.<ref name=death/><ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=rubber/><ref name=stavrosells>{{cite news|title=Stavro sells off part of Gardens NHL expected to give him fast nod for deal with pal|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=June 21, 1996}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/news/larrytanenbaum_bio.html|title=Larry Tanenbaum|accessdate=March 8, 2014|publisher=[[Toronto Raptors]]}}</ref>\n\nMLGV subsequently purchased all the remaining shares and took MLGL private in 1998, after acquiring more than the 90% of stock necessary to force objecting shareholders out,<ref name=rubber>{{cite news|title=Stavro set to take Gardens private Meeting seen as a 'rubber stamp'|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=August 6, 1996}}</ref><ref name=slow/><ref name=settotake>{{cite news|title=Stavro set to take Gardens private|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=May 3, 1994}}</ref> and MLGL and MLGV amalgamated.<ref name=death/><ref name=osc/>  The purchase was the subject of an [[Ontario Securities Commission]] (OSC) review, due to allegations that MLGV had engaged in [[insider trading]] by failing to disclose that broadcast revenue was expected to substantially increase,<ref name=isnteverything/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=osc/><ref name=quietexit/><ref name=eyeweekly>{{cite web|url=http://contests.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_04.01.99/rolling/times.php|title=Signs of the times|date=April 1, 1999|accessdate=March 16, 2014|work=[[Eye Weekly]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317081458/http://contests.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_04.01.99/rolling/times.php|archivedate=March 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/1999/03/23/Franchises/STAVRO-FOUND-TO-HAVE-MISLED-SHAREHOLDERS-DURING-94-BID.aspx?hl=NHL&sc=0|title=Stavro found to have misled shareholders during '94 bid|date=March 23, 1999|accessdate=March 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=irregular/> and a $50 million lawsuit from Bill who claimed that Stavro and others devalued MLGL and withheld information relevant to the value of the company prior to the sale of his stock.<ref name=billjoins>{{cite news|title=Bill Ballard joins Gardens battle Files lawsuit seeking return of his shares|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=February 23, 1996}}</ref>  Ontario's Office of the Public Trustee, which was charged with representing the charities named by Harold's will as beneficiaries, argued that Stavro had a conflict of interest as both executor of the will and buyer and had not paid market value because there was no public bidding process for the shares.<ref name=repeats/><ref name=billjoins/><ref name=faceoff/><ref name=settotake/><ref name=quietexit/>  Several minority owners, including [[Harry Ornest]], who held 3.5% of the company, and [[Jim Devellano]] also objected to MLGV's attempts to take the company private without an auction.<ref name=repeats/><ref name=faceoff/><ref name=slow/>  Stavro and his partners in MLGV reached a settlement in 1996 to pay an additional $23.5 million plus interest to the charities as well as $2.5 million to the minority shareholders who had sued,<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=rubber/><ref name=quietexit/> clearing the way for them to become the majority owner of MLGL.  They also settled with the OSC in 1999 for $1.6 million, which included a fine and costs.<ref name=quietexit>{{cite web|url=http://www.canoe.ca/NewsStand/LondonFreePress/Sports/2003/06/26/119735.html|title= A quiet exit for Maple Leafs boss|date=June 26, 2003|accessdate=March 16, 2014|newspaper=[[The London Free Press]]|first=Lance|last=Hornby}}</ref><ref name=eyeweekly/><ref name=irregular>{{cite web|url=http://investorvoice.ca/PI/006.html|title= An irregular regulator|first=Karen|last=Howlett|date=October 20, 1999|accessdate=March 16, 2014|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>  Teachers' invested $44.3 million and TD $9.75 million in the deal.<ref name=otppgraphic>{{cite web|url=http://www.otpp.com/documents/10179/20932/MLSE+Infographic/d8ea6bed-5a05-4879-8b29-9e400488a251|title=Play-by-play|accessdate=March 9, 2014|year=2012|publisher=[[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]]}}</ref><ref name=longtime/>\n\nFollowing the merger, the ownership structure of the now defunct MLGV was retained by MLGL.  MLGH was the majority owner of MLGL, holding 51% of the company.  It in turn was controlled by Stavro (55%), with minority shareholders Tanenbaum (25%) and TD Capital Group (20%).<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=rubber/><ref name=stavrosells/> The remaining 49% of MLGL was owned by Teachers'.<ref name=rubber/><ref name=stavrosells/><ref name=longtime/><ref name=longtime>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/2011/05/11/td-decision-to-divest-mlse-interest-long-time-coming/|title=How TD became a MVP in the MLSE sale|last=Tedesco|first=Theresa|date=May 11, 2011|accessdate=March 8, 2014|newspaper=[[National Post]]}}</ref>  This tiered ownership structure gave Stavro effective control of MLGL with only a net 29% stake of the company.<ref name=longtime/>  Teachers' invested a further $50 million in the company in the form of a [[convertible bond]] in 1998 to finance the purchase of the Raptors and ACC and complete construction of the arena.<ref name=isnteverything>{{cite news | last = Vardi | first = Nathan | title = Winning Isn't Everything | url = https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2007/1126/096.html#selection-653.27-653.98 | work = Forbes | date = November 16, 2007 | accessdate = November 16, 2007}}</ref><ref name=bigwins/>\n\n===Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan===\nIn 2003 an agreement was reached to restructure the company with Stavro selling his stake to [[Bell Globemedia]] for a reported $120\u2013150-million after debt repayments,<ref name=longtime/> the other partners converting their debts into equity, and each partner getting a direct ownership stake in the newly renamed MLSE, with MLGH being dissolved.<ref name=isnteverything/><ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=longtime/> This left Teachers' as the controlling majority owners of MLSE with 58.4%, and minority partners Bell Globemedia (15.4%), TD Capital with (13.5%) and Tanenbaum, who took over as non-executive chairman, with 13%.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=isnteverything/><ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=longtime/>  Each owner of MLSE had a right of first refusal on any shares sold, in proportion to their ownership share.<ref name=longtime/><ref name=snapup/>  The same year MLSE was internally valued at over $1 billion by Teachers' in its annual report.  In 2008 the Toronto Star reported that a valuation commissioned by the company concluded that the company was worth US$1.5 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2008/01/05/toronto_billionaire_eyes_leafs_empire.html|title=Toronto billionaire eyes Leafs empire|date=January 5, 2008|accessdate=January 11, 2014|work=Toronto Star|last=Westhead|first=Rick}}</ref>  On December 5, 2008 CTVglobemedia (the renamed Bell Globemedia) sold half of its 15.4% stake to Tanenbaum for $100 million, making Tanenbaum the second-largest stakeholder with 20.7%.<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=longtime/>  The transaction valued the company at $1.2 billion.  On August 20, 2009 Teachers' announced that it had agreed to purchase the remaining 7.7% stake in MLSE owned by CTVglobemedia, bumping their stake to 66%.<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=longtime/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2009/08/20/teachers_pension_plan_boosting_stake_in_mlse.html|title=Teachers' Pension Plan boosting stake in MLSE|date=August 20, 2009|accessdate=April 5, 2014|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref>\n\n===Bell and Rogers===\nIn December 2010 it was reported that Rogers Communications, owner of the Toronto Blue Jays, was in negotiations to purchase the Teachers' 66% stake in MLSE, with the asking price set at $1.3 billion,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/hockey/2010/12/01/rogers_in_13b_talks_to_buy_majority_stake_in_leafs_empire.html|title=Rogers in $1.3B talks to buy majority stake in Leafs empire|date=December 1, 2010|accessdate=April 5, 2014|last1=Cribb|first1=Robert|last2=Van Alphen|first2=Tony|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/rogers-leafs-sale/|title=Report: Rogers bids $1.3 billion for MLSE|date=December 1, 2010|accessdate=April 5, 2014|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]}}</ref> and in March 2011 Teachers' confirmed that their share in the company was up for sale.<ref name=snapup/><ref name=notforsale>{{cite web|url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2011/11/25/mlse-not-for-sale-teachers/|title=MLSE no longer for sale: Teachers' Pension Plan|first=Sean|last=Fitz-Gerald|date=November 25, 2011|accessdate=March 9, 2014|newspaper=[[National Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140310004314/http://sports.nationalpost.com/2011/11/25/mlse-not-for-sale-teachers/|archive-date=March 10, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Tanenbaum's right of first refusal on the shares gave him control over any sale by Teachers'.<ref name=longtime/><ref name=snapup/> In May 2011 Teachers' announced that they had reached an agreement to purchase TD Capital's 13.5% ownership share, giving them 79.5% of the company and leaving Tanenbaum as the only minority partner with 20.5%, simplifying a sale of their shares.<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=snapup>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/teachers-snaps-up-tds-maple-leaf-sports-stake/article591372/|title= Teachers snaps up TD's Maple Leaf Sports stake|date=May 10, 2011|accessdate=March 9, 2014|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|last=Perkins|first=Tara|location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011 Teachers' announced that they were taking the company off the market.<ref name=notforsale/> However, only a couple of weeks later, on December 9, 2011, Teachers' announced the sale of its entire stake in MLSE to a partnership between [[BCE Inc.]] and Rogers Communications, in a deal valued at [[Canadian dollar|$]]1.32 billion,<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=sportsempire>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/12/09/us-mapleleaf-rogers-bce-idUSTRE7B80VN20111209|title=Toronto sports empire sold to Rogers and BCE|first=Euan|last=Rocha|date=December 9, 2011|accessdate=March 16, 2014|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> giving the company an [[equity value]] of $1.66 billion and an [[enterprise value]] of $2 billion<ref name=value>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/rogers-bce-on-verge-of-deal-for-mlse/article4247367/|title= Rogers, BCE on verge of deal for MLSE|last1=Robertson|first1=Grant|last2=Perkins|first2=Tara|work=The Globe and Mail|date=December 8, 2011|accessdate=April 6, 2014|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlse.com/news/otppmlse_120911.aspx|title=OTPP announces sale of MLSE majority interest|date=September 9, 2011|accessdate=January 6, 2014|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106211058/http://www.mlse.com/news/otppmlse_120911.aspx|archive-date=January 6, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> due to the assumption of their share of MLSE's $372 million in debt and $66 million in leases.<ref name=\"crtc-mlse2\"/>  As part of the deal, Tanenbaum increased his stake in the company by 5%, valued at $109 million, to 25% to secure his approval.<ref name=sportsempire/><ref name=\"crtc-mlse2\"/><ref name=tsn-mlsepurchase>{{cite web|url=http://www2.tsn.ca/toronto/story/?id=382315|title=BCE and Rogers team up to buy 75 percent of MLSE|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]|date=December 10, 2011|accessdate=April 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otpp.com/news/article/-/article/21045|title=Teachers' completes $1.32-billion sale of MLSE|date=August 22, 2012|accessdate=December 27, 2013|publisher=[[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]]}}</ref> The deal required the approval of Canada's [[Competition Bureau]], the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission (with regards to MLSE's TV channels), as well as the NHL, the AHL, the NBA, and MLS (with regards to each of MLSE's main sports franchises).\n\nThe Competition Bureau announced in May 2012 that it would not challenge the transaction, but that it will \"actively review\" the situation in light of \"serious concerns\" expressed by various parties, reserving the right to take action at a later date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.competitionbureau.gc.ca/eic/site/cb-bc.nsf/eng/03464.html|title=Competition Bureau Statement on Bell and Rogers' Acquisition of Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment|author=[[Competition Bureau]]|date=May 2, 2012|accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref> The NHL Board of Governors approved the sale at a meeting in Las Vegas on June 19, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.tsn.ca/toronto/story/?id=398779|title=NHL board approves sale of MLSE to BCE-Rogers|date=June 20, 2012|accessdate=January 11, 2014|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref> The final approval, that of the CRTC, was granted on August 16, with the commission noting that it only had jurisdiction over the TV channels owned by MLSE (the transfer of ownership from MLSE to Bell, Rogers and Kilmer directly, it decided, posed no major concerns), and not the broadcast rights associated with MLSE's teams.<ref name=\"crtc-mlse2\"/><ref name=\"crtc-mlse\">{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2012/2012-443.htm|title=Broadcasting Decision CRTC 2012-443|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]|date=August 16, 2012|accessdate=August 25, 2012}}</ref> The transaction closed on August 22, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/bell-rogers-now-official-owners-of-mlse/article4493958/|title=Bell, Rogers now official owners of MLSE|work=The Globe and Mail|date=August 22, 2012|accessdate=August 25, 2012|location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\n{{chart top|width=100%|Ownership structure since August 2012 under Rogers and Bell}}\n{{chart/start|align=center|}}\n{{chart| | | | |MLSE | | | | |MLSE=MLSE<br/>100%}}\n{{chart| | | |,|-|^|-|-|-|.| }}\n{{chart| | | ROGBELL | | | | KILMER | ROGBELL=Rogers/Bell holding company<br/>75%|KILMER=Kilmer Sports<br/>25%}}\n{{chart| |,|-|^|-|.| | | |!| }}\n{{chart| ROGERS | | BELL | | LT | ROGERS=Rogers Communications<br/>50%|BELL=Bell holding company<br/>50%|LT=Larry Tanenbaum<br/>100%}}\n{{chart| | | |,|-|^|-|.| | | }}\n{{chart| | | BCE | | BMT | | | BCE=BCE Inc.<br/>74.67%|BMT=BCE Master Trust Fund<br/>25.33%}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\nAs part of the sale, two [[numbered companies]] were created to jointly hold stock.  Following the restructuring, the ownership hierarchy of MLSE was:<ref name=\"crtc-mlse\" />\n* 8047286 Canada Inc. (Rogers/Bell [[joint venture|joint]] holding company) \u2013 75%\n** [[Rogers Communications]] \u2013 50% (net ownership 37.5%)\n** 7680147 Canada Inc. (Bell holding company) \u2013 50%\n*** [[BCE Inc.]] \u2013 74.67% (net ownership 28%)\n*** BCE Master Trust Fund (investment fund of Bell's pension plan) \u2013 25.33% (net ownership 9.5%)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/892971/bell-acquires-ownership-position-in-maple-leaf-sports-and-entertainment-mlse|title=Bell acquires ownership position in Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment - MLSE|author=[[BCE Inc.]]|date=December 9, 2011|accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n* Kilmer Sports (holding company of [[Larry Tanenbaum]]) \u2013 25%\n\nThis ownership structure ensures that, at the shareholder level, Rogers and Bell vote their overall 75% interest in the company together and thus decisions on the management of the company must be made by consensus of the two. (If Rogers and Bell owned their interests directly, either Rogers or Bell could be overruled by its competitor in combination with Tanenbaum.) As such, Rogers and Bell have agreed that their previously four of six (now six of eight) directors on the MLSE board will always vote together, and thus that any disagreements between the two companies will be settled privately without the involvement of Tanenbaum.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/leafs-beat/mlse-board-expected-to-undergo-major-change-after-sale-is-finalized/article4426208/|title=MLSE board expected to undergo major change after sale is finalized|first=David|last=Shoalts|work=The Globe and Mail|date=July 18, 2012|accessdate=March 6, 2013|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref name=board />  Bell has indicated that the involvement of Bell's pension fund is, at least in part, intended to ensure Bell can retain its existing 18% interest in the Montreal Canadiens, as NHL rules prevent any shareholder that owns more than 30% of a team from holding an ownership position in any other team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/bell-to-keep-canadiens-stake-1.997652|title=Bell to keep Canadiens stake|author=[[The Canadian Press]]|work=[[CBC.ca]]|date=December 9, 2011|accessdate=December 10, 2011}}</ref> As a result of Bell and Rogers having co-ownership in MLSE, the regional broadcasts of Maple Leafs and Toronto FC games are split between Bell's TSN and Rogers' Sportsnet; the national rights to the Raptors and the NBA overall are also split between TSN and Sportsnet.\n\nIn 2015 MLSE initiated a corporate restructuring, with the plan to transfer most of its assets to another holding company, named \"Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Partnership\" (MLSEP), which would be wholly owned, directly and indirectly, by MLSE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2015/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-83489.pdf|title=Consent to Assignment of Agreements with Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Ltd (\"MLSEL\")|date=September 2, 2015|accessdate=October 1, 2015|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref>\n\n==Assets==\n\n===Sports teams===\n* [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] ([[National Hockey League]]) \u2013 Valued at US$1.50 billion in 2019, 2nd in the NHL<ref name=forbestml>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/teams/toronto-maple-leafs/|title=Toronto Maple Leafs|work=Forbes|publisher=Forbes Media LLC.|year=2017|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n** [[Toronto Marlies]] ([[American Hockey League]])\n* [[Toronto Raptors]]  ([[National Basketball Association]]) \u2013 Valued at US$2.1 billion in 2020, 10th in the NBA<ref name=forbestr>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/teams/toronto-raptors/|title=Toronto Raptors|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n** [[Raptors 905]] ([[NBA G League]])\n** Raptors Uprising GC ([[NBA 2K League]])\n* [[Toronto FC]] ([[Major League Soccer]]) \u2013 Valued at US$395 million in 2019, 5th in MLS<ref name=forbesmls>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrissmith/2019/11/04/major-league-soccers-most-valuable-teams-2019-atlanta-stays-on-top-as-expansion-fees-sale-prices-surge/#72d3b3b051b5|title=Major League Soccer\u2019s Most Valuable Teams 2019: Atlanta Stays On Top As Expansion Fees, Sale Prices Surge|work=[[Forbes]]|date=November 4, 2019|accessdate=November 6, 2019|last=Smith|first=Chris}}</ref>\n** [[Toronto FC II]] ([[USL League One]])\n** [[Toronto FC III]] ([[U.S. Soccer Development Academy]])\n** Toronto FC eSports ([[eMLS Cup]])\n* [[Toronto Argonauts]] ([[Canadian Football League]])\n\n{{side box|metadate=no|position=left|above='''Valuations of MLSE franchises since 1991<br>(in US dollars)'''|abovestyle=text-align:center\n|text=\n{{Graph:Chart\n| width = 700\n| height = 350\n| xAxisTitle = Year valuation reported<!--Note that the NBA reporting date was switched from December->January and this seems to have been applied retroactively by Forbes-->\n| x = 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1995, 1996, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019, 2020\n| yAxisTitle = Valuation (USD)\n| yAxisFormat = $,.10\n| colors = blue, red, green\n| y1 = 45000000, 54000000, 63000000, 77000000, 90000000, 96000000, 105000000, 119000000, 151000000, 203000000, 216000000, 241000000, 263000000, 280000000, ,332000000, 413000000, 448000000, 470000000, 505000000, 521000000, 1000000000, 1150000000, 1300000000, 1150000000, 1100000000, 1400000000, 1450000000, 1500000000\n| y2 = {{repeat|6| ,}} 138000000, ,121000000, 138000000, 148000000, 172000000, 217000000, 249000000, 297000000, 278000000, 315000000, 373000000, 400000000, 386000000, 399000000, 382000000, 405000000, 520000000, 920000000, 980000000, 1125000000, 1400000000, 1675000000, 2100000000\n| y3 = {{repeat|17| ,}} 44000000 {{repeat|5| ,}} 121000000, , 175000000, 245000000, 280000000, 290000000, 395000000\n| showSymbols = \n}}\n|below=\n1991\u20131997: [[Financial World]]<ref>Data from the following annual reports:\n* {{Cite journal|title=Secrets of the front office: What America's pro teams are worth|date=July 9, 1991|last1=Baldo|first1=Anthony|last2=Biesada|first2=Alexandra|last3=Hackney|first3=Holt|last4=Ozanian|first4=Michael K|last5=Taub|first5=Stephen|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=28}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=Big leagues, bad business|date=July 7, 1992|last1=Ozanian|first1=Michael K|last2=Taub|first2=Stephen|last3=Morris|first3=Kathleen|last4=Fink|first4=Ronald|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=34}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=Foul ball|date=May 25, 1993|last1=Ozanian|first1=Michael K|last2=Taub|first2=Stephen|last3=Fink|first3=Ronald|last4=Kimelman|first4=John|last5=Reingold|first5=Jennifer|last6=Starr|first6=Jason|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=50}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=The $11 billion pastime: Why sports franchise values are soaring even as team profits fall|date=May 10, 1994|last1=Ozanian|first1=Michael K|last2=Fink|first2=Ronald|last3=Kimelman|first3=John|last4=Reingold|first4=Jennifer|last5=Osterland|first5=Andrew|last6=Starr|first6=Jason|last7=Grabarek|first7=Brooke|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=50}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=Suite deals: Why new stadiums are shaking up the pecking order of sports franchises|date=May 9, 1995|last1=Ozanian|first1=Michael K|last2=Atre|first2=Tushar|last3=Fink|first3=Ronald|last4=Reingold|first4=Jennifer|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=42}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=The high-stakes game of team ownership|date=May 20, 1996|last1=Atre|first1=Tushar|last2=Auns|first2=Kristine|last3=Badenhausen|first3=Kurt|last4=McAuliffe|first4=Kevin|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=49}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=More than a game: An in-depth look at the raging bull market in sports franchises|date=June 17, 1997|last1=Badenhausen|first1=Kurt|last2=Nikolov|first2=Christopher|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=40}}</ref>{{spaces|2|em}}1998\u2013present: [[Forbes]]\n\n{{legend inline|blue|Maple Leafs<ref name=forbestml/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/31/biz_07nhl_Toronto-Maple-Leafs_312012.html|title=#1 Toronto Maple Leafs|date=November 8, 2007|accessdate=May 8, 2014|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>}}{{spaces|2|em}}{{legend inline|red|Raptors<ref name=forbestr/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/32/biz_07nba_Toronto-Raptors_321933.html|title=#14 Toronto Raptors|date=December 6, 2007|accessdate=May 8, 2014|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>}}{{spaces|2|em}}{{legend inline|green|TFC<ref name=forbesmls/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrissmith/2016/09/07/major-league-soccers-most-valuable-teams-2016-new-york-orlando-thrive-in-first-seasons/#79dbd7a2266a|title=Major League Soccer's Most Valuable Teams 2016: New York, Orlando Thrive In First Seasons|work=[[Forbes]]|date=September 7, 2016|accessdate=September 7, 2016|last=Smith|first=Chris}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrissmith/2015/08/19/major-league-soccers-most-valuable-teams-2015-2/|title=Major League Soccer's Most Valuable Teams 2015|work=[[Forbes]]|date=August 19, 2015|accessdate=August 19, 2015|last=Smith|first=Chris}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrissmith/2013/11/20/major-league-soccers-most-valuable-teams/|title=Major League Soccer's Most Valuable Teams|work=[[Forbes]]|date=November 20, 2013|accessdate=January 22, 2014|last=Smith|first=Chris}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/09/09/mls-soccer-beckham-biz-sports-cz_kb_0909mlsvalues.html|title=Major League Soccer's Most Valuable Teams|date=September 9, 2008|last1=Schwartz|first1=Peter|last2=Badenhausen|first2=Kurt|accessdate=May 8, 2014|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>}}\n}}\n\nNote that the valuations are estimates done by ''[[Forbes]]'', and are not based on numbers provided by MLSE. MLSE has refuted past valuations made by ''Forbes''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2012/11/29/nhl_lockout_maple_leafs_worth_a_billion_says_forbes.html|title=NHL lockout: Maple Leafs worth a billion says Forbes|last=McGran|first=Kevin|date=November 29, 2012|accessdate=March 3, 2020|work=Toronto Star|publisher=Torstar Corporation}}</ref>\n\n===Facilities and properties===\n\n====Owns====\n* [[Scotiabank Arena]] \u2013 a multi-purpose [[indoor arena]] in [[downtown Toronto]] home to the Maple Leafs and Raptors which was constructed at a cost of $265 million\n* [[OVO Athletic Centre]] \u2013 practice facility for the Raptors\n* [[Maple Leaf Square]] (37.5%<ref name=notforsale/>) \u2013 a real estate development adjacent to the Scotiabank Arena, developed in partnership with fellow OTPP subsidiary [[Cadillac Fairview]], which includes, among other tenants, the following businesses operated by MLSE:\n** Real Sports Bar & Grill \u2013 a sports-themed restaurant\n** Real Sports Apparel \u2013 a sports clothing store\n** e11even \u2013 an upscale restaurant on the corner of Bremner and York streets<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/life/food_wine/2011/01/28/e11even_slams_diners_into_boards.html | location=Toronto | work=The Star | first=Amy | last=Pataki | title=E11even Slams Diners Into Boards | date=January 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Invested in and operates (owned by the City of Toronto)====\n* [[BMO Field]] \u2013 home of Toronto FC, the Argonauts and [[Canada men's national soccer team]] ([[CONCACAF]])\n* [[Coca-Cola Coliseum]] \u2013 home of the Marlies\n\n====Invested in====\n* [[Ford Performance Centre]] \u2013 practice facility for the Maple Leafs and Marlies\n* [[BMO Training Ground]] \u2013 practice facility for Toronto FC, and home of Toronto FC II and the TFC Academy\n* [[Lamport Stadium]] \u2013 former home of Toronto FC II and the TFC Academy; practice facility for the Argonauts.\n\n===Television channels===\n* [[Leafs Nation Network]] \u2013 a specialty channel devoted to the Maple Leafs and Marlies (valued at $19 million on behalf of the CRTC in 2012<ref name=\"crtc-mlse2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2012/2012-443.htm|title=Broadcasting Decision CRTC 2012-443|date=August 16, 2012|accessdate=September 3, 2015|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]}}</ref>)\n* [[NBA TV Canada]] \u2013 a localized version of [[NBA TV]], a US basketball channel, which also devotes part of its schedule to specific coverage of the Raptors (valued at $21 million on behalf of the CRTC in 2012<ref name=\"crtc-mlse2\"/>)\n\n==Staff==\n{|style=\"float: right\"\n|[[File:Edward RogersIII.jpg|thumb|Edward Rogers III, Deputy Chairman of Rogers Communications and member of the board of directors of MLSE]]\n|\n|[[File:Shanahan.png|thumb|Brendan Shanahan, President and Alternate Governor, Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n|}\n\n===Board of directors===\n* [[Larry Tanenbaum]] \u2013 Kilmer Sports (non-executive chairman of the board)<ref name=board>{{cite web|url=http://mlse.com/our-company/board-of-directors/|title=Board of Directors|accessdate=March 9, 2014|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment}}</ref>\n* [[George A. Cope]] \u2013 BCE and [[Bell Canada]]<ref name=board/>\n* [[Dale Lastman]] \u2013 [[Goodmans LLP]]<ref name=board/>\n* Guy Laurence \u2013 [[Rogers Communications]]<ref name=board/>\n* [[Edward Rogers III]] \u2013 Rogers Communications<ref name=board/>\n* Anthony Staffieri \u2013 Rogers Communications<ref name=board/>\n* Bernard Le Duc \u2013 Bell Canada<ref name=board/>\n* Siim Vanaselja \u2013 Bell Canada<ref name=board/>\n\n===Executive team===\n* [[Michael Friisdahl]] \u2013 president and CEO<ref name=Friisdahl>{{cite web|url=http://mlse.com/news/mlse-names-michael-friisdahl-president-ceo/|title=MLSE NAMES MICHAEL FRIISDAHL PRESIDENT & CEO|date=October 29, 2015|accessdate=October 29, 2015|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment}}</ref>\n* [[Brendan Shanahan]] \u2013 president and alternate governor, Toronto Maple Leafs<ref name=leaders>{{cite web|url=http://mlse.com/our-company/leaders-at-mlse/|title=Leaders at MLSE|accessdate=March 30, 2014|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment}}</ref>\n* [[Masai Ujiri]] \u2013 president, Toronto Raptors<ref name=leaders/>\n* Bill Manning \u2013 president, Toronto FC and Toronto Argonauts<ref name=leaders/><ref name=ArgosApprove/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Toronto Maple Leafs}}\n{{Toronto Raptors}}\n{{Toronto FC}}\n{{Toronto Argonauts}}\n{{Toronto Marlies}}\n{{NHLOwners}}\n{{NBAOwners}}\n{{Toronto Argonauts owner navbox}}\n{{Rogers Communications}}\n{{Bell Canada}}\n}}\n\n{{portalbar|Canada|Companies|Ontario}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment}}\n[[Category:Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment| ]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Sports management companies]]\n[[Category:Television broadcasting companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer owners]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association owners]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League owners]]\n[[Category:Toronto Argonauts owners]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 1931]]\n[[Category:1931 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Bell Canada]]\n[[Category:Rogers Communications]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian sports and real estate company}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Ltd.\n| former_name = Maple Leaf Gardens Ltd. (1931\u20131998)\n| logo = MLSE logo 2014.png\n| image = Air Canada Centre from CN Tower.jpg\n| image_caption = A bird's-eye-view of MLSE headquarters in the tower next to Scotiabank Arena from the CN Tower\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1931}} in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| founder = [[Conn Smythe]]\n| location = [[Scotiabank Arena]], 50 [[Bay Street]]\n| location_city = Toronto, Ontario\n| location_country = Canada\n| area_served = [[Greater Toronto Area]]\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap|[[Larry Tanenbaum]] (chairman)|[[Michael Friisdahl]] (president & CEO)}}\n| industry = {{Unbulleted list|[[Professional sports]]|[[Property management]]}}\n| equity = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| num_employees = \n| owner = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap|[[Rogers Communications]] (37.5%)|BCE (37.5%)|&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;[[BCE Inc.]] (28%)|&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;BCE Master Trust Fund (9.5%)|[[Larry Tanenbaum|Kilmer Sports]] (25%)}}\n| subsid = <!--NOTE: Before unilaterally changing this to hlist, please consult the subsidiary parameter at this template's page which states clearly: \"If there is more than one entry, use {{Unbulleted list}} to format the entries.\"--> {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap|[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]|[[Toronto Raptors]]|[[Toronto FC]]|[[Toronto Argonauts]]|[[Toronto Marlies]]|[[Raptors 905]]|[[Toronto FC II]]|[[Scotiabank Arena]]|[[OVO Athletic Centre]]|[[Maple Leaf Square]] (37.5%)}}\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.mlse.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Ltd.''' ('''MLSE''') is a [[professional sports]] and [[commercial real estate]] company based in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. With assets that include franchises in four of the six [[major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada]], it is the largest sports and entertainment company in Canada, and one of the largest in [[North America]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/rogers-bell-buy-control-of-mlse-1.997655|title=Rogers, Bell buy control of MLSE|date=2011-12-09|accessdate=2020-04-04|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]}}</ref>\n\nThe primary holdings of the company are its major sports franchises, the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] of the [[National Hockey League]], [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]], [[Toronto Argonauts]] of the [[Canadian Football League]], and [[Toronto FC]] of [[Major League Soccer]], as well as their minor league [[farm team]]s, the [[Toronto Marlies]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL), [[Raptors 905]] of the [[NBA G League]] and [[Toronto FC II]] of the [[USL League One]], respectively.\n\nIn addition, it owns [[Scotiabank Arena]] (originally named Air Canada Centre), the home arena of the Maple Leafs and Raptors, and the [[OVO Athletic Centre]] (originally named BioSteel Centre), the practice facility for the Raptors. MLSE also manages or has invested in several other sports facilities including [[BMO Field]], home of Toronto FC and the Toronto Argonauts; [[Coca-Cola Coliseum]], home of the Marlies; [[Ford Performance Centre]], the practice facility of the Maple Leafs and Marlies; [[BMO Training Ground]] practice facility for Toronto FC and home of Toronto FC II and the [[TFC Academy]]; and [[Lamport Stadium]], practice facility for the Argonauts.\n\nMLSE was founded by [[Conn Smythe]] in 1931 as '''Maple Leaf Gardens Limited (MLGL)''' to act as a [[holding company]] for the Maple Leafs and their planned new arena [[Maple Leaf Gardens]], from which the company got its name. Smythe transferred his ownership of the Leafs to the company in exchange for shares in MLGL and sold shares in the holding company to the public to help fund construction of the arena. While initially primarily a hockey company, with ownership stakes in a number of [[professional ice hockey|minor]] and [[junior hockey]] clubs including the [[Toronto Marlboros]] of the [[Ontario Hockey Association]], the company later branched out to own the [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] of the CFL from the late 1970s to late 1980s, before merging with the Raptors, who were constructing the Air Canada Centre at the time, and adopting their current name in 1998. The company launched Toronto FC in 2007. Most recently, the company completed its purchase of the Argonauts in January 2018.<ref name=ArgosApprove>{{citeweb|url=https://www.argonauts.ca/2018/01/19/mlse-acquisition-toronto-argonauts-approved-cfl-board-governors/|title=MLSE ACQUISITION OF TORONTO ARGONAUTS APPROVED BY CFL BOARD OF GOVERNORS|date=January 19, 2018|accessdate=January 19, 2018|publisher=[[Toronto Argonauts]]}}</ref>\n\nOver most of its 80 plus years of existence MLSE was a [[public company]]. Following the death of majority owner [[Harold Ballard]] in 1990, [[Steve Stavro]] led a controversial bid to buy the company and take it [[Privately held company|private]]. In 2012, the [[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]] sold their 79.53% share of the company for {{CAD|1.32}} billion to a joint venture between [[Rogers Communications]] and [[BCE Inc.]], two of Canada's largest media companies, giving the company an equity value of {{CAD|1.66}} billion and an enterprise value of {{CAD|2}} billion.\n\n==Corporate history==\n{{see also|History of the Toronto Maple Leafs}}\n\n===Founding===\n[[File:Maple Leaf Gardens' roof under construction, 1931 (public domain).png|thumb|left|300px|Maple Leaf Gardens roof under construction, pictured in 1931]]\nThe corporation's roots can be traced back to 1927, when [[Conn Smythe]] organized a group of investors to purchase Toronto's premier hockey franchise, the [[Toronto St. Patricks]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), which had won [[Stanley Cup]] championships in [[1917\u201318 NHL season|1918]] (as the [[Toronto Arenas]]) and [[1921\u201322 NHL season|1922]], from a group headed by [[Charles Querrie]]. The club was playing poorly and minority partner [[Jack Bickell]] contacted Smythe about becoming coach of the team.  However, Smythe told Bickell that he was more interested in buying a stake in the team. Not long after, with the team in trouble financially due to majority owner Querrie having lost a lawsuit to former [[Toronto Blueshirts]] owner [[Eddie Livingstone]] over ownership of the franchise, Querrie put the St. Pats up for sale and agreed in principle to sell them to [[C. C. Pyle]] for $200,000, who planned to move the team to [[Philadelphia]].<ref name=thoughages>{{cite web|url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2010/12/01/maple-leafs-owners-through-the-ages/|title=Maple Leafs' owners through the ages|last=Sandler|first=Jeremy|newspaper=[[National Post]]|date=December 1, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140320041448/http://sports.nationalpost.com/2010/12/01/maple-leafs-owners-through-the-ages/|archivedate=March 20, 2014}}</ref><ref name=ml1920>{{cite web|title=Maple Leafs History: 1920s |publisher=NHL.com |url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=42182|accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref>{{sfn|Shea|Wilson|2016|p=30\u201331}} After Bickell contacted Smythe to inform him of the sale, Smythe persuaded Querrie that civic pride was more important than money and put together a syndicate that bought the St. Pats. Smythe himself invested $10,000 of his own money and his group contributed $75,000 up front and a further $75,000 due 30 days later, with Bickell retaining his $40,000 share in the team.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=smythe>{{cite web|url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2011/10/21/excerpt-the-lives-of-conn-smythe/|title=The Lives of Conn Smythe: From the Battlefield to Maple Leaf Gardens: A Hockey Icon's Story|year=2011|accessdate=January 11, 2014|work=[[National Post]]|first=Kelly|last=McParland|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140112052642/http://sports.nationalpost.com/2011/10/21/excerpt-the-lives-of-conn-smythe/|archivedate=January 12, 2014}}</ref>  The deal was finalized on Valentine's Day,<ref name=smythe/> and the new owners quickly renamed the team the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]], after the [[maple leaf|national symbol]] of Canada.{{sfn|Shea|Wilson|2016|p=33}} Smythe attributed his choice of a maple Leaf for the logo to his experiences as a Canadian Army officer and prisoner of war during [[World War I]].<ref name=smytheyoung>{{cite book |last1=Smythe |first1=Conn |author1link=Conn Smythe|last2=Young |first2=Scott |author2link=Scott Young (writer)|title=Conn Smythe: If you can't beat 'em in the alley |year=1981 |publisher=McClelland and Stewart |location=Toronto, Ontario |isbn=0-7710-9078-1}}</ref>{{rp|85\u201386}}  Later that year, Smythe bought the [[junior hockey]] [[Toronto Marlboros]] of the [[Ontario Hockey Association]] to serve as a developmental team for Maple Leafs.<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.marlies.ca/history/marlies.asp |title=Marlies history |accessdate=February 17, 2014 |publisher=Toronto Marlies |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208045746/http://www.marlies.ca/history/marlies.asp |archivedate=December 8, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=timeline>{{cite web|url=http://www.marlies.ca/history/timeline.asp |title=Marlies timeline |accessdate=February 17, 2014 |publisher=Toronto Marlies |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208045751/http://www.marlies.ca/history/timeline.asp |archivedate=December 8, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tor chi 94.jpg|thumb|The Toronto Maple Leafs, the primary asset of MLGL for many years, play a home game at the Gardens in 1994]]\n\nIn 1929 Smythe decided, in the midst of the [[Great Depression]], that the Maple Leafs needed a new arena. The [[Arena Gardens]], their then home which they shared with the Marlboros,<ref name=history/> had been built in 1912 and lacked modern amenities.{{sfn|Shea|Wilson|2016|p=45}}  It seated just 8,000, which the Maple Leafs were regularly filling. After considering various locations, the site at the corner of Carlton and Church was purchased from [[Eaton's|The T. Eaton Co. Ltd.]] for $350,000,<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|104}} a price said to be $150,000 below market value. A new 12,473 seat (14,550 including standing room) arena, [[Maple Leaf Gardens]] (MLG), was designed by the architectural firm of [[Ross and Macdonald]]. To finance construction, Smythe got backing from [[Sun Life]] for half of the expected $1 million cost.<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|103}} He then formed '''Maple Leaf Gardens Limited''' (MLGL) as a management company that would own both the hockey team and the arena.<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|102}} A public offering of shares in MLGL was made at $10 each (${{formatprice|{{Inflation|CA|10|1931}}}} in {{Inflation-year|CA}} dollars),{{inflation-fn|CA}} with a free common share for each five preferred shares purchased.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maple Leaf Gardens, Limited - Prospectus|newspaper=The Globe|date=March 5, 1931}}</ref> Ownership of the hockey team was transferred to MLGL in return for shares. To fund construction of the building, workers were paid 20% of their salary in MLG stock.<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|104\u2013106}}<ref name=bigmoney>{{cite news|title=Big money always part of Gardens story|first=Paul|last=Patton|newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=April 13, 1989}}</ref> Construction started on June 1, 1931,<ref name=\"startwork\">{{cite news |title=New Arena Work to Start on Saturday at Midnight|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=May 30, 1931}}</ref> and MLG was opened five months and two weeks later, on November 12, 1931, at a cost of $1.5 million<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idCATRE5B03FL20091201|title=Toronto's Maple Leaf Gardens gets C$60 million facelift|date=December 1, 2009|accessdate=January 26, 2014|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Maple Leaf Gardens 1931 - Air Canada Centre 1999: History vs. high tech: No design marvel, Air Canada Centre struggles to graft Gardens' history into a high-tech package that bucks the retro trend|date=February 13, 1999|last=Beamish|first=Mike|work=[[Vancouver Sun]]}}</ref> (${{formatprice|{{Inflation|CA|1500000|1931}}}} in {{Inflation-year|CA}} dollars).{{inflation-fn|CA}} The Marlboros also moved to the new arena.<ref name=history/>  Bickell was named the first president of MLG.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.hhof.com/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/LegendsMember.jsp?mem=b197801&type=Builder&page=bio&list=ByName|title=Builders - J. P. Bickell - Biography|publisher=[[Hockey Hall of Fame]]}}</ref>\n\nTo help fill dates at the new arena, Smythe acquired an expansion franchise in the professional [[International Lacrosse League]] on behalf of MLGL for the 1932 season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Maple Leaf Gardens granted franchise|date=December 10, 1931|newspaper=The Globe}}</ref><ref name=testolympic/> which was also given the name the [[Toronto Maple Leafs (ILL)|Toronto Maple Leafs]].<ref name=testolympic>{{cite news|title=On The Highways of Sport: Local Seniors Will Test Olympic Team Tonight|date=January 29, 1932|last=Rodden|first=M.J.|newspaper=The Globe}}</ref><ref name=twoteams/> A team named the [[Toronto Tecumsehs (ILL)|Toronto Maple Leafs]] had competed in the first season of the ILL at the Arena Gardens,<ref name=twoteams>{{cite news|title=Two Toronto teams in lacrosse loop|date=January 29, 1932|newspaper=The Globe}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=On the highway of sports: Maroons and Leafs in lacrosse opener tonight|date=June 29, 1931|last=Rodden|first=M.J.|newspaper=The Globe}}</ref> but was renamed the Tecumsehs with the arrival of Smythe's team.<ref name=\"testolympic\"/><ref name=twoteams/> Both teams played at MLG.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maple Leafs score decisive victory|date=June 20, 1932|first=jack|last=Murray|newspaper=The Globe}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=On The Highways of Sport: Tecumsehs' Victory Creates All-Round Tie|date=May 9, 1932|last=Rodden|first=M.J.|newspaper=The Globe}}</ref> Smythe pulled out following the season due to financial losses,<ref>{{cite news|title=On The Highways of Sport: Mustangs on Rampage at U. of T.'s Expense|date=October 31, 1932|last=Rodden|first=M.J.|newspaper=[[The Globe (Toronto newspaper)|The Globe]]}}</ref> and the league did not play the following year.\n\n===Minor hockey expansion===\nThe company has owned numerous [[minor league]] hockey teams over the years, which have served as developmental [[farm team]]s for the Maple Leafs. A group backed by Smythe and [[Frank Selke]] of the [[Montreal Canadiens]] was awarded an [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) franchise for [[Rochester, New York]] in July 1956, after a local group could not come up with the US$150,000 in capital required by the league.<ref name=eager>{{cite news|last=Marcotte |first=Bob |title=Eager fans embraced arrival of the Rochester Amerks |url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/article/20110307/NEWS0204/103070318/Eager-fans-embraced-arrival-Rochester-Amerks |newspaper=Democrat and Chronicle |date=March 7, 2011 |agency=Gannett Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5x795iwiX?url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/article/20110307/NEWS0204/103070318/Eager-fans-embraced-arrival-Rochester-Amerks |archivedate=March 11, 2011 |location=Rochester, New York |pages=1B,4B |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=makesit>{{cite news|title=Rochester makes it - Gains AHL franchise|date=July 3, 1956|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]}}</ref><ref name=coffers>{{cite news|title=Sale of Rochester hockey team pads Maple Leaf coffers|date=July 7, 1966|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]|first=Neil|last=MacCarl}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Give Rochester conditional OK on AHL franchise|date=June 20, 1956|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> The Leafs and Canadiens would each own 27.5% of the team, with the balance sold to Rochester interests.<ref name=eager /><ref>{{cite news|title=Maple Leafs Seek Farm Club in AHL|date=March 18, 1959|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>  The team was named the [[Rochester Americans]].  The Amerks were a joint affiliate of both the Canadiens and the Maple Leafs,<ref name=makesit/> though the club was operated by the Canadiens.<ref name=control>{{cite news|title=Leafs Purchase Control Of AHL Squad From Habs|date=June 15, 1959|pages=22|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> In the summer of 1959 the Maple Leafs bought out the Canadiens' ownership share of the club, giving them a 55% controlling interest, due to concerns that with Montreal operating the club they were giving their prospects priority over those of the Leafs.<ref name=coffers/><ref name=control/>  They purchased most of the remaining 45% in 1963,<ref name=coffers/><ref>{{cite news|title=Rumors Have Pilous Going to Rochester|date=June 5, 1963|pages=15|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=19players>{{cite news|title=19 players go: AHL franchise at Rochester sold by Leafs|date=July 7, 1966|last=Rimstead|first=Paul|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> boosting their ownership share to 98% by November 1964.<ref name=exceeds>{{cite news|title=Nothing Exceeds Like Success|date=November 13, 1964|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> In July 1966 the Maple Leafs sold the team to a group which included their then General Manager [[Punch Imlach]] for a reported $400,000.<ref name=coffers/><ref name=19players/><ref name=sixtyseven>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gNfXe3VrVHMC&pg=PA31|title='67: The Maple Leafs, Their Sensational Victory, and the End of an Empire|last1=Cox|first1=Damien|author1link=Damien Cox|last2=Stellick|first2=Gord|author2link=Gord Stellick|year=2009|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]]|page=31|isbn=9780470739273}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Saturday sale on shorts|date=July 9, 1966|last=Beddoes|first=Dick|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Corporate reports: Maple Leaf Gardens notes drop in profit|date=November 7, 1966|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|page=25}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pride at Maple Leaf Gardens.jpg|thumb|Maple Leaf Gardens, the former home of the Toronto Maple Leafs, after which MLGL was named]]\n\nIn June 1963 the [[Spokane Comets]] [[Western Hockey League (1952\u201374)|Western Hockey League]] franchise was purchased by a group led by the Maple Leafs, who relocated them to become the [[Denver Invaders]] and act as the Leaf's farm team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pilous Offered Job As Boss at Denver, Leafs New Farm Club|date=June 6, 1963|newspaper=The Globe and Mail }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs buy coast club|date=June 5, 1963|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19630605&id=-LVWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=F-kDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6929,1504554|title=Spokane's Western Hockey Franchise Moves to Denver; Toronto Maple Leafs Purchase Mel Smith's Comet Stock|last=Missildine|first=Harry|date=June 5, 1963|newspaper=[[The Spokesman-Review]]}}</ref><ref name=PCWHL>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UpldzQdhpr8C&pg=PA130|title=Ice Warriors: The Pacific Coast/Western Hockey League 1948\u20131974|last=Stott|first=Jon C|year=2008|publisher=Heritage House Publishing|isbn=9781927051047}}</ref> Though the league did not acknowledge that the Maple Leafs had an ownership stake in the team,<ref name=PCWHL/><ref>{{cite news|title=WHL Approves Leafs' Farm In Denver|date=June 21, 1963|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> they held a majority position with the Denver partners only owning roughly 36%.<ref name=pulledout>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1310&dat=19640626&id=xv1VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=--IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4977,5599035|title=Invaders pulled out of Denver by Smythe|date=June 26, 1964|newspaper=[[The Register-Guard]]}}</ref><ref name=retreaters/><ref name=loses>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19640626&id=ojlWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HukDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1590,3324630|title=Denver loses club|date=June 26, 1964|newspaper=[[The Spokesman-Review]]}}</ref> Following reported losses of $150,000 in their first season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs' Denver loses estimated at $150,000|date=June 30, 1964|first=Milt|last=Dunnell|authorlink=Milt Dunnell|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]}}</ref> Smythe announced that the team would be relocated after the team failed to reach a 2,000 season ticket target by a league-imposed deadline.<ref name=PCWHL/><ref name=pulledout/><ref name=retreaters>{{cite news|title=Denver's Invaders Become Retreaters|date=June 26, 1964|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=loses/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/1029529/|title=Invader Hockey club to quit Denver|date=June 26, 1964|newspaper=[[Redlands Daily Facts]]}}</ref> The team became the [[Victoria Maple Leafs]] for the following season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sports Briefs: Palmer Will Appear In Canadian Open|date=July 18, 1964|pages=21|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> In June 1967 MLGL sold the team for $500,000 to a group from Phoenix,<ref name=sixtyseven/><ref name=PCWHL/><ref>{{cite news|title=Phoenix club charges Leafs broke contract|date=May 22, 1968|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey lawsuits out of style|date=September 8, 1967|first=Dick|last=Beddoes|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> which relocated it to become the [[Phoenix Roadrunners (WHL)|Phoenix Roadrunners]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19670517&id=I0MjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HbkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2112,4282228|title=Victoria team to Phoenix|date=May 17, 1967|newspaper=[[Montreal Gazette]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Minor pro leagues may soon merge|date=June 6, 1967|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canada.com/story_print.html?id=ac72c73c-cd4f-4650-a0b6-f19c3af4fba7&sponsor=|title=At home in the desert|date=November 29, 2005|accessdate=February 16, 2014|newspaper=[[Times Colonist]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127235107/http://www.canada.com/story_print.html?id=ac72c73c-cd4f-4650-a0b6-f19c3af4fba7&sponsor=|archivedate=January 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964 MLGL the [[Tulsa Oilers (1964\u201384)|Tulsa Oilers]] of the [[Central Professional Hockey League]] were launched. The team was owned and operated by MLGL as a developmental club for the Maple Leafs.<ref name=exceeds/> In the spring of 1973 it was announced that the Oilers would relocate to become the [[Oklahoma City Blazers (1965\u201377)|Oklahoma City Blazers]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs switch Tulsa team in CHL to Oklahoma City|date=April 20, 1973|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs shift farm|date=April 21, 1973|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref>  Prior to the 1976\u201377 season the Maple Leafs decided to share an affiliate with the [[Chicago Blackhawks|Chicago Black Hawks]] in an attempt to reduce costs,<ref>{{cite news|title=NHL clubs will cut 100 players in effort to combat rising costs|date=January 31, 1976|first=Don|last=Ramsay|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|pages=43}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Some NHL rules aren't enforced at playoff time|date=April 27, 1976|first=Jim|last=Proudfoot|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref> and pulled out of the Blazers.<!--When did they pull out?  Did they fold or sell the franchise?-->  In 1978 the [[New Brunswick Hawks]] of the AHL were established,<ref name=\"Sports roundup\">{{cite news|title=Sports roundup|date=June 24, 1978|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> and were jointly operated by the Chicago Black Hawks and the Toronto Maple Leafs as their farm team.<ref name=\"Sports roundup\"/><ref name=newfarm/><ref name=mayget/><ref name=leave/><ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey notebook Dull Sabres have pundits speculating|date=February 9, 1982|work=The Globe and Mail|last=Houston|first=William}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sports roundup|date=July 8, 1978|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs, Hawks to Moncton|date=June 20, 1978|publisher=Toronto Star}}</ref>  MLGL and the Black Hawks each owned half of the franchise.<ref name=price>{{cite news|title='Everything has price,' Ballard says; it's $50 million for Leafs. Gardens|date=March 31, 1982|last=Houston|first=William|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=\"Globe and Mail\">{{cite news|title=Ballard wants Leafs to have own farm club|date=March 21, 1980|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Across Canada: No liquor licence for Leafs-Hawks farm club|date=November 9, 1978|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AHL Hawks get Tessier|date=August 22, 1981|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>  However, by 1980 MLGL had decided that the Leafs needed a team of their own,<ref name=\"Globe and Mail\"/> with a spokesperson citing the limited number of roster spots as the rationale for the move.<ref name=newfarm/><ref name=mayget/>  In 1981 the [[Cincinnati Tigers (ice hockey)|Cincinnati Tigers]] of the old [[Central Hockey League (1963\u20131984)|Central Hockey League]] were established under the ownership of MLGL,<ref name=newfarm>{{cite news|title=Leafs get new farm club in Central Hockey League|date=June 24, 1981|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=mayget>{{cite news|title=Cincinnati may get Leaf farm team|date=June 17, 1981|last=Campbell|first=Neil|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=price /><ref name=owned/> but the team averaged only 1,500 fans and lost $750,000 in their first season and folded the following spring.<ref name=leave/><ref>{{cite news|title=Salming wins Conacher award Niagara may get Leaf farm team|date=June 11, 1982|last=Campbell|first=Neil|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=musicalchairs>{{cite news|title=It's musical chairs on ice as CHL franchises switch|date=May 28, 1982|last=Campbell|first=Neil|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>  Shortly thereafter, with Chicago having pulled out of New Brunswick in favour of affiliating with the [[Springfield Indians]] on their own,<ref name=leave>{{cite news|title=Leaf team to leave Moncton|date=June 2, 1982|work=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref name=musicalchairs/> the Leafs relocated the New Brunswick Hawks to [[St. Catharines]], Ontario to establish the [[St. Catharines Saints]] as their farm team.<ref name=owned>{{cite news|title=Leafs place AHL team in St. Kitts|date=June 22, 1982|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zmhGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K-kMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1166%2C2190660|title=Red Wings return to North as AHL swells to 13 teams|last=Kane|first=Mike|date=July 24, 1982|work=[[Schenectady Gazette]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AHL adds three teams in expansion|date=July 24, 1982|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>  The team played in St. Catharines until 1986, and after stops in [[Newmarket, Ontario]] as the [[Newmarket Saints]] (1986\u20131991) and [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador]] as the [[St. John's Maple Leafs]] (1991\u20132005), the team moved to Toronto as the [[Toronto Marlies]] (named after the company's former junior team) where they have been playing ever since.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marlies.ca/history/ahl.asp|title=AHL History|accessdate=January 26, 2014|publisher=Toronto Marlies|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317061340/http://www.marlies.ca/history/ahl.asp|archivedate=March 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegram.com/article/20130404/COLUMN35/104049867/-1/mobile|title=AHL: Bracken Kearns easy Worcester Sharks MVP choice|date=April 4, 2013|accessdate=January 26, 2014|work=[[Telegram & Gazette]]|last=Ballou|first=Bill}}</ref>\n\nThe Toronto Marlboros served as a junior farm team for the Maple Leafs for 40 years until direct NHL sponsorship of junior clubs ended in 1967 when the NHL made the [[NHL Entry Draft|Entry Draft]] universal.<ref name=history/><ref name=Hamilton/>  In October 1988, with the team losing hundreds of thousands of dollars a year, MLGL reached an agreement to sell the Marlboros for a reported $500,000, severing their ties with the Maple Leafs.<ref name=Hamilton>{{cite news|title=Hamilton lawyer, realtor purchase OHL Marlboros|first=William|last=Houston|date=October 20, 1988|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=newhome>{{cite news|title=Hamilton new home as Marlies are bought|date=October 20, 1988|first=Lois|last=Kalchman|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref name=deathmarlies>{{cite news|title=Death of the Marlies: The cold, hard facts Rising costs and dwindling attendance have sunk once-proud Toronto Marlies, seven- time winners of Memorial Cup|date=March 18, 1989|first=Paul|last=Hunter|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref name=endnears/><ref>{{cite news|title=Toronto should miss Marlies, but it won't|first=Jim|last=Proudfoot|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=February 8, 1989}}</ref> However, the Leafs retained the rights to the Marlies name.<ref name=newhome/><ref name=deathmarlies/><ref name=endnears/>  The OHL team moved to Hamilton for the 1989\u201390 season, becoming the [[Dukes of Hamilton]].<ref name=timeline/><ref name=endnears>{{cite news|title=Marlies fare well as end nears Club on a win streak before transformation to Dukes of Hamilton|date=March 13, 1989|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\n===Growth beyond hockey===\n\nIn 1967 MLGL entered into negotiations to purchase the financially struggling [[Toronto Maple Leafs (International League)|Toronto Maple Leafs]] baseball team of the minor AAA [[International League]].<ref name=helpinghand>{{cite news|title=Hockey Leafs offer helping hand to struggling baseball namesakes|last=Dechman|first=Phillip|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=August 28, 1967}}</ref><ref name=doom/><ref name=notover>{{cite news|title=Game's not over yet for ball Leafs, support grows to keep team here|last=Dechman|first=Phillip|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=September 7, 1967}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Baseball club gives assurance stadium bill will be paid|last=Dechman|first=Phillip|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=November 2, 1967}}</ref> The asking price was $60,000.<ref name=doom/> The deal ultimately fell apart due to concerns about the team's stadium, [[Maple Leaf Stadium]], which needed up to $250,000 in repairs and whose owner wanted $4 million to purchase it,<ref name=doom>{{cite news|title=Ballard lays Leafs' doom to apathy|date=October 18, 1967|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=notover/> and the team was sold and relocated to become the [[Louisville Colonels (minor league baseball)|Louisville Colonels]] for the following season.  MLGL owner Harold Ballard said that the company's interest was due in part to help position itself to go after a [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) franchise for Toronto.<ref name=doom/><ref name=notover/>   In early 1974 MLGL announced plans to build a new baseball stadium in Toronto,<ref>{{cite news|title=East of Yonge near expressway: Free stadium if Metro adopts Ballard's $190 million development|date=January 16, 1974|first=Alden|last=Baker|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> but the city ultimately decided to renovate [[Exhibition Stadium]] to make it suitable for baseball.<ref>{{cite news|title=Work could start this fall: Metro votes 23 to 6 to enlarge the CNE Stadium|date=February 27, 1974|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|last=Simpson|first=Jeff}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Baseball franchise seekers may pool their resources to expedite stadium plan|date=January 24, 1974|first=Jim|last=Vipond|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>  At the time, the MLGL group, led by Lorne Duguid, vice-president of [[Hiram Walker]] Distillers and MLGL executive,<ref>{{cite news|title=Gardens will seek baseball franchise|date=November 28, 1974|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> was one of at least four bidding for a Toronto MLB team, including competing groups led by [[Labatt Brewing Company]], Robert Hunter, the former President of the International League Maple Leafs, and Canadian Baseball Co, led by Sydney Cooper.<ref name=bothapproached>{{cite news|title=Both major leagues will be approached|date=November 20, 1974|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Not a question of money': Godfrey leads Metro delegation seeking major-league franchise|date=October 11, 1974|last=Parsons|first=Anne|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=consolidation>{{cite news|title=Franchise consolidation not sighted: Toronto bids likely to fatten price|date=December 4, 1974|first=Mary|last=Trueman|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fourth group pursues franchise: As among major baseball clubs sought for Toronto by Labatt|date=November 29, 1974|first=Mary|last=Trueman|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>  After negotiating with the owners of the [[Baltimore Orioles]], [[Chicago White Sox]], [[Cleveland Indians]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Big league baseball asks Ballard to buy team for Toronto|date=March 16, 1972|newspaper=Toronto Star|first=Jim|last=Proudfoot}}</ref> and [[Oakland Athletics]] in their attempt to acquire a team for Toronto,<ref>{{cite news|title=Ballard confident Gardens group soon will buy Giants ballclub|date=October 21, 1975|first=Don|last=Ramsay|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> MLGL offered $15 million for the [[San Francisco Giants]]<ref>{{cite news|title=2 Toronto-based groups seek franchise at winter baseball meetings in Florida|date=December 4, 1975|first=Jim|last=Vipond|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> but the team's owner decided in early 1976 to sell the club to the Labatt group for US$13.25 million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Giants Moving: Toronto |author= |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |date=January 9, 1976|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hbwMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Ql8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5064,759147 }}</ref>  While the Giants' relocation was ultimately rejected by a U.S. court,<ref>{{cite web |date=April 4, 1976|accessdate=January 2, 2015 |title=Will Toronto ever get a baseball franchise? |url=http://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/sports/baseball/major-league-baseball-comes-to-canada/will-toronto-ever-get-a-franchise.html |publisher=[[CBC News]]|first=Suzanne|last=Howden}}</ref> Labatt was awarded an expansion team in the [[American League]] that became the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] for US$7 million later that year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Labatt's, Webster get ball franchise|date=March 27, 1976|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|first=Paul|last=Patton}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Toronto Is Given A.L. Franchise|date=March 27, 1976|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Expansion approved In Eastern Division: Toronto can join American League in 1977|date=March 22, 1976|first=Dave|last=Perkins|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\nA team named the [[Toronto Maple Leafs (NLA)|Toronto Maple Leafs]] competed in the inaugural season of the [[National Lacrosse Association]], a professional [[box lacrosse]] league, in 1968 at MLG.<ref name=leafsrespond>{{cite news|title=Leafs respond with win for new coach Kapasky|date=July 18, 1968|last=Cauz|first=Louis|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> MLGL owners Ballard and Stafford Smythe were two of the five founding partners of the club,<ref>{{cite news|title=Big gamble by backers in lacrosse|date=April 9, 1968|last=Golla|first=James|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> but financial difficulties forced MLGL to take over ownership midway though the season.<ref name=leafsrespond/><ref>{{cite news|title=TV key to lacrosse expansion|date=August 8, 1968|first=Terry|last=Fraser|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]}}</ref><ref name=losesfaith>{{cite news|title=Kells loses faith in sports fans|date=August 14, 1969|first=Terry|last=Fraser|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]}}</ref> The NLA suspended operations prior to the following season.<ref name=losesfaith/><ref>{{cite news|title=Pro lacrosse league suspends operations|date=March 18, 1969|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ivor Wynne Stadium5.jpg|thumb|Ivor Wynne Stadium, former home of the Hamilton Tiger-Cats which MLGL owned from the late 1970s to the late 1980s]]\n\nIn the early 1970s MLGL announced plans to apply for a second Toronto-based [[Canadian Football League]] team, in addition to the [[Toronto Argonauts]], which would play at [[Varsity Stadium]], but the proposal never went anywhere.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bid to CFL for 2nd team in Toronto|first=Dick|last=Beddoes|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|date=April 18, 1973|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jake Gauaur is waiting for Bill Ballard's cheque|date=April 28, 1973|first=Al|last=Sokol|work=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref name=linking>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2012/11/20/linking-torontos-football-hockey-pasts|title=Linking Toronto's football, hockey pasts|date=November 20, 2012|accessdate=January 14, 2014|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|last=Hornby|first=Lance}}</ref>  In 1974, when his former partner [[John Bassett]] put the Argonauts up for sale for $3.3 million, Ballard expressed interest in buying the team, but it was ultimately sold to [[William R. Hodgson]].<ref name=linking/><ref>{{cite news|title=Bassett offers to sell Argos for $3.3 million|date=February 22, 1974|work=Toronto Star|first=Al|last=Sokol}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bollard wants look at Argo balance sheet before bidding for team|date=February 23, 1974|work=The Globe and Mail|last=Cauz|first=Louis}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Barbara and Ballard agree, want to study Argo books|first=Rex|last=MacLeod|work=The Globe and Mail|date=February 26, 1974}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Argo franchise sold to hotel chain owner|date=February 28, 1974|work=Toronto Star|first=Al|last=Sokol}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jc3YbqHtsW4C|title=Bassett: John Bassett's forty years in politics, publishing, business and sports|author=[[Maggie Siggins|Siggins, Maggie]]|year=2011}}</ref>  Shortly thereafter Ballard tried to buy the [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] of the CFL from owner [[Michael DeGroote]], but this offer was also rejected. Three money-losing seasons later, in February 1978, DeGroote sold the team to MLGL for $1.3 million.<ref name=Hamilton/><ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs' owner Ballard spends $1.3 million to buy the Tiger-Cats|first=Rick|last=Matsumoto|work=Toronto Star|date=January 24, 1978|pages=B1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Third group says Ticat bid likely if Ballard vetoed|date=February 3, 1978|last=Goodman|first=Jeffrey|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= All we need are some players Fans 'choice' for Ticats gleefully takes over team |date=February 17, 1978|last=Palango|first=Paul|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=ticats>{{cite web|url=http://ticats.com/page/history_history|title=Tiger-Cats History|accessdate=January 14, 2014|publisher=[[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116113510/http://ticats.com/page/history_history|archive-date=January 16, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>  During his tenure as owner of the Tiger-Cats, Ballard repeatedly threatened to move the franchise to Toronto's Varsity Stadium,<ref>{{cite news|title=Ticats talked with Varsity brass|date=November 30, 1988|last1=Starkman|first1=Randy|author1link=Randy Starkman|last2=Hunter|first2=Paul|work=Toronto Star}}</ref> which was vetoed by the Argos,<ref>{{cite news|title=Alternative to Tiger-Cats: Bassett sees Hamilton in USFL|date=March 22, 1983|first=Marty|last=York|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> and claimed to have lost roughly $20 million over 11 seasons.<ref name=braley>{{cite news|title=Ballard sells Tiger-Cats to Hamilton businessman|date=February 15, 1989|work=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]}}</ref>   MLGL sold the team in March 1989 to [[David Braley]] for $2.<ref name=ticats/><ref name=braley/><ref>{{cite news|title=Ballard may get more out of $2 Ti-Cat sale|date=November 21, 1989|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|work=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iM02FnDRZMIC|publisher=[[Dundurn Press]]|last=Januska|first=Michael|title=Grey Cup Century|year=2012|page=192}}</ref>\n\nRuby Richman, the former coach of [[Canada men's national basketball team]], working with Ballard pursued a number of existing [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and [[American Basketball Association]] (ABA) teams to relocate to Toronto to play at MLG in the 1970s.<ref name=richmanquest/><ref name=nbaawards/><ref name=covetsrockets/> Richman had a tentative agreement to purchase both the [[Miami Floridians]] and [[Pittsburgh Condors]] of the ABA with a plan to merge them into a single Toronto-based team, but the deal fell through.<ref name=richmanquest>{{cite news|title=Ruby Richman's quest: The pro basketball chase|date=March 3, 1976|last=Fear|first=Jonathan|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> Later, Richman held negotiations with the [[Detroit Pistons]], which were seeking $5 million for the franchise, but pulled out when the price was raised to $8.25 million.<ref name=richmanquest/>  MLGL attempted to purchase and relocate the [[Buffalo Braves]], which had played a number of regular season games at MLG over the years, to Toronto in 1974 for $8.5 million,<ref name=dream>{{cite news|title=Toronto dream of NBA team remains dream|date=January 14, 1975|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Snyder rejects Gardens bid of $8.5 million for Braves|work=The Globe and Mail|date=October 5, 1974}}</ref> and again several times later,<ref name=richmanquest/><ref name=hawks/><ref>{{cite news|title=Bid to bring Braves to Toronto has 50-50 chance|last=Goodman|first=Jeffrey|date=December 14, 1977|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VFM_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=KVIMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4925,5570645|title=Toronto group seeking Braves|date=December 14, 1977|accessdate=October 8, 2013|work=[[Windsor Star]]}}</ref> but the owners eventually chose to move the team to [[San Diego]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gU4sAAAAIBAJ&sjid=os0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=4052,1555484|title=Boston, Buffalo Exchange Owners; Buffalo Transfer to San Diego Approved|date=July 8, 1978|accessdate=October 8, 2013|work=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Nt0hAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G0cEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4972,3789055|title=Brown now looking west|date=June 23, 1978|accessdate=October 8, 2013|work=[[The Daily News (Kentucky)|Daily News]]}}</ref>  When Toronto was awarded an expansion NBA franchise in 1974 for the 1975\u201376 season<ref name=nbaawards>{{cite news|title=NBA awards expansion franchise to Toronto for 1975\u201376 season|date=June 22, 1974|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=withoutowner>{{cite news|title=N.B.A. Adds Toronto, Without Owner|date=June 22, 1974|first=Sam|last=Goldaper|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref name=back>{{cite news|title=Toronto is back in NBA picture|last=Keller|first=Arlie|work=Toronto Star|date=September 26, 1975}}</ref> MLGL was one of three groups to bid for the rights to the team,<ref name=nbaawards/><ref name=withoutowner/><ref>{{cite news|title=Ballard expects to win bid for NBA franchise by end of November|date=November 8, 1974|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fresh backing is expected for Toronto's NBA entry|last=Keller|first=Arlie|work=Toronto Star|date=December 13, 1974}}</ref> but the club never materialized as no group was able to secure funding for the expansion fee of $6.8 million.<ref name=dream/><ref>{{cite news|title=NBA lowers curtain on Toronto's quest for team next season|date=January 15, 1975|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Richman seeks NBA backers for Toronto|date=January 8, 1975|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> MLGL attempted to purchase and relocate the [[Houston Rockets]] in 1975, which were seeking $8 million for the team, but the team's lease ultimately prevented a relocation.<ref name=richmanquest/><ref name=covetsrockets>{{cite news|title=Ballard covets NBA Rockets, sends Richman to make deal|date=September 25, 1975|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rockets' president doubts Ballard to get Houston NBA team|date=September 26, 1975|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> In 1976 MLGL attempted to buy the [[Atlanta Hawks]].<ref name=hawks>{{cite news|title=Basketball by this fall is MLG aim|date=June 3, 1976|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=back/> In 1979 a Toronto group which included Ballard again pushed for an expansion franchise, but lost out to the [[Dallas Mavericks]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Toronto's NBA bid is real longshot|date=February 8, 1979|first=Jeffry|last=Goodman|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Roundup: Toronto team may join NBA|date=February 5, 1979|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>  A Toronto group, which included [[Bill Ballard]], son of Harold, and [[Basketball Hall of Fame]]r [[Wilt Chamberlain]] submitted an application and US$100,000 deposit for an NBA expansion franchise for MLG in 1986, but of the six cities to apply<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/08/21/sports/sports-people-toronto-in-nba-bid.html|title=Sports people; Toronto in N.B.A. Bid|date=August 21, 1986|accessdate=January 27, 2014|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Toronto investors seek NBA franchise|date=August 20, 1986|work=The Globe and Mail|first=James|last=Davidson}}</ref> Toronto was not one of the four which were successful.<ref>{{cite news|title=No NBA club for Toronto|date=April 23, 1987|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> It was not until the NBA awarded an expansion franchise to [[John Bitove]], over a group led by future MLSE minority partner [[Larry Tanenbaum]] which had partnered with the Maple Leafs,<ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs left out in cold by NBA decision|last=Shoalts|first=David|work=The Globe and Mail|date=October 1, 1993}}</ref> and the [[Toronto Raptors]] joined the NBA for the 1995\u201396 season that the city would get an NBA team.\n\n===Merger with the Raptors and rebranding===\nIn 1997 it was reported that the Maple Leafs were in negotiations to purchase the [[Toronto Shooting Stars]] of the [[National Professional Soccer League (1984\u20132001)|National Professional Soccer League]].<ref name=hiatus>{{Cite news|title=Shooting Stars to go on hiatus for one season|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=August 15, 1997|page=E5}}</ref>  The team had been suspended following their inaugural season playing at MLG during which the club lost nearly $1 million and the league was forced to take over operations after only three games when ownership pulled out.<ref name=hiatus/><ref>{{cite news|title=Hamilton in the running for moving Stars|date=March 11, 1997|newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=League bails out soccer's Stars|first=Norman|last=Da Costa|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=November 2, 1996|page=E7}}</ref>  However, the team never returned to play.  Following the inaugural season of the [[Hamilton, Ontario]]-based [[Ontario Raiders]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]] in 1998, in which they lost $250,000 playing at [[Copps Coliseum]], owner [[Chris Fritz]] was forced to look for partners.<ref name=quits>{{cite news|title=Raiders call it quits in Hamilton|date=August 20, 1998|last=Kernaghan|first=John|newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref>  MLSE engaged in negotiations to purchase the team and have it play at MLG.<ref name=quits/><ref>{{cite news|title=Hamilton's pro lacrosse is going, going&nbsp;... |date=July 7, 1998|last=Milton|first=Steve|newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Three-way toss up for Ontario Raiders|date=July 14, 1998|last=Kernaghan|first=John|newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref>  However, a group which included [[Bill Watters]], the then Assistant General Manager of the Toronto Maple Leafs, ultimately bought the team for $250,000 and promptly moved it to MLG where they rebranded the team the [[Toronto Rock]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Watters, Beeston, Domi, Orr bring pro lacrosse to town|date=December 4, 1998|newspaper=Toronto Star|last=Brown|first=Josh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rock will test Toronto's taste for pro lacrosse|date=December 24, 1998|last=Stevens|first=Neil|newspaper=[[Waterloo Region Record]]}}</ref>  MLSE held negotiations with the [[Arena Football League]] in 1998 on acquiring a US$4\u20137 million expansion franchise for the following season to coincide with the opening of the ACC.<ref name=mayland>{{cite news|title=Arena football team may land in Toronto|date=July 29, 1998|last=York|first=Marty|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=CFL is looking at new arenas to keep football alive|date=March 17, 1999|last=York|first=Marty|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>  The company also submitted an application for a [[Women's National Basketball Association]] franchise, but was rejected by the league due to concerns about their readiness.<ref name=mayland/><ref name=dreamjob>{{cite book|title=Dream Job|last=Peddie|first=Richard|year=2013|publisher=[[Harper Collins]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Air Canada Centre and CN Tower from Bay St.jpg|thumb|left|Scotiabank Arena, home to the Maple Leafs and Raptors since 1999, came under the ownership of MLGL while under construction with the merger of the two franchises]]\n\nWith MLG aging, MLGL began planning for a new home arena for the Maple Leafs in the 1990s.  At the time, the Raptors were constructing a new arena, later to be called  [[Scotiabank Arena]], which they invited the Maples Leafs to be a joint tenant at.  However, MLGL reject the offer, arguing that \"the footprint is too small\".<ref name=ACCchron/>  When [[Allan Slaight]] took over controlling ownership of the Toronto Raptors in late 1996,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/1996/10/21/Franchises/RAPTORS-UP-FOR-GRABS-AS-SLAIGHT-ENACTS-BUYOUT-CLAUSE.aspx|title=Raptors up for grabs as Slaight enacts buyout clause|date=October 21, 1996|accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1996/Bitove-Bows-out-Slaight-Maps-Out-Raptors-Future/id-d77393e4d1aeb24a3a980f15a557f8cf|title= Bitove Bows out, Slaight Maps Out Raptors' Future|date=November 15, 1996|accessdate=December 27, 2013|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Allan Slaight wins control of Raptors|date=November 16, 1996|last=Smith|first=Doug|newspaper=[[Kingston Whig-Standard]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Slaight maps out the future: Bitove bows out of Raptors' life|date=November 16, 1996|newspaper=[[The Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref> talks began again between the two groups.  MLGL put forward a proposal to the city to construct a new $300 million shared arena just to the north, on top of the rail tracks [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]], with the already under construction Raptors arena being converted to a bus terminal.<ref name=ACCchron>{{cite web|url=http://www.canoe.ca/HelloHangar/chronology.html|title=CHRONOLOGY|publisher=[[Canoe.ca]]|accessdate=May 1, 2016}}</ref>  However, the proposal died when an agreement could not reached with the [[City of Toronto government]] on rent for the land.<ref name=ACCchron/><ref>{{cite news|title=An open letter to the Citizens of Toronto|date=July 12, 1997|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref>  In November 1997 MLSE submitted a new proposal for a $250 million arena at [[Exhibition Place]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-22960236.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911123230/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-22960236.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 11, 2016|title=AROUND AND ABOUT|newspaper=[[Buffalo News]]|date=November 25, 1997}}</ref>  However, after years of acrimonious negotiations MLGL purchased 100% of the Raptors basketball club and the ACC, from [[Allan Slaight]] and the [[Bank of Nova Scotia]] on February 12, 1998.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors bought by Leafs|date=February 13, 1998|last=Tedesco|first=Theresa|newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Deal between Raptors and Leafs has a|date=February 13, 1998|last=Tedesco|first=Theresa|publisher=[[Canwest]]}}</ref>  MLGL paid a reported $467 million, made up of $179 million for the team and $288 million for the arena.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stunning deal sees Leafs buy Raptors|date=February 13, 1998|publisher=[[Canadian Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NBA approves sale of Raptors|date=March 28, 1998|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/mar/28/sports/sp-33649|title= NBA at a Glance / Daily Report|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 28, 1998|accessdate=January 10, 2014}}</ref> [[Richard Peddie]], who had been President of the Toronto Raptors, was retained in the merger and became MLSE's President and CEO.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.uwindsor.ca/alumni/richardpeddie|title=Richard Peddie BComm '70, LLD '01|accessdate=December 27, 2013|publisher=[[University of Windsor]]}}</ref>  That July the company adopted a new name, Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment (MLSE), to reflect its broader holdings.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey Briefs|date=July 16, 1998|work=Toronto Star}}</ref>  MLSE subsequently ordered major modifications to the original design of the ACC, which was basketball-specific, to make it more suitable for hockey.  Originally planned to cost $217 million, the budget was increased to $265 million after MLSE took control.<ref name=cost>{{cite news|title=Upgrades added to cost|first=David|last=Shoalts|date=February 17, 1999|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>  In February 1999 the company opened the ACC as the new home to the Leafs and Raptors.  MLG, which was left with no major tenants, was sold in 2004 for $12 million to [[Loblaw Companies]], Canada's largest food retailer, which converted the ground level into one of its [[Loblaws]] franchises.  A condition of the sale was that it was not to be used as a sports and entertainment facility, though MLSE eventually consented to allowing a small arena to be restored in the building to house [[Ryerson University]]'s [[Ryerson Rams|Rams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citynews.ca/2011/10/19/maple-leaf-gardens-building-renamed/|title=Maple Leaf Gardens building renamed|last=Chu|first=Showwei|date=October 19, 2011|accessdate=January 16, 2014|publisher=[[CityNews]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2009/11/30/ryerson_and_loblaws_make_a_deal_for_maple_leaf_gardens.html|title=Ryerson and Loblaws make a deal for Maple Leaf Gardens|date=November 30, 2009|accessdate=January 16, 2014|work=Toronto Star|last= Balkissoon|first= Denise}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Raptors 0607.JPG|thumb|A Raptors game at Air Canada Centre in 2006 following their acquisition by MLGL]]\n\nThe [[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]] (CRTC) granted MLSE two [[Category 2 specialty channel|category 2]] digital [[specialty channel]] licenses in 2000 for [[Leafs TV]] and [[Raptors NBA TV]], which launched on September 7, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030321125842/http://www.crtc.gc.ca/ownership/cht177.pdf|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/ownership/cht177.pdf|title=Maple Leaf|date=January 16, 2002|archivedate=March 21, 2003|accessdate=September 3, 2015|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]}}</ref>  The channels were used by MLSE to broadcast live games involving their teams in an attempt to increase competition for their rights and drive up the fees paid by other broadcasters.<ref name=dreamjob/>\n\n[[File:Ricohcoliseum.jpg|thumb|left|Ricoh Coliseum after being renovated in 2005 to house MLSE's Toronto Marlies]]\n\nIn August 2004 MLSE announced that they would relocate their AHL farm team from [[St. John's, Newfoundland]] to Toronto to play in [[Ricoh Coliseum]] (later renamed Coca-Cola Coliseum) for the 2005\u201306 season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theahl.com/leafs-making-final-run-in-st-john-s-p137005|title=Leafs making final run in St. John's|date=November 29, 2004|accessdate=January 3, 2013|publisher=[[American Hockey League]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103163121/http://theahl.com/leafs-making-final-run-in-st-john-s-p137005|archivedate=January 3, 2014}}</ref> after the arena was left without a hockey tenant following the termination of their lease with the [[Toronto Roadrunners]], the AHL affiliate of the [[Edmonton Oilers]], for defaulting on their rent.<ref name=exboard>{{cite web|url=http://www.explace.on.ca/database/rte/files/Item%2017-MLSEL.pdf|title=Expansion of MLSEL Office Space in Ricoh Coliseum|date=June 26, 2013|accessdate=January 3, 2014|publisher=[[Exhibition Place]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103154508/http://www.explace.on.ca/database/rte/files/Item%2017-MLSEL.pdf|archivedate=January 3, 2014}}</ref><ref name=default>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/oilers-farm-team-caught-in-lease-controversy-at-ricoh/article1000820/|title= Oilers' farm team caught in lease controversy at Ricoh |date=June 16, 2004|accessdate=January 3, 2014|last=Erwin|first=Steve|work=The Globe and Mail|location=Toronto}}</ref>  MLSE agreed to a 20-year lease for the Coliseum,<ref name=exboard/> which had undergone a $38 million renovation in 2003,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/coliseum-gets-makeover/article1009714/|title= Coliseum gets makeover |date=January 16, 2003|accessdate=January 2, 2014|last=Christie|first=James|work=The Globe and Mail|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref name=BW>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20031106005775/en/Ricoh-Canada-Announces-Opening-Torontos-Ricoh-Coliseum#.UsZBY_ggp2N|archiveurl=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Ricoh+Canada+Inc.+Announces+the+Opening+of+Toronto%27s+Ricoh+Coliseum.-a0109864185|archivedate=November 6, 2003|title=Ricoh Canada Inc. Announces the Opening of Toronto's Ricoh Coliseum.|date=November 6, 2003|accessdate=January 2, 2014|work=[[Business Wire]]}}</ref> that called for rent to cover debt financing charges, property taxes and generate a return to the arena investors,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2013/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-57447.pdf|title=Comprehensive Review of City's Loan Guarantee and Loan Portfolio|date=April 9, 2013|accessdate=January 3, 2014|publisher=[[City of Toronto government]]}}</ref> which exceeds $4 million annually.<ref name=dreamjob/>\n\n[[File:Maple Leaf Square, North Tower.jpg|thumb|Condos at Maple Leaf Square built by a partnership including MLSE next to Scotiabank Arena]]\n\nMLSE announced in April 2005 that they would be working with [[Cadillac Fairview]] (a wholly owned subsidiary of Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan) and Lanterra Developments to build [[Maple Leaf Square]], a major entertainment complex situated next to the ACC. The $500 million {{convert|1700000|sqft|m2}} complex, which was completed in 2010, is a mixed use facility which features the Hotel St. Germain, e11ven restaurant, Real Sports Apparel, Real Sports Bar and Grill, [[Longo's]] grocery store, office space and condominium residences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlse.com/our-company/|title=Inside MLSE: History|accessdate=April 6, 2014|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcl.com/Projects-that-Inspire/Pages/Maple-Leaf-Square.aspx|title=Maple Leaf Square|accessdate=April 6, 2014|publisher=[[PCL Construction]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/news/columnists/joe_warmington/2010/10/06/15609141.html|title=Leafs Nation deserves better|first=Joe|last=Warmington|date=October 6, 2010|accessdate=April 6, 2014|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapleleafsquare.com/home.html|title=Maple Leaf Square|publisher=[[Maple Leaf Square]]|accessdate=April 6, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140804001927/http://www.mapleleafsquare.com/home.html|archivedate=August 4, 2014}}</ref>  In conjunction with the construction of Maple Leaf Square was a two-year, $48 million renovation of the ACC to connect it with the square, which added a new atrium that includes a [[High-definition television|high-definition]] broadcast studio for Leafs TV, [[NBA TV Canada]] and [[GolTV Canada]].  The external wall of the atrium features a 30 by {{convert|50|ft|m|adj=on}} video screen which often broadcasts games to spectators gathered in the plaza in front of the arena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/news/accexpansion_presser_091109.html|title=Air Canada Centre Re-Opens Bigger And Better After Summer Hiatus|date=September 11, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2014|publisher=[[Toronto Raptors]]}}</ref>\n\n===Further expansion===\n\n[[File:First-goal-at-BMO.jpg|thumb|left|Toronto FC scores their first goal at BMO Field in 2007 following their launch by MLSE]]\n\n[[File:First period play gets a little rowdy.jpg|thumb|Fans watch the Toronto Maple Leafs play the Boston Bruins in game 2 of the Eastern Conference Quarterfinals in the [[2013 Stanley Cup playoffs]] at Maple Leaf Square, a plaza built by MLSE next to the Scotiabank Arena]]\n\nMLSE was awarded a [[Major League Soccer]] expansion team for Toronto, which would become known as [[Toronto FC]], in 2005 for US$10 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mikeozanian/2013/05/21/david-beckham-to-earn-huge-windfall-from-new-yorks-mls-expansion/|title=David Beckham To Earn Huge Windfall From New York's MLS Expansion|date=May 21, 2013|accessdate=November 23, 2013|work=[[Forbes]]|first=Mike|last=Ozanian}}</ref>  The company also agreed to contribute $8 million towards the construction of Toronto FC's future home [[BMO Field]], which was to cost $62.9 million total, and purchased the naming rights to the stadium for $10 million for 20 years, which they subsequently resold to the [[Bank of Montreal]] for $27 million over the first 10 years.<ref name=approved/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bmo.com/bmo/files/news%20release/4/1/bmo_bmofieldtor_sep2006_en.htm|title=BMO Field to be Home for Toronto FC and Canada's National Soccer Teams|date=September 20, 2006|accessdate=April 27, 2014|publisher=[[Bank of Montreal]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923192654/http://www.bmo.com/bmo/files/news%20release/4/1/bmo_bmofieldtor_sep2006_en.htm|archive-date=September 23, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/695264964/Real-Salt-Lake-negotiating-deal-for-stadium-name-rights.html|title=Real Salt Lake negotiating deal for stadium name rights|date=March 27, 2008|accessdate=April 27, 2014|first=James|last=Edward|newspaper=[[Deseret News]]}}</ref>  MLSE also agreed to cover any construction cost overruns.<ref name=approved>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/toronto-city-council-approves-soccer-stadium-deal-1.536727|title=Toronto city council approves soccer stadium deal|date=October 27, 2005|accessdate=October 1, 2013|publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/784743/bmo-field-mlse-delivers-financial-return-to-city-of-toronto|title=BMO Field, MLSE delivers financial return to City of Toronto|accessdate=February 23, 2011}}</ref> The governments of Canada, Ontario and Toronto contributed $27 million, $8 million and $9.8 million respectively, with the City of Toronto also providing the land.<ref name=approved/><ref name=exboardreport>{{cite web|url=http://www.explace.on.ca/database/rte/files/BMO%20Field-Stadium%20Improvements.pdf|title=Improvements to BMO Field at Exhibition Place|date=March 6, 2014|accessdate=March 8, 2014|publisher=[[Exhibition Place]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309030551/http://www.explace.on.ca/database/rte/files/BMO%20Field-Stadium%20Improvements.pdf|archivedate=March 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/2005/agendas/council/cc051026/pof9rpt/cl036.pdf|title=Soccer Stadium at Exhibition Place |date= October 2005|accessdate=October 1, 2013|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref>  In return, MLSE got the management rights for the stadium for 20 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Soccer/TorontoFC/2009/06/03/pf-9660301.html|title=Grass at BMO remains a contentious issue|date=June 3, 2009|last=Sandor|first=Steven|work=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref>  Prior to the 2010 MLS season, MLSE spent $3.5 million to convert the stadium from [[FieldTurf]] to natural grass,<ref name=exboardreport/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontofc.ca/news/2010/03/grass-installation-underway|title=Grass Installation Underway|date=March 29, 2010|accessdate=October 1, 2013|publisher=[[Toronto FC]]}}</ref> and a further $2 million to expand the north end by 1,400 seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontofc.ca/news/2010/03/north-end-expansion-bmo-field|title=North End Expansion Of BMO Field|publisher=[[Toronto FC]]|date=March 18, 2010|accessdate=November 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2010/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-26066.pdf|title=Additional Seating at BMO Field at Exhibition Place|date=December 9, 2009|accessdate=November 23, 2013|publisher=[[City of Toronto government]]}}</ref> As part of the deal to convert the field to natural grass, MLSE spent $1.2 million adding a winter bubble to [[Lamport Stadium]] and $800,000 building a new artificial turf field to replace the community use hours lost at BMO Field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/grass-bmo-field-attains-final-approval|title=Grass at BMO Field Attains Final Approval|date=January 23, 2010|accessdate=January 1, 2014|publisher=[[Major League Soccer]]}}</ref>  The company manages the operations of the facility during the winter season, when the field is covered by the dome and community soccer programs are held.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2009/cc/bgrd/backgroundfile-23709.pdf|title=Upgrades to BMO Field at Exhibition Place and Allan Lamport Stadium|date=September 22, 2009|publisher=[[City of Toronto government]]}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2009/cc/bgrd/backgroundfile-23710.pdf|title=Upgrades to BMO Field at Exhibition Place and Allan Lamport Stadium - Attachment 1|date=September 9, 2009|publisher=[[City of Toronto government]]}}</ref>\n\nMLSE partnered with Rogers Communications in 2005 to bid to host a regular season [[National Football League]] game [[NFL in Toronto|in Toronto]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Will NFL road show arrive in Toronto?; Godfrey chases regular- season game London the early favourite for 2006|date=September 27, 2005|newspaper=Toronto Star|last=Byers|first=Jim}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=FOOTBALL NFL: Toronto partners pitch to host game|date=October 4, 2005|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|last=Grange|first=Michael}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Godfrey buoyed by talks; NFL officials may decide on Toronto quest in weeks Rogers Centre could host game as early as next year|date=October 4, 2005|newspaper=Toronto Star|last=Byers|first=Jim}}</ref>  On January 30, 2008 it was announced that Rogers and Larry Tanenbaum, chairman of MLSE, had reached an agreement with the [[Buffalo Bills]] to host an annual regular-season and three exhibition NFL games over five seasons at Toronto's [[Rogers Centre]] beginning in 2008, with the games branded the [[Bills Toronto Series]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The breakdown of the Bills' plan to play 8 games in T.O.|date=February 7, 2008|newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref> At the time MLSE was considering bringing an NFL team to Toronto permanently and building them a new stadium, but abandoned the idea when they concluded that the project would not generate sufficient financial return to justify the significant cost of the project.<ref name=dreamjob/> Subsequently, MLSE president [[Tim Leiweke]] said on an NFL team in Toronto: \"We can't own a team (per NFL rules), but we do have more expertise on how to build (stadiums) than anyone&nbsp;... MLSE can play a role.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/football/2013/11/24/jon_bon_jovi_mlse_give_toronto_inside_track_on_buffalo_bills_kelly.html|title=Jon Bon Jovi, MLSE give Toronto inside track on Buffalo Bills: Kelly|date=November 24, 2013|accessdate=January 7, 2014|last=Kelly|first=Cathal|work=Toronto Star}}</ref> It has been reported that MLSE is interested in building and managing the proposed NFL stadium,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2013/11/25/wheels-quietly-in-motion-to-move-buffalo-bills-to-toronto/|title=Wheels (quietly) in motion to move Buffalo Bills to Toronto|date=November 25, 2013|accessdate=January 7, 2014|last=Arthur|first=Bruce|work=[[National Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107215652/http://sports.nationalpost.com/2013/11/25/wheels-quietly-in-motion-to-move-buffalo-bills-to-toronto/|archive-date=January 7, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmontonsun.com/2014/07/29/former-sabres-owner-golisano-didnt-submit-bid-to-buy-bills|title=Former Sabres owner Golisano didn\u2019t submit bid to buy Bills|date=July 29, 2014|accessdate=July 30, 2014|first=John|last=Kryk|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref> which it has already begun designing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/football/livin-on-a-prayer-buying-bills-building-new-toronto-stadium-would-be-a-2-billion-play/article15581107/|title=Bon Jovi buying Bills, building new Toronto stadium would be a $2-billion play |date=November 24, 2013|accessdate=February 2, 2014|work=The Globe and Mail|last=Shoalts|first=David}}</ref>  In 2013 MLSE minority owner Tanenbaum and board member [[Edward Rogers III]] partnered with musician [[Jon Bon Jovi]] to purchase an NFL team.  Following the death of Bills' owner [[Ralph Wilson]] in 2014 the group submitted an offer to purchase the franchise, with speculation that they would move the team to Toronto when their lease permitted it, but were outbid by the [[Terrence Pegula|Pegulas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/sports/source-bon-jovi-group-bid-105-billion-could-have-gone-higher-20140909|title=Source: Bon Jovi group bid $1.05 billion, could have gone higher|work=[[Buffalo News]]|first=Tom|last=Precious|date=September 9, 2014|accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:MLSE logo.jpg|thumb|Logo of MLSE following the launch of Toronto FC, which was used until 2014]]\n\nBefore MLSE completed its purchase of the Argonauts of the CFL in early 2018, the company contemplated purchasing the team at least twice, with minority partner Tanenbaum keen to add the team to his list of franchises, but concluded that the cost and effort that would be required to make the team profitable was not worth the minimal financial upside.<ref name=dreamjob/><ref name=soon>{{cite web|url=http://www2.tsn.ca/toronto/story/?id=442375|title=Argonauts could soon be sold to MLSE or Tanenbaum|date=January 28, 2014|accessdate=February 2, 2014|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref>  In 2013, it was reported that the company was again considering purchasing the team and having them play at a renovated BMO Field,<ref name=soon/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2013/09/03/eventual-argos-sale-could-lead-nfl-to-toronto|title=MLSE interested in Argos with eye on NFL in Toronto|date=September 3, 2013|accessdate=January 8, 2014|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|last=Zicarelli|first=Frank}}</ref><ref name=bigbucks/> with the asking price reportedly $20 million,<ref name=argos4sale>{{cite web|url=http://metronews.ca/news/vancouver/981787/b-c-lions-not-for-sale-toronto-argos-are-owner-david-braley/|title=B.C. Lions not for sale, Toronto Argonauts are: owner David Braley|date=March 24, 2014|accessdate=March 27, 2014|work=[[Metro International]]|last=Tucker|first=Cam}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/03/22/babcock-deserves-jack-adams-award-more-than-ever|title=Babcock deserves Jack Adams Award more than ever|first=Steve|last=Simmons|authorlink=Steve Simmons|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=March 22, 2014|accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref> but later coming down to $10 million.<ref name=spelltrouble>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/07/16/argonauts-off-field-foes-spell-trouble-for-franchise-and-league|title=Argonauts' off-field woes spell trouble for franchise and CFL|first=Bill|last=Lankhof|date=July 16, 2014|accessdate=July 19, 2014|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref>  A vote by MLSE's board on purchasing the team was called in December 2013, but they were unable to come to an agreement on the issue.<ref name=soon/><ref name=shoalts>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/football/leiweke-outlines-mlse-plans-for-stadium-renovation/article16570810/|title=MLSE outlines plans for stadium renovation, with eye on NFL team |date=January 29, 2014|accessdate=February 2, 2014|work=The Globe and Mail|last=Shoalts|first=David|location=Toronto}}</ref>  On May 20, 2015 it was announced that two of the three ownership partners of MLSE, Bell Canada and Tanenbaum's Kilmer Group, had acquired ownership of the Argos, with the deal to close at the end of the year, and would move the team to BMO Field for the 2016 season.<ref name=argospr>{{cite news|date=May 20, 2015|accessdate=May 20, 2015|title=Bell Canada and Kilmer Group to acquire Argonauts|url=http://argonauts.ca/article/bell-canada-and-kilmer-group-to-acquire-argonauts|publisher=Toronto Argonauts|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150522130512/http://argonauts.ca/article/bell-canada-and-kilmer-group-to-acquire-argonauts|archivedate=May 22, 2015}}</ref> It has been speculated that Rogers was not interested in investing in the team since Bell has exclusive rights to broadcast all CFL games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/football/cfl/argonauts-announce-sale-move-to-bmo-field-1.3080235|title=Argonauts announce sale, move to BMO Field|publisher=[[CBC Sports]]|date=May 20, 2015|accessdate=May 20, 2015}}</ref> MLSE eventually completed its purchase the Argos in January 2018.<ref name=ArgosApprove/><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.argonauts.ca/2017/12/13/maple-leafs-sports-entertainment-acquire-grey-cup-champion-toronto-argonauts/|title=MAPLE LEAFS SPORTS & ENTERTAINMENT TO ACQUIRE GREY CUP CHAMPION TORONTO ARGONAUTS|date=December 13, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2017|publisher=[[Toronto Argonauts]]}}</ref> According to the ''[[National Post]]'', the sale, which came less than a month after the team won the [[105th Grey Cup|2017]] [[Grey Cup]], \"is expected to help the Argos, given MLSE\u2019s financial scale and promotional, ticketing and operational advantages.\" <ref name=\"Jackson 2017-12-13\">{{cite news|url=http://business.financialpost.com/telecom/mlse-buys-toronto-argos-now-owns-every-major-toronto-sports-team-but-the-blue-jays |title=MLSE buys Toronto Argos, now owns every major Toronto sports team but the Blue Jays |first=Emily |last=Jackson |newspaper=[[National Post]] |date=December 13, 2017 |accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref>  Additionally, it is thought that control of the Argos by MLSE will enhance Toronto's chances of acquiring an NFL franchise,<ref name=shoalts/> with Peddie saying \"the NFL is telling them that if you want an NFL team, you better make sure the Argos are okay.\"<ref name=soon/>  Leiweke has said that moving into a renovated BMO field \"will help turn [the Argos] around\" and that \"there's no way the NFL comes here without the CFL being unbelievably successful first.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/2014/01/28/leiweke_hints_mlse_may_buy_argonauts_with_eyes_on_future_nfl_team.html|title=Leiweke hints bringing Argos to BMO Field could have NFL implications |date=January 28, 2014|accessdate=February 2, 2014|work=Toronto Star|first=Zoe|last=McKnight}}</ref> Upon completion of the sale, MLSE now owns four of the five major league sports teams in Toronto (only the Blue Jays are not owned by MLSE, although Rogers Communications, which owns the Blue Jays, has an ownership stake in MLSE).\n\nWhen the nearby city of [[Oshawa]] built a new arena, known as [[General Motors Centre]], MLSE was chosen to manage the building.  However, disappointing results in the first year and a half of operations following the arena's opening in November 2006 led MLSE to request that its contract be terminated in March 2008.<ref name=DurhamRegion/> The company had been attempting to get into the business of managing facilities beyond those where their teams play but decided to withdraw, with Bob Hunter, MLSE's Vice President of venues and entertainment, saying that managing the arena was \"no longer a strategic focus for us\".<ref name=DurhamRegion>{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamregion.com/news-story/3480098-mlse-bows-out-of-management-contract-with-gmc/|title=MLSE bows out of management contract with GMC|date=April 1, 2008|accessdate=January 29, 2014}}</ref><ref name=OshawaExpress>{{cite news|url=http://www.oshawaexpress.ca/story879.html |title=Global Spectrum takes over GM Centre |first=Jessica |last=Verge |newspaper=The Oshawa Express |date=June 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018003129/http://www.oshawaexpress.ca/story879.html |archivedate=October 18, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Recent projects===\n\n[[File:Kia training ground.jpg|thumb|BMO Training Ground built by MLSE in the early 2010s to serve as Toronto FC's practice facility and home to the TFC Academy]]\n\nIn 2008 MLSE launched the [[TFC Academy]] [[youth system]] to develop soccer players for Toronto FC<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaircanadacentre.com/assets/default/Practice%20Facility.pdf|title=Toronto FC Training Ground and Home of Toronto FC Academy|accessdate=April 10, 2014|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment}}</ref> by taking advantage of MLS's new [[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|homegrown player rule]] which allows clubs to retain the rights to players they develop without them being subject to the [[MLS SuperDraft]]. The senior academy team originally competed in the [[Canadian Soccer League]] until pulling out in early 2013 due to the CSL losing its sanctioning from the [[Canadian Soccer Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/canadian-soccer-association-allowed-to-de-sanction-csl-1.1395924|title=Canadian Soccer Association allowed to de-sanction CSL|date=April 23, 2013|accessdate=April 10, 2014|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mississauga.com/sports-story/3134429-mississauga-eagles-withdraw-from-csl/|title=Mississauga Eagles withdraw from CSL|first=Iain|last=Colpitts|date=April 18, 2013|accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref>  The team played that year in the [[Ontario Soccer League]] before joining [[League1 Ontario]] for the 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-ca/news/4172/canada/2014/04/09/4741589/tfc-academy-joins-new-ontario-semi-pro-league|title=TFC Academy joins new Ontario semi-pro league|date=April 9, 2014|accessdate=April 10, 2014|first=Rudi|last=Schuller|publisher=Goal.com}}</ref>  In November 2014 MLSE announced the establishment of [[Toronto FC II]], their own minor league professional soccer team playing in the United Soccer League (now known as the [[USL Championship]]) and serving as a [[MLS Reserve League|reserve team]] for TFC and a bridge between the Academy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.torontofc.ca/news/2014/11/toronto-fc-announces-usl-pro-team |title=Toronto FC announces USL PRO team|publisher=[[Toronto FC]]| date=November 20, 2014|accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref>  The team began play in 2015 at a newly renovated 2,000 seat stadium, with plans to expand it to 5,000 by 2017, constructed at the [[Ontario Soccer Centre]] in [[Vaughan]], just north of Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uslsoccer.com/home/857824.html|title=Toronto FC Unveils USL PRO Details|date=January 21, 2015|accessdate=January 21, 2015|publisher=[[USL Pro]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122210220/http://www.uslsoccer.com/home/857824.html|archivedate=January 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontariosoccer.net/ArticleDetails/TabId/29984/ArtMID/46727/ArticleID/246/OSA-Toronto-FC-and-Vaughan-partner-in-new-stadium-.aspx|title=OSA, Toronto FC and Vaughan partner in new stadium|date=January 21, 2015|accessdate=January 21, 2015|publisher=[[Ontario Soccer Association]] |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122211315/http://www.ontariosoccer.net/ArticleDetails/TabId/29984/ArtMID/46727/ArticleID/246/OSA-Toronto-FC-and-Vaughan-partner-in-new-stadium-.aspx|archivedate=January 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkregion.com/sports-story/5269051-toronto-fc-affiliate-rolls-into-vaughan/|title=Toronto FC affiliate rolls into Vaughan|date=January 21, 2015|accessdate=April 28, 2015|first=Adam|last=Martin-Robbins}}</ref>  However, after the expansion did not materialize, which was required to meet the 5,000 seat minimum requirement set by the [[United States Soccer Federation]] for the USL to be sanctioned as a [[United States soccer league system|division 2]] league, the club announced that it would move its home games to BMO Field and Lamport Stadium beginning with the 2018 season.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/sports-story/7526188-tfc-ii-leaving-vaughan-for-toronto-after-3-season-run-stadium-size-at-issue/|title=TFC II leaving Vaughan for Toronto after 3-season run; stadium size at issue|first=Tim|last=Kelly|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=September 5, 2017|newspaper=Vaughan Citizen}}</ref>  On July 2, 2018 the club announced they would move to [[USL League One]] for the league's first season in 2019.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.torontofc.ca/post/2018/07/02/toronto-fc-ii-joins-usl-division-iii-founding-member|title=Toronto FC II joins USL Division III as Founding Member|date=July 2, 2018|accessdate=July 8, 2018|publisher=[[Toronto FC]]}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011 [[Downsview Park]] was selected as the site of Toronto FC's new state-of-the-art academy and training facility. Construction began on the [[BMO Training Ground]] in May 2011, and the facility opened in June 2012.  It includes three grass fields, one domed turf field and a field house. MLSE spent more than $21 million building the facility and pays rent for the land,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/tfc/2011/10/12/video_tfc_building_permanent_training_facility_at_downsview_park.html|title=Video: TFC building permanent training facility at Downsview Park|date=October 12, 2011|accessdate=January 3, 2014|last=Girard|first=Daniel|work=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontofc.ca/trainingground |title=About the facility |accessdate=January 1, 2014 |publisher=[[Toronto FC]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209160116/http://www.torontofc.ca/trainingground |archivedate=February 9, 2014 }}</ref>  In July 2014 it was announced that MLSE would expand the training grounds to house a practice facility for the Argos, which would rent the facility from MLSE and practice on a nearby city owned field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.argonauts.ca/article/argos-partner-with-mlse-to-build-new-practice-facility|title=Argos partner with MLSE to build new practice facility|date=July 24, 2014|accessdate=July 24, 2014|publisher=[[Toronto Argonauts]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730020701/http://www.argonauts.ca/article/argos-partner-with-mlse-to-build-new-practice-facility|archivedate=July 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/argos/2014/07/24/argos_maple_leafs_sports_and_entertainment_partner_on_new_practice_facility.html|title=Argonauts, MLSE partner on new practice facility|date=July 25, 2014|accessdate=July 25, 2014|newspaper=Toronto Star|first=Josh|last=Rubin}}</ref>  The team moved in that September,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/09/09/new-practice-facility-gives-argonauts-some-stability|title=New practice facility gives Argonauts some stability|date=September 9, 2014|accessdate=September 9, 2014|first=Frank|last=Zicarelli|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref> but later moved their practice facility to Lamport Stadium in 2018.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.tsn.ca/argonauts-to-relocate-football-operations-staff-1.1100509|title=Argonauts to relocate football-operations staff|date=June 1, 2018|accessdate=June 1, 2018|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref>\n\nThen Raptors President and General Manager [[Bryan Colangelo]] said in 2008 that MLSE was considering launching an [[NBA Development League]] franchise in the Toronto area within a couple of years to serve as a developmental team for the Raptors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/basketball/2008/01/15/dleague_coming_to_to.html|title=D-League coming to T.O.?|date=January 15, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2014|newspaper=Toronto Star|first=Doug|last=Smith}}</ref> Hamilton's Copps Coliseum and Oshawa were reportedly under consideration to host the franchise.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thespec.com/article/310148|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113141026/http://www.thespec.com/article/310148|title=Hey, it ain't the NBA ... But Raptors placing a D-League farm team in Copps will draw drafted players|date=January 16, 2008|archivedate=January 13, 2010 |newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]|first=Scott|last=Radley}}</ref> However, a Canadian-based franchise posed difficulties due to tax and visa complications,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/lewenberg-d-league-team-is-a-coup-for-raptors-organization-1.321593|title=Lewenberg: D-League team is a coup for Raptors organization|first=Josh|last=Lewenberg|date=June 29, 2015|accessdate=June 30, 2015|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref> and Rochester, New York, which is just across the United States border, was considered as an alternative.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/sports/2014/08/13/rochester-razorsharks-toronto-raptors/14010607/|title=RazorSharks discussing partnership with Raptors|first=Will|last=Cleveland|date=August 13, 2014|accessdate=August 16, 2014|newspaper=[[Democrat and Chronicle]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2015/02/21/d-league-team-on-the-way-for-raptors|title=D-League team on the way for Raptors|date=February 21, 2015|accessdate=February 22, 2015|newspaper=Toronto Sun|first=Ryan|last=Wolstat}}</ref>  In May 2015 it was announced that MLSE had purchased a D-League franchise, which would be named [[Raptors 905]] and would begin play that fall at the [[Paramount Fine Foods Centre|Hershey Centre]] in [[Mississauga]], a suburb of Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://raptors905.dleague.nba.com/news/mlse-purchases-nba-d-league-team-as-league-expands-to-19-teams-for-2015-16-season/|title=MLSE Purchases NBA D-League Team As League Expands To 19 Teams For 2015-16 Season|date=June 29, 2015|accessdate=June 29, 2015|publisher=[[Toronto Raptors]]|first=Anthony|last=Oliva}}</ref> The franchise reportedly cost $6 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/raptors/2015/06/24/raptors-to-announce-d-league-team-will-play-in-mississauga-this-season.html|title=Raptors to announce D League team will play in Mississauga this season|date=June 24, 2015|accessdate=June 29, 2015|first=Doug|last=Smith|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced on January 23, 2009 that MLSE would acquire the 80.1% interest in [[GolTV (Canada)|GolTV Canada]], a digital cable soccer channel, held by MLSE owner Tanenbaum through [[Insight Sports]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.highbeam.com/1758/article-1G1-192490992/mlse-acquires-goltv-insight-sports|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407083810/http://business.highbeam.com/1758/article-1G1-192490992/mlse-acquires-goltv-insight-sports|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 7, 2014|title= MLSE acquires GolTV from Insight Sports.|date=January 23, 2009|accessdate=April 5, 2014|publisher=[[CNW Group]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/tfc-gets-new-family-member|title=TFC gets new family member|publisher=[[Major League Soccer]]}}</ref>  The channel operated as a localized version of [[GOL TV|GOL TV USA]], which owned the remaining 19.9%, with focus on Toronto FC.  MLSE informed the CRTC in 2015 that it had acquired full ownership of the channel,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/ownership/eng/cht177.pdf|title=Maple Leafs & Raptors|date=March 5, 2015|accessdate=May 20, 2015|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-Television Commission]]}}</ref> however later that year they announced that it would cease operations and the license be abandoned, effective August 31, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2015/2015-299.htm|title=Gol TV \u2013 Revocation of licence|date=July 7, 2015|accessdate=July 7, 2015|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-Television Commission]]}}</ref>  In November 2009 MLSE applied to the CRTC for a Category 2 digital TV license for a general interest sports service provisionally named Mainstream Sports,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2009/2009-803.htm#9|title=Broadcasting Notice of Consultation CRTC 2009-803|date=December 23, 2009|accessdate=January 11, 2014|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]}}</ref> which was granted in June 2010.<ref name=msscrtc>{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2010/2010-395.htm|title=Broadcasting Decision CRTC 2010-395|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]|date=June 18, 2011|accessdate=December 10, 2011}}</ref> MLSE planned to broadcast its teams' games on the channel, along the lines of team-owned [[regional sports network]]s in the United States such as [[YES Network]] and the [[New England Sports Network]], with the tentative name \"Real Sports\" (in keeping with the branding of MLSE's sports bar and apparel store).<ref name=dreamjob/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/david-shoalts/whats-next-for-mlse/article2251448/|title=What's next for MLSE?|first=David|last=Shoalts|work=The Globe and Mail|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=December 10, 2011|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/2011/11/27/maple_leaf_sports_plans_broadcast_gamble.html|title=Maple Leaf Sports plans broadcast gamble|first=Rick|last=Westhead|work=Toronto Star|date=November 27, 2011|accessdate=December 10, 2011}}</ref> It was never revealed whether the channel would have replaced, or supplemented, MLSE's existing digital channels.  Peddie credited the threat of a Real Sports channel as a motivator for Rogers and Bell, owners of sports channels [[Sportsnet]] and [[The Sports Network|TSN]] respectively, to purchase the company due to concerns about losing the rights to broadcast MLSE teams to the channel or having to pay huge fees for them.<ref name=dreamjob/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2013/10/22/leafs_nba_gol_tv_hidden_key_to_mlse_value_richard_peddie_says.html|title=Leafs, NBA, GOL TV, hidden key to MLSE value, Richard Peddie says|date=October 22, 2013|accessdate=January 6, 2014|work=Toronto Star}}</ref> The acquisition of MLSE by Rogers and Bell in 2012, and associated agreements to divide the company's regional broadcast rights between the two, eliminated the need for the channel<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/allure-of-certainty-makes-partners-out-of-rivals-rogers-bce/article2266649/|title=Allure of certainty makes partners out of rivals Rogers, BCE|first=Susan|last=Krashinsky|work=The Globe and Mail|date=December 10, 2011|accessdate=December 10, 2011|quote=It also prevents the launch of a well-connected competitor. MLSE has a broadcast licence for a 'specialty' cable sports channel \u2013 tentatively named Real Sports, according to sources \u2013 that could have snatched away those games once the deals with Sportsnet and TSN had expired.|location=Toronto}}</ref> and its license expired after the three-year deadline for launch passed in 2013.<ref name=msscrtc/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/ownership/eng/cht177.pdf|title=Maple Leafs & Raptors|date=March 12, 2014|accessdate=April 5, 2014|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2009 the Maple Leafs and Marlies opened their new hockey practice facility, the [[MasterCard Centre]] (later renamed the Ford Performance Centre).<ref name=nowopen>{{cite web|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=497918|title=Leafs New Practice Rink Unveiled On Tuesday|date=September 8, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2014|publisher=[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]}}</ref> The arena was a joint venture between MLSE, the City of Toronto and the [[Lions Club|Lakeshore Lions Club]] to replace the nearby [[Lakeshore Lions Arena]],<ref name=cadillac>{{cite news|url=http://www.torontosun.com/sports/hockey/2009/09/09/10798796-sun.html|title=Leafs open 'Cadillac' of practice facilities|work=Toronto Sun|last=Hornby|first=Lance|date=September 8, 2009|accessdate=May 6, 2011}}</ref> and was built at a cost of $44 million, after cost overruns drove up the cost from $33.65 million.<ref name=takeover>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2011/06/13/city_poised_to_take_over_arenas_40_million_debt.html|title=City poised to take over arena's $40 million debt|date=June 13, 2011|accessdate=January 6, 2014|work=Toronto Star|last=Moloney|first=Paul}}</ref><ref name=guar/><ref name=stink/>  The Lions Club contributed $40 million to the project, with the city providing a $35.5 million loan guarantee.<ref name=guar>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2011/06/20/torontos-449-million-loan-groan|title=Toronto's $449-million loan groan|last=Levy|first=Sue-Ann|date=June 20, 2011|accessdate=January 6, 2014|work=Toronto Sun}}</ref><ref name=stink>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2011/06/13/rink-stink|title=Rink stink|last=Levy|first=Sue-Ann|date=June 11, 2011|accessdate=January 6, 2011|work=Toronto Sun}}</ref><ref name=onhook>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/toronto-taxpayers-on-hook-as-lakeshore-arena-runs-out-of-cash/article2058581/|title= Toronto taxpayers on hook as Lakeshore arena runs out of cash|date=June 13, 2011|accessdate=January 6, 2014|work=The Globe and Mail|last=Church|first=Elizabeth}}</ref><ref name=whatwrong>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2011/06/25/what_went_wrong_with_etobicokes_stateoftheart_arena.html|title=What went wrong with Etobicoke's state-of-the-art arena?|date=June 25, 2011|accessdate=January 6, 2014|last=Doolittle|first=Robyn|authorlink=Robyn Doolittle|work=Toronto Star}}</ref>  The [[Toronto District School Board]] leased the land for the arena to the Lakeshore Lions for a 50-year term.<ref name=onhook/> MLSE spent a further $5 million on training and medical facilities,<ref name=nowopen/><ref name=cadillac/> and pays $600,000 annually to rent the building.<ref name=nowopen/><ref name=cadillac/>  The arena was originally operated by the Lakeshore Lions Club,<ref name=teamup>{{cite web|url=http://www.mastercard.com/ca/company/en/press/2009/08_19_hockey_excellence.html|title=Leafs, Marlies, Lakeshore Lions Club Team up with MasterCard To Foster Hockey Excellence|date=August 19, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2004|publisher=[[MasterCard]]}}</ref> but in June 2011, with the arena on the verge of defaulting on its rising debt, the City of Toronto took control and assumed its $43.4 million debt<ref name=guar/><ref name=stink/><ref name=onhook/><ref name=annualreport>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2012/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-50421.pdf|title=Annual Report 2011|year=2011|accessdate=January 6, 2014|publisher=Lakeshore Arena Corporation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2011/06/20/bailout-for-lakeshore-lions-arena-approved|title=Bailout for Lakeshore Lions arena approved|date=June 20, 2011|accessdate=January 6, 2014|last=Peat|first=Don|work=Toronto Sun}}</ref> with the intention to return it to private management within 2\u20133 years.<ref name=takeover/><ref name=guar/><ref name=onhook/><ref name=annualreport/><ref name=financialstatement>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2013/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-58245.pdf|title=RE: Lakeshore Arena Corporation 2012 Audited Financial Statements and Annual Report of the Board of Directors|date=March 31, 2013|accessdate=January 6, 2014|publisher=Lakeshore Arena Corporation}}</ref>  A city councillor has suggested that MLSE, which operates BMO Field and Coca-Cola Coliseum on behalf of the city, would be \"the logical party\" to take over the arena, and a spokesperson for the company said \"while we don't have any interest in purchasing the facility, we are open to discussing the possibility of managing the facility on behalf of the City\".<ref name=takeover/> MLSE's executive vice president of venues and entertainment Bob Hunter confirmed that they would bid for the right to run the building.<ref name=whatwrong/>\n\nAt one point MLSE contemplated purchasing the Toronto Blue Jays of MLB and Sportsnet from [[Rogers Communications]], but concerns about the viability of Rogers Centre as a baseball venue and the profitability of the team resulted in the company not pursuing either.<ref name=dreamjob/> The company also considered investing in an English soccer club,<ref name=dreamjob/><ref>{{cite news|last=Westhead|first=Rick|title=Leafs owner eyes U.K. soccer|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/2008/04/24/leafs_owner_eyes_uk_soccer.html|work=Toronto Star|date=April 24, 2008|accessdate=May 29, 2012}}</ref> and in May 2012, after the [[Leeds United]] Supporters Trust put out a request for a takeover from majority shareholder [[Ken Bates]], it was reported that MLSE were in talks to buy the [[Football League Championship]] team. However, the company later denied that it planned to purchase the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-in-takeover-talks-with-investors-updated-1-4594092|title=Leeds United in takeover talks with investors UPDATED|first=Phil|last=Hay|work=[[Yorkshire Evening Post]]|date=May 29, 2012|accessdate=May 29, 2012}}</ref> In 2015 reports emerged that MLSE was investigating taking over the bankrupt [[Parma F.C.]] of Italy's [[Serie A]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teleducato.it/news/17774/forse-la-maple-leaf-sportsentertainment-dietro-il-fondo-canadese-interessato-al-parma.html|title=Forse la Maple Leaf Sports&Entertainment dietro il fondo canadese interessato al Parma|date=March 24, 2015|accessdate=March 25, 2015|publisher=Teleducato}}</ref>\n\nPeddie retired as President and CEO of MLSE at the end of 2011 after 14 years on the job,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/2012/01/08/feschuk_newly_retired_peddie_muses_on_life_after_mlse.html|title=Newly retired Peddie muses on life after MLSE|last=Feschuk|first=Dave|date=January 8, 2012|accessdate=December 17, 2013|work=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.uwindsor.ca/ols/2013/speakers/richard-peddie-2013|title=Richard Peddie|accessdate=December 27, 2013|publisher=[[University of Windsor]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228064221/http://www1.uwindsor.ca/ols/2013/speakers/richard-peddie-2013|archivedate=December 28, 2013}}</ref> having tripled the value of the company.<ref name=isnteverything/> However, he was often criticized for his inability to end the company's long championship drought.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/what-to-make-of-peddies-legacy-with-mlse/|title=What to make of Peddie's legacy with MLSE?|date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=July 3, 2014|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]}}</ref>  The Leafs haven't won a championship since 1967, and at the time the only other major championship won under MLSE ownership was the [[74th Grey Cup]] in 1986 by the Tiger-Cats.  Toronto FC subsequently won in 2017, as did the Raptors in 2019.  (The Argonauts' 2017 Grey Cup win came shortly before MLSE announced its purchase of the team.) Though [[Tom Anselmi]] briefly took over as President,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/2013/07/24/tim_leiweke_shakes_up_mlse_corporate_structure.html | title=Tim Leiweke shakes up MLSE corporate structure|date=July 24, 2013|accessdate=July 3, 2014|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref> he was replaced in June 2013 by high-profile executive Tim Leiweke, who had previously run [[Anschutz Entertainment Group]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/apr/27/sports/la-sp-0427-tim-leiweke-20130427|title=Tim Leiweke tapped to lead Canadian sports conglomerate|last=Elliot|first=Helene|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 27, 2013|accessdate=July 3, 2014}}</ref>  On August 21, 2014 Leiweke announced that he was stepping down, but would remain in his position until a successor was appointed.<ref name=Leiweke2015>{{Cite news|url = http://sports.nationalpost.com/2014/08/21/tim-leiweke-set-to-step-down-from-mlse-to-pursue-other-opportunities/|title = Tim Leiweke set to step down from MLSE to pursue other opportunities|last = Fitz-Gerald|first = Sean|date = August 21, 2014|accessdate = August 21, 2014|newspaper = [[National Post]]|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140822014701/http://sports.nationalpost.com/2014/08/21/tim-leiweke-set-to-step-down-from-mlse-to-pursue-other-opportunities/|archive-date = August 22, 2014|url-status = dead}}</ref>  MLSE announced on October 29, 2015 that [[Michael Friisdahl]] had been hired as Leiweke's successor as President and CEO, and would officially assume his duties in December 2015.<ref name=Friisdahl/>\n\n[[File:BMO Field in 2016.png|thumb|BMO Field in 2016]]\nThe financial success of Toronto FC led MLSE to undertake a major [[BMO Field#Renovation|renovation of BMO Field]].<ref name=bmoexpansion>{{cite web|url=http://bmofield.com/expansion/ |title=BMO Field Expansion |publisher=BMO Field |accessdate=October 11, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141126015028/http://bmofield.com/expansion/ |archivedate=November 26, 2014 }}</ref>  Under a two phase process, the stadium's capacity was increased from 21,566 to 30,000 by May 2015, and a canopy roof covering most permanent seating areas was added and the pitch lengthened to accommodate a [[Canadian football]] field by May 2016.<ref name=cityamend>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2014/mm/bgrd/backgroundfile-70433.pdf|title=Draft Amended and Restated Letter of Intent from Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment Ltd|date=June 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2014|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bmofield.com/venue-info/stadium-history/|title=Stadium History|accessdate=May 6, 2016|publisher=[[BMO Field]]}}</ref> The renovations were originally budgeted to cost $120 million, but ended up at $150 million in total.<ref name=facelift/> In exchange for a $10 million contribution to the project by the City of Toronto, which owns the stadium, they receive rent from MLSE,<ref name=excomrep/><ref name=loi/> while MLSE's management and naming rights agreements for the stadium, which were set to expire in 2027, were extended by 10 years.<ref name=excomrep/><ref name=loi/> The province of Ontario also contributed $10 million to the financing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/mtc/en/2016/05/ontario-partnering-with-city-of-toronto-to-support-bmo-field-expansion.html|title=Ontario Partnering with City of Toronto to Support BMO Field Expansion|date=May 6, 2016|accessdate=May 6, 2016|publisher=Government of Ontario}}</ref>  The City insisted that the renovations allow the Argonauts, who had to vacate their current home the Rogers Centre, to move in.<ref name=bigbucks>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/03/16/mlse-plans-to-spend-big-bucks-to-upgrade-bmo-field|title=MLSE plans to spend big bucks to upgrade BMO Field|last=Larson|first=Kurtis|date=March 16, 2014|accessdate=March 16, 2014|newspaper=Toronto Sun}}</ref><ref name=excomrep/><ref name=makeover/><ref name=citypushing>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2014/03/07/mlse_city_pushing_to_move_argos_to_bmo_field.html|title=MLSE: City pushing to move Argos to BMO Field|date=March 7, 2014|accessdate=March 8, 2014|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref>  The sale of the Argos in May 2015 to a new ownership group consisting of MLSE owners Bell and Tanenbaum was accompanied by an announcement that they had reached an agreement with MLSE to relocate to the stadium for the 2016 season. The Argos contributed $10 million to the conversion of the field to make it CFL compatible, which was matched by MLSE.<ref name=facelift>{{cite web|url=http://www.cp24.com/sports/toronto-fc-news/bmo-field-gets-another-facelift-as-tfc-argos-prepare-to-share-stadium-1.2846586|title=BMO Field gets another facelift as TFC, Argos prepare to share stadium|date=April 5, 2016|accessdate=April 10, 2016|publisher=[[CP24]]}}</ref><ref name=hotseat>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2016/05/07/tfc-groundskeeper-at-bmo-field-on-the-hot-seat.html|title=TFC groundskeeper at BMO Field on the hot seat|first=Laura|last=Armstrong|date=May 7, 2016|accessdate=May 7, 2016|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref name=mystery/> MLSE financed the rest of the project, and was responsible for cost overruns.<ref name=excomrep>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2014/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-67466.pdf|title=Renovation and Expansion of BMO Field|date=March 5, 2014|accessdate=March 15, 2014|publisher=[[City of Toronto government]]}}</ref><ref name=loi/><ref name=makeover>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2014/03/14/mlse_wants_10_million_from_toronto_for_bmo_field_makeover.html|title=MLSE wants $10 million from Toronto for BMO Field makeover|date=March 14, 2014|accessdate=March 16, 2014|newspaper=Toronto Star|last=Tepper|first=Sean}}</ref><ref name=kelly>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/03/14/norm-kelly-wants-city-to-advance-mlse-10-million-for-bmo-improvements|title=Norm Kelly wants city to advance MLSE $10 million for BMO improvements|last=Peat|first=Dan|newspaper=Toronto Sun|date=March 14, 2014|accessdate=March 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/03/12/mayor-rob-fords-pay-freeze-request-goes-to-executive-committee|title=Mayor Rob Ford's pay freeze request goes to executive committee|last=Peat|first=Dan|newspaper=Toronto Sun|date=March 12, 2014|accessdate=March 16, 2014}}</ref>  The renovated stadium can be temporarily expanded to a capacity of roughly 40,000 for big events.<ref name=loi>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2014/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-67468.pdf|title=Proposal for Expansion of Stadium at Exhibition Place|date=March 10, 2014|accessdate=March 15, 2014}}</ref> The Argos purchase agreement called for two Grey Cups to played at BMO Field, the first being the [[104th Grey Cup]] in 2016,<ref name=mystery>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2015/04/24/argos-fate-rests-on-talks-with-mystery-group.html|title=Argos\u2019 fate rests on talks with mystery group|date=April 23, 2015|accessdate=April 23, 2015|first=Jennifer|last=Pagliaro|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2015/04/24/live-leiweke-updates-bmo-field-argos-talks|title=New owner could help Argos land new home|date=April 23, 2015|accessdate=April 23, 2015|first=Jenny|last=Yuen|newspaper=Toronto Sun}}</ref> and the stadium was chosen to host [[rugby sevens]] at the 2015 Pan-Am games and the 2017 [[NHL Centennial Classic]].<ref name=bigbucks/><ref name=excomrep/><ref name=makeover/><ref name=paidback>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2014/01/19/mlses_leiweke_taxpayers_would_be_paid_back_for_bmo_field_expansion.html|title=MLSE's Leiweke: Taxpayers would be paid back for BMO Field expansion|first=Daniel|last=Dale|date=January 19, 2014|accessdate=April 20, 2014|work=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref name=plans>{{cite web|url=http://www.explace.on.ca/database/rte/files/2014_0305%20BMO%20Field%20-%20Public%20Meeting_FINAL.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309031754/http://www.explace.on.ca/database/rte/files/2014_0305%20BMO%20Field%20-%20Public%20Meeting_FINAL.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 9, 2014 |title=BMO Field - Public Meeting |date=March 5, 2014 |accessdate=March 8, 2014 |publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/24-7/winter-classic-could-be-coming-to-toronto/|title=Toronto could host Winter Classic in 2017|date=December 31, 2013|accessdate=January 3, 2014|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, MLSE reached an agreement with the City of Toronto to build a practice facility for the Raptors at Exhibition Place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/08/15/cne-is-forced-to-change-with-the-landscape|title=CNE is forced to change with the landscape|first=Joe|last=Warmington|newspaper=Toronto Sun|date=August 15, 2014|accessdate=August 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/basketball/raptors-exhibition-place-plan-scores-victory-at-toronto-city-hall/article20134057/|title=Raptors\u2019 Exhibition Place plan scores victory at Toronto city hall|first=Elizabeth|last=Church|date=August 20, 2014|accessdate=August 22, 2014|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2014/08/20/executive_committee_approves_plan_for_raptors_training_centre_at_exhibition_place.html|title=Executive committee approves plan for Raptors training centre at Exhibition Place|first=Paul|last=Moloney|date=August 20, 2014|accessdate=August 22, 2014|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/08/25/mayor-rob-ford-fuming-after-raptors-facility-approved|title=Mayor Rob Ford rips Raptors facility approval|date=August 25, 2014|accessdate=September 1, 2014|first=Don|last=Peat|newspaper=Toronto Sun}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/new-raptors-training-centre-approved-by-toronto-council-1.2746164|title=New Raptors training centre approved by Toronto council|date=August 25, 2014|accessdate=September 1, 2014|publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://app.toronto.ca/tmmis/viewAgendaItemHistory.do?item=2014.EX44.3|title=Proposed Basketball Training Centre at Exhibition Place|accessdate=August 16, 2014|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref> MLSE paid the $30 million construction cost, and leases the property from the city for $205,000 annually, subject to reassessments for inflation, for a 20-year term, with two options to extend it by a further 10 years, following which the city would take ownership of the building.<ref name=rapsloi>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2014/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-72809.pdf|title=Appendix A|date=August 2014|accessdate=August 20, 2014|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref><ref name=btcproposal>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2014/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-72768.pdf|title=Proposed Basketball Training Centre at Exhibition Place|date=August 6, 2014|accessdate=August 17, 2014|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref>  Construction was completed in time for the team's hosting of the [[2016 NBA All-Star Game|NBA All-Star Game]] in February 2016.<ref name=announcepract>{{cite news|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/04/16/raptors-close-to-making-announcement-on-new-practice-court|title=Raptors close to making announcement on new practice court|first=Ryan|last=Wolstat|newspaper=Toronto Sun|date=April 16, 2014|accessdate=April 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=MLSEppt>{{cite web |url=http://www.explace.on.ca/database/rte/files/Raptors%20Training-PP-MLSE.pdf|title=High performance basketball development and training centre|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports + Entertainment|accessdate=August 16, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819085621/http://www.explace.on.ca/database/rte/files/Raptors%20Training-PP-MLSE.pdf|archivedate=August 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://iconvenue.com/portfolio/toronto-raptors-practice-facility|title=Toronto Raptors Practice Facility|accessdate=February 9, 2015|publisher=ICON Venue Group}}</ref> Originally known as the Biosteel Centre, in March 2019, the Raptors reached an agreement with [[OVO Sound|OVO]] on a [[naming rights]] deal to brand the facility as the [[OVO Athletic Centre]].<ref>https://www.nba.com/raptors/press-release/raptors-ovo-elevate-partnership-with-ovo-athletic-centre Toronto Raptors press release</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, MLSE confirmed that they were planning on launching a [[professional boxing]] series, featuring 3-4 major fights a year co-promoted with [[Groupe Yvon Michel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2015/02/13/mlse-boxing-venture-on-hold--just-be-gauze|title=MLSE boxing venture on hold ... just be-gauze|date=February 13, 2015|accessdate=February 14, 2015|first=Steve|last=Buffery|newspaper=Toronto Sun}}</ref> Originally planned to start with a [[World Boxing Council]] (WBC) [[light heavyweight]] title fight in April at Ricoh Coliseum, this was delayed due to regulatory restrictions on the amount of gauze that can be used for [[wrist wraps]] in Ontario.  MLSE and Michel joined with [[Lennox Lewis]] to promote a WBC [[light-heavyweight]] title fight in September 2015 at Ricoh Coliseum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/stevenson-stops-karpency-in-third-round-to-defend-wbc-title-for-sixth-time/article26345793/|title=Stevenson stops Karpency in third round to defend WBC title for sixth time|first=Neil|last=Davidson|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=September 12, 2015|accessdate=November 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017 MLSE announced that it had reached an agreement with [[Scotiabank]] to rename the ACC Scotiabank Arena, effective July 1, 2018, for a reported CAD $800 million over 20 years, which would make it the largest such deal in North American sports history.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlse-agrees-to-record-arena-rights-deal-with-scotiabank-1.842133|title=MLSE agrees to record arena rights deal with Scotiabank|first=Rick|last=Westhead|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=August 29, 2017|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref>\n\nMLSE announced in December 2017 that it had agreed to purchase the Toronto Argonauts of the Canadian Football League outright, with the deal finalized on January 19, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfl.ca/2018/01/19/mlse-completes-acquisition-argos-name-manning-president/|title=MLSE completes acquisition of Argos; name Manning as President|date=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Timeline of sports franchise ownership===\n<timeline>\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nImageSize  = width:1050 height:auto barincrement:20\nPeriod     = from:01/01/1930 till:01/07/2020\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal\nPlotArea   = right:42 left:38 bottom:50 top:5\n\nColors = \n         id:line     value:black\n         id:bg       value:white\n\nBarData =\n  bar:NHL       text:\n  bar:OHL       text:\n  bar:ILL       text:\n  bar:AHL       text:\n  bar:AHL2      text:\n  bar:WHL       text:\n  bar:CHL       text:\n  bar:CHL2      text:\n  bar:NLA       text:\n  bar:CFL       text:\n  bar:CFL2      text:\n  bar:NBA       text:\n  bar:MLS       text:\n  bar:USLPRO    text:\n  bar:NBAGL     text:\n\nPlotData =\n  width:15 textcolor:black shift:(3,-4) fontsize:s align:center\n\n  bar:NHL  color:red from:01/07/1931 till:end text:[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-4) text:[[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-4) text:[[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n  bar:OHL  color:red from:01/07/1931 till:01/10/1988 text:[[Toronto Marlboros]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-4) text:[[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-4) text:[[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]]\n  bar:ILL  color:red from:01/01/1932 till:01/11/1932 shift:(42,-4) text:[[Toronto Maple Leafs (ILL)|Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-4) text:[[International Lacrosse League|ILL]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-4) text:[[International Lacrosse League|ILL]]\n  bar:AHL  color:red from:01/07/1956 till:01/07/1966 text:[[Rochester Americans]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-12) text:[[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-12) text:[[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n  bar:AHL2  color:red from:01/07/1978 till:01/07/1982  shift:(-28,-4) text:[[New Brunswick Hawks]]\n  bar:AHL2  color:red from:01/07/1982 till:01/07/1986  shift:(2,-4) text:[[St. Catharines Saints|SC Saints]]\n  bar:AHL2  color:red from:01/07/1986 till:01/07/1991  text:[[Newmarket Saints|N Saints]]\n  bar:AHL2  color:red from:01/07/1991 till:01/07/2005 text:[[St. John's Maple Leafs]]\n  bar:AHL2  color:red from:01/07/2005 till:end text:[[Toronto Marlies]]\n  at:01/07/1982 mark:(line,white)\n  at:01/07/1986 mark:(line,white)\n  at:01/07/1991 mark:(line,white)\n  at:01/07/2005 mark:(line,white)\n  bar:WHL  color:red from:01/07/1963 till:01/07/1964 shift:(-30,-4) text:[[Denver Invaders]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-4) text:[[Western Hockey League (1952\u201374)|WHL]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-4) text:[[Western Hockey League (1952\u201374)|WHL]]\n  bar:WHL  color:red from:01/07/1964 till:01/07/1967 shift:(35,-4) text:[[Victoria Maple Leafs]]\n  at:01/07/1964 mark:(line,white)\n  bar:CHL  color:red from:01/07/1964 till:01/07/1973 text:[[Tulsa Oilers (1964\u201384)|Tulsa Oilers]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-12) text:[[Central Professional Hockey League|CHL]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-12) text:[[Central Professional Hockey League|CHL]]\n  bar:CHL  color:red from:01/07/1973 till:01/07/1976  shift:(40,-4) text:[[Oklahoma City Blazers (1965\u201377)|Oklahoma City Blazers]]\n  at:01/07/1973 mark:(line,white)\n  bar:CHL2  color:red from:01/07/1981 till:01/07/1982 text:[[Cincinnati Tigers (ice hockey)|Cincinnati Tigers]]\n  bar:NLA  color:red from:01/08/1968 till:01/01/1969 text:[[Toronto Maple Leafs (NLA)|Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-4) text:[[National Lacrosse Association|NLA]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-4) text:[[National Lacrosse Association|NLA]]\n  bar:CFL  color:red from:01/01/1978 till:01/01/1989 text:[[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]]\n  bar:CFL2  color:red from:19/01/2018 till:end shift:(-28,-4) text:[[Toronto Argonauts]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,4) text:[[Canadian Football League|CFL]]\n  at:end shift:(20,4) text:[[Canadian Football League|CFL]]\n  bar:NBA  color:red from:01/02/1998 till:end text:[[Toronto Raptors]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-4) text:[[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-4) text:[[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n  bar:MLS  color:red from:01/01/2007 till:end text:[[Toronto FC]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-4) text:[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-4) text:[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n  bar:USLPRO  color:red from:01/05/2015 till:end shift:(-5,-4) text:[[Toronto FC II]]\n  at:start shift:(-15,-4) text:[[USL League One|USL]]\n  at:end shift:(20,-4) text:[[USL League One|USL]]\n  bar:NBAGL  color:red from:01/09/2015 till:end shift:(-5,-4) text:[[Raptors 905]]\n  at:start shift:(-21,-4) text:[[NBA G League|NBAGL]]\n  at:end shift:(26,-4) text:[[NBA G League|NBAGL]]\nLineData =\n  from:start till:end atpos:327\n  from:start till:end atpos:309\n  from:start till:end atpos:290\n  from:start till:end atpos:272\n  from:start till:end atpos:234\n  from:start till:end atpos:216\n  from:start till:end atpos:178\n  from:start till:end atpos:160\n  from:start till:end atpos:122\n  from:start till:end atpos:104\n  from:start till:end atpos:85\n  from:start till:end atpos:66\n  from:start till:end atpos:49\n  at:01/07/1931\nScaleMajor = gridcolor:line unit:year increment:5 start:01/01/1930\n\n</timeline>\n\n==Ownership==\n\n===Conn Smythe===\n[[File:Conn smythe.jpg|thumb|Conn Smythe, founder of Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n\nAlthough Conn Smythe was the face of MLGL from its founding in 1931, he did not acquire majority ownership of the company until 1947, following a power struggle between directors who supported him as president and those who wanted him replaced with [[Frank J. Selke]]. With the help of a $300,000 loan from Toronto stockbroker and MLGL shareholder Percy Gardiner, and the support of minority partner Jack Bickell, Smythe was able to buy 30,000 shares in MLGL from Gardiner<ref name=powerplay>{{cite news|title=Gardens power plays|date=April 3, 1995|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> and installed himself as president on November 19, 1947, replacing Edward Bickle.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baseball's bankroll gone |last=Dunnell|first=Milt|authorlink=Milt Dunnell|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=July 5, 1965}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Hunter |first=Douglas |year=1997 |title=Champions: The Illustrated History of Hockey's Greatest Dynasties. |location=Chicago, Illinois |publisher=Triumph Books |isbn=1-57243-213-6 |page=50}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Smythe is elected Gardens' president|date=November 20, 1947|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]}}</ref>  The loan was paid off in 1960.<ref>{{cite book |title=Centre Ice: The Smythe Family, the Gardens, and the Toronto Maple Leafs Hockey Club |last1=Smythe |first1=Thomas Stafford |last2=Shea |first2=Kevin Shea |publisher=Fenn Publishing Co. |year=2000 |location=Bolton, Ontario, Canada |isbn=1-55168-250-8 |ref=harv|pages=156\u2013167}}</ref>  In November 1961, Smythe sold 45,000 of his 50,000 shares to a three-person partnership formed by his son [[Stafford Smythe]], [[Harold Ballard]], and John Bassett (owner of the ''[[Toronto Telegram]]'' and part-owner of the Canadian Football League's Toronto Argonauts) for $2.3 million.  When combined with their own holdings, this gave the Stafford-Ballard-Bassett partnership 87,000 shares, representing 60% of the company.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|217}}<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=death>{{cite news|title=Ballard's death laid groundwork|date=December 1, 2010|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref name=bassettsells/> Ballard fronted Stafford most of the money for the purchase though a loan he obtained.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=shakeup>{{cite news|title=Ballard president in shakeup at Gardens|last=Beddoes|first=Dick|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=October 21, 1971}}</ref>  According to several sources, Conn thought the sale was only to his son,<ref name=thoughages/> and was furious when he learned that Ballard and Bassett were his partners. He had hoped that Stafford would keep MLGL for his son, Tommy.<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|217\u2013218}} However, it is unlikely that Stafford could have raised the millions needed for the deal on his own. Stafford became president of MLGL and governor of the Maple Leafs, with Ballard becoming executive vice president and Bassett chairman of the board.<ref name=powerplay/>\n\n===Harold Ballard, John Bassett, and Stafford Smythe===\nIn March 1966, Conn sold his remaining MLGL shares and resigned from the board of directors after a [[Muhammad Ali]] boxing match was scheduled for MLG. He found Ali's refusal to serve in the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] during the [[Vietnam War]] to be offensive,<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|232}} and said that by accepting the fight, MLGL owners had \"put cash ahead of class.\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Cash rated over class' Conn quits |author=McKee, Ken |work=Toronto Star |date=March 8, 1966}}</ref>  Within three years under the new owners, profits had tripled to just under $1 million. Ballard negotiated lucrative deals to place advertising throughout the building, and greatly increased the number of seats in the arena.<ref>''Ballard: A Portrait of Canada's Most Controversial Sports Figure'', William Houston, Summerhill Press, 1984, p. 60.</ref>\n\nFollowing a [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] raid at MLG in 1968, Stafford was charged with income tax evasion, and he and Ballard were accused of illegally taking money from MLGL to pay for home renovations and other personal expenses. Just before the charges were laid, Bassett argued to the board of directors that Stafford and Ballard should be removed from their posts. On June 26, 1969, following an 8\u20137 vote of the board, Stafford and Ballard were both fired, and Bassett was appointed president of MLGL. However, Bassett did not force Stafford and Ballard to sell their shares, and both men remained on the board.  This proved to be a serious strategic blunder; Stafford was the largest single shareholder in MLGL, and he and Ballard controlled almost half the company's stock between them.  They were thus able to regain control of the board in 1970, and Stafford was once again appointed president.<ref name=powerplay/>  Facing an untenable situation, Bassett sold the 196,200 MLGL shares he controlled to Stafford and Ballard in September 1971 for $5.4 million, which he used to buy out his partners in the Argonauts.<ref name=death/><ref name=bassettsells>{{cite news|title=Bassett sells Gardens stock, buys control of Argos|first=Dick|last=Beddoes|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|date=September 2, 1971|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=shakeup/> Combined with their 306,295 jointly controlled shares, the transaction gave the Stafford-Ballard partnership 78% of the stock.<ref name=bassettsells/><ref name=shakeup/>  Stafford died in October 1971 of a bleeding ulcer at only 50 years of age, just before his trial was scheduled to begin.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/> Under the terms of Stafford's will, of which Ballard was an [[executor]],<ref name=repeats>{{cite news|title=History repeats itself&nbsp;... almost|date=March 22, 1999|last=Tedesco|first=Theresa|newspaper=[[National Post]]}}</ref> each partner was allowed to buy the other's shares upon their death. Stafford's brother and son tried to keep the shares within the family,<ref>{{cite news|title=MLG control at stake: Smythe bid for Ballard stock rejected|first=Dick|last=Beddoes|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|date=January 5, 1972|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> but in February 1972 Ballard bought all 251,545 of Stafford's shares for $7.5 million, valuing the company at $22 million.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=death/><ref name=rinkrat/><ref name=buyscontrol/><ref name=gardensprez/> Stafford's brother Hugh also sold his shares to Ballard, ending the Smythe family's 45-year involvement in the company. Combined with Ballard's 262,162 shares, this gave him majority ownership of about 70%.<ref name=rinkrat>{{cite news|title=Harrold Ballard: From rink rat to Gardens' boss|date=February 5, 1972|newspaper=Toronto Star|last=Orr|first=Frank}}</ref><ref name=buyscontrol>{{cite news|title=Ballard buys Gardens control for $7,546,350|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=February 4, 1972|first=Milt|last=Dunnell|authorlink=Milt Dunnell}}</ref><ref name=gardensprez>{{cite news|title=Gardens' president Harold Ballard to buy Smythe shares|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=February 5, 1972|last=Lutsky|first=Irvin}}</ref>  Six months later, Ballard was convicted of 47 charges, including fraud and theft of money and goods, and sentenced to three years in a federal penitentiary.<ref name=howherold/><ref name=MLH70>{{cite web|url=http://mapleleafs.ice.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=42187|title=Maple Leafs History - 1970s|publisher=Maple Leafs Sports & Entertainment|accessdate=June 27, 2017}}</ref>{{sfn|Shea|Wilson|2016|p=212}}\n\n===Harold Ballard===\nIn 1966, Ballard set up a family [[holding company]] named Harold E. Ballard Ltd. (HEBL) for his assets, including his shares in MLGL, as part of an [[estate freeze]].<ref name=assulttrial>{{cite news|title=Son of a Ballard: Assault trial a rehearsal for family fight for fortune|date=September 23, 1989|last=McDonald|first=Archie|newspaper=[[Vancouver Sun]]}}</ref><ref name=follies>{{cite news|title=The Maple Leaf Follies: Who needs hockey? With a team of lawyers fighting for ambitious corporations and the feuding Ballard clan, nothing can compare with the faceoff for Maple Leaf Gardens|newspaper=[[Financial Post]]|date=October 1, 1991|last=Johnson|first=Arthur}}</ref> Ballard distributed 103 [[common shares]] in HEBL, with his three children (Bill, Harold Jr., and Mary Elizabeth) each receiving 34 which were held in [[Trust law|trust]], and his wife Dorothy receiving 1, which Harold would inherit upon her death three years later.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=assulttrial/><ref name=familyaffair>{{cite news|title=Ballard money a family affair Daughter gets $15.5 million as Harold buys her shares|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=January 25, 1989}}</ref><ref name=missdeadline/> Harold retained 308,000 [[preferred shares]] in HEBL.<ref name=follies/><ref name=faceoffbrewing>{{cite news|title=Faceoff brewing over Ballard's fortune|last=Hurst|first=Lynda|newspaper=[[Montreal Gazette]]|date=February 25, 1990}}</ref>  While the equity of the company was vested in the common stock, both common and preferred shares each received a single vote, ensuring that Harold retained control of the company.<ref name=follies/>\n\nAfter getting into financial difficulty, Ballard reached an agreement in November 1980 with [[Molson Brewery]] (who at the time owned the Montreal Canadiens) for the company to cover his debt financing charges on a loan of $8.8 million for 10 years in exchange for an option to purchase a 19.9% block of shares in MLGL from HEBL and a right of first refusal on the rest of HEBL's shares.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=molsonnets/><ref name=molsonpurchase/>  The NHL did not learn of the deal until the late 1980s.<ref name=molsonnets/> In 1982, he offered to sell the company for $50 million, with the arena alone reportedly valued at $11 million, though a stockholders' report the following year placed the value of MLGL at $23.5 million.<ref name=bigmoney/><ref name=price/> When Harold transferred ownership of his personal real estate holdings, which were valued at $2.52 million, to HEBL in January 1989, he acquired 4 newly issued common shares in the company plus a promise of a further $896,472 rather than cash.<ref name=howherold/><ref name=follies/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> Mary Elizabeth sold her stake in HEBL to her father for $15.5 million in January 1989,<ref name=familyaffair/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> after originally having a deal to sell the stake to Don Giffin,<ref name=follies/> while Harold Jr. sold his back to HEBL for $21 million in June of the same year.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=follies/><ref name=missdeadline/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> Harold secured a loan from Molson for the full amount of his buyout of Mary Elizabeth, using the 34 acquired shares in HEBL as security.<ref name=missdeadline>{{cite news|title=Harold E. Ballard Ltd. misses Molson loan deadline|date=January 3, 1991|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]}}</ref> Harold Jr.'s shares were subsequently retired.<ref name=faceoffbrewing/> Bill sued his father for $170 million over HEBL's acquisition of Harold Jr.'s stake,<ref name=assulttrial/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> claiming that he and partner [[Michael Cohl]] had acquired a right of first refusal to purchase the shares for $20 million that February.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> Shortly thereafter, HEBL issued Harold 32 common shares and $125,216 in exchange for ownership of his 350,200 personally held MLGL shares and $125,000.<ref name=howherold/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> Two more new common shares would be granted to Harold to repay the $911,000 debt HEBL owed him from his two transactions with the company.<ref name=howherold/> This gave Harold, who feared that Bill was positioning himself to take over the holding company, control of HEBL.<ref name=powerplay/> Harold did not want his bickering children to inherit MLGL because he feared they would destroy it.<ref name=howherold>{{cite news|title=How Harold Ballard got the Gardens|last=Tyler|first= Tracey|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=November 25, 1990}}</ref>\n\nThough Ballard ran up significant amounts of personal debt during his ownership of MLGL, he made the company very profitable, so much so that MLG became known as the \"Cashbox on Carlton Street,\" referring to the address of the arena.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4tlXuNrwjsYC&pg=PT416&lpg=PT416|title=The Lives of Conn Smythe|first=Kelly|last=McParland|year=2011|publisher=[[Random House]]}}</ref> Upon Harold's death on April 11, 1990,<ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/>{{sfn|Shea|Wilson|2016|p=275}} most of his estate, which was worth less than $50 million, was left to charitable organizations.<ref name=deepdebt/> The executors of Harold's will were supermarket tycoon [[Steve Stavro]], Giffin, and [[Donald Crump]]. In November 1990 Molson exercised their option on 19.9% of the company, paying $10,000 for 735,575 of HEBL's MLGL shares, which at the time were valued at $20 million.<ref name=molsonnets/> Due to restrictions against cross-ownership in the NHL, the company set up a trust to hold their stake,<ref name=molsonnets>{{cite news|title=Molson nets share of Maple Leafs|date=November 2, 1990|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]}}</ref><ref name=molsonpurchase>{{cite news|title=Molson to purchase $20 million in Gardens shares for $10,000|newspaper=[[Kitchener-Waterloo Record]]|date=November 1, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Molson puts shares of Gardens in trust|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=November 1, 1990}}</ref> and the league instructed them to sell the shares within an \"adequate amount of time.\"<ref name=missdeadline/><ref name=cantpay/><ref name=Molsondeal/> Shortly after the estate, which had limited income due to HEBL still owing [[Toronto-Dominion Bank]] $15.8 million on its loan to acquire Harold Jr's HEBL stock, missed a January 1991 deadline to repay its $20 million loan (including interest) from Molson,<ref name=missdeadline/><ref name=cantpay>{{cite news|title=TD payments left Ballard with no cash for Molson|date=January 4, 1991|newspaper=Toronto Star|last=Van Alphen|first=Tony}}</ref> Stavro personally loaned the estate the funds to pay off the debt,<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=death/><ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Ballard loses in court to Stavro|newspaper=[[Windsor Star]]|date=April 13, 1991}}</ref> and in exchange, he received an option to purchase the estate's HEBL shares before January 1996.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=death/><ref name=deepdebt>{{cite news|title=Ballard's estate deeper in debt despite Leafs season|date=June 25, 1993|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]}}</ref><ref name=deepdebt/><ref name=Molsondeal/> Bill challenged the transaction, but it was approved by the court.<ref name=billjoins/> In early 1991, Molson offered to buy the estate's shares for $40 each.<ref name=billjoins/> In September 1991, Bill sold his HEBL stock to his father's estate for $21 million, giving it ownership of the entire company.<ref name=Molsondeal>{{cite news|title=Molson deal gives Stavro total control of Gardens|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=September 24, 1991}}</ref> Shortly thereafter it was announced that Stavro had reached a deal with Molson on an option to purchase their MLGL shares until April 1994 and for Molson to waive their option on the estate's shares.<ref name=deepdebt/><ref name=Molsondeal/>\n\n===Steve Stavro===\n{{chart top|width=100%|Ownership structure prior to privatization in 1998}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart| | | | | MLGL | | | | |MLGL=MLGL}}\n{{chart| | |,|-|-|^|.| | | | }}\n{{chart| | PUBLIC | | MLGV | | | | PUBLIC=Outstanding public stock|MLGV=MLGV}}\n{{chart| | | | | |,|^|-|-|.| }}\n{{chart| | | | | MLGH | | OTPP |MLGH=MLGH<br/>51%|OTPP=OTPP<br/>49%}}\n{{chart| |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.| }}\n{{chart| TD | | SS | | KILMER | TD=TD Bank<br/>20%|SS=Steve Stavro<br/>55%|KILMER=Kilmer Sports<br/>25%}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | |!| }}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | LT | LT=Larry Tanenbaum<br/>100%}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\nStavro founded MLG Ventures (MLGV) in March 1994 with partners Toronto\u2014Dominion Bank and [[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]].<ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=osc>{{cite web|url=https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/en/10823.htm|title=In the matter of the Securities Act, R.S.O. 1990, Chapter S.5|publisher=[[Ontario Securities Commission]]|accessdate=March 8, 2014}}</ref>  MLG Holdings Ltd. (MLGH), of which Stavro owned 80% and TD Bank controlled the remaining 20%, held a 51% ownership stake in MLGV, with the remaining 49% owned by Teachers'.<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=rubber/><ref name=bigwins>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2007/1126/103.html|title=Big Wins - At the Bank|date=November 26, 2007|accessdate=March 16, 2014|work=[[Forbes]]|first=Christina|last=Settimi}}</ref>  The following month MLGV announced that they had reached an agreement to purchase the 60.3% of MLGL held by Harold's estate for $34 a share or $75 million total, valuing the company at $125 million.<ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=faceoff>{{cite news|title=The face-off at Maple Leaf Gardens|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=August 13, 1994}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Date-by-Date Story of Gardens Takeover Fight|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/512622201.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+11%2C+1994&author=&pub=The+Spectator&edition=&startpage=C.15&desc=Date-by-date+story+of+Gardens+takeover+fight|newspaper=[[The Hamilton Spectator]]|date=November 11, 1994|page=C15}}</ref><ref name=slow>{{cite news|title=Slow speed of probe into sale angers Gardens shareholders|date=August 4, 1994|newspaper=Toronto Star|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen}}</ref><ref name=settotake/> The estate still owned Stavro $23 million at the time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stavro's Gardens bid enjoys the rink to itself|date=April 11, 1994|newspaper=Toronto Star|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen}}</ref>  Molson also sold its 19.9% of MLGL to MLGV in April 1994 for $25 million.<ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=faceoff/><ref name=settotake/> Larry Tanenbaum's company Kilmer Sports purchased a 25% share of MLGH from Stavro in 1996 for a reported $21 million.<ref name=death/><ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=rubber/><ref name=stavrosells>{{cite news|title=Stavro sells off part of Gardens NHL expected to give him fast nod for deal with pal|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=June 21, 1996}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/news/larrytanenbaum_bio.html|title=Larry Tanenbaum|accessdate=March 8, 2014|publisher=[[Toronto Raptors]]}}</ref>\n\nMLGV subsequently purchased all the remaining shares and took MLGL private in 1998, after acquiring more than the 90% of stock necessary to force objecting shareholders out,<ref name=rubber>{{cite news|title=Stavro set to take Gardens private Meeting seen as a 'rubber stamp'|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=August 6, 1996}}</ref><ref name=slow/><ref name=settotake>{{cite news|title=Stavro set to take Gardens private|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=May 3, 1994}}</ref> and MLGL and MLGV amalgamated.<ref name=death/><ref name=osc/>  The purchase was the subject of an [[Ontario Securities Commission]] (OSC) review, due to allegations that MLGV had engaged in [[insider trading]] by failing to disclose that broadcast revenue was expected to substantially increase,<ref name=isnteverything/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=osc/><ref name=quietexit/><ref name=eyeweekly>{{cite web|url=http://contests.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_04.01.99/rolling/times.php|title=Signs of the times|date=April 1, 1999|accessdate=March 16, 2014|work=[[Eye Weekly]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317081458/http://contests.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_04.01.99/rolling/times.php|archivedate=March 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/1999/03/23/Franchises/STAVRO-FOUND-TO-HAVE-MISLED-SHAREHOLDERS-DURING-94-BID.aspx?hl=NHL&sc=0|title=Stavro found to have misled shareholders during '94 bid|date=March 23, 1999|accessdate=March 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=irregular/> and a $50 million lawsuit from Bill who claimed that Stavro and others devalued MLGL and withheld information relevant to the value of the company prior to the sale of his stock.<ref name=billjoins>{{cite news|title=Bill Ballard joins Gardens battle Files lawsuit seeking return of his shares|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=February 23, 1996}}</ref>  Ontario's Office of the Public Trustee, which was charged with representing the charities named by Harold's will as beneficiaries, argued that Stavro had a conflict of interest as both executor of the will and buyer and had not paid market value because there was no public bidding process for the shares.<ref name=repeats/><ref name=billjoins/><ref name=faceoff/><ref name=settotake/><ref name=quietexit/>  Several minority owners, including [[Harry Ornest]], who held 3.5% of the company, and [[Jim Devellano]] also objected to MLGV's attempts to take the company private without an auction.<ref name=repeats/><ref name=faceoff/><ref name=slow/>  Stavro and his partners in MLGV reached a settlement in 1996 to pay an additional $23.5 million plus interest to the charities as well as $2.5 million to the minority shareholders who had sued,<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=rubber/><ref name=quietexit/> clearing the way for them to become the majority owner of MLGL.  They also settled with the OSC in 1999 for $1.6 million, which included a fine and costs.<ref name=quietexit>{{cite web|url=http://www.canoe.ca/NewsStand/LondonFreePress/Sports/2003/06/26/119735.html|title= A quiet exit for Maple Leafs boss|date=June 26, 2003|accessdate=March 16, 2014|newspaper=[[The London Free Press]]|first=Lance|last=Hornby}}</ref><ref name=eyeweekly/><ref name=irregular>{{cite web|url=http://investorvoice.ca/PI/006.html|title= An irregular regulator|first=Karen|last=Howlett|date=October 20, 1999|accessdate=March 16, 2014|newspaper=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>  Teachers' invested $44.3 million and TD $9.75 million in the deal.<ref name=otppgraphic>{{cite web|url=http://www.otpp.com/documents/10179/20932/MLSE+Infographic/d8ea6bed-5a05-4879-8b29-9e400488a251|title=Play-by-play|accessdate=March 9, 2014|year=2012|publisher=[[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]]}}</ref><ref name=longtime/>\n\nFollowing the merger, the ownership structure of the now defunct MLGV was retained by MLGL.  MLGH was the majority owner of MLGL, holding 51% of the company.  It in turn was controlled by Stavro (55%), with minority shareholders Tanenbaum (25%) and TD Capital Group (20%).<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=rubber/><ref name=stavrosells/> The remaining 49% of MLGL was owned by Teachers'.<ref name=rubber/><ref name=stavrosells/><ref name=longtime/><ref name=longtime>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/2011/05/11/td-decision-to-divest-mlse-interest-long-time-coming/|title=How TD became a MVP in the MLSE sale|last=Tedesco|first=Theresa|date=May 11, 2011|accessdate=March 8, 2014|newspaper=[[National Post]]}}</ref>  This tiered ownership structure gave Stavro effective control of MLGL with only a net 29% stake of the company.<ref name=longtime/>  Teachers' invested a further $50 million in the company in the form of a [[convertible bond]] in 1998 to finance the purchase of the Raptors and ACC and complete construction of the arena.<ref name=isnteverything>{{cite news | last = Vardi | first = Nathan | title = Winning Isn't Everything | url = https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2007/1126/096.html#selection-653.27-653.98 | work = Forbes | date = November 16, 2007 | accessdate = November 16, 2007}}</ref><ref name=bigwins/>\n\n===Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan===\nIn 2003 an agreement was reached to restructure the company with Stavro selling his stake to [[Bell Globemedia]] for a reported $120\u2013150-million after debt repayments,<ref name=longtime/> the other partners converting their debts into equity, and each partner getting a direct ownership stake in the newly renamed MLSE, with MLGH being dissolved.<ref name=isnteverything/><ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=longtime/> This left Teachers' as the controlling majority owners of MLSE with 58.4%, and minority partners Bell Globemedia (15.4%), TD Capital with (13.5%) and Tanenbaum, who took over as non-executive chairman, with 13%.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=isnteverything/><ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=longtime/>  Each owner of MLSE had a right of first refusal on any shares sold, in proportion to their ownership share.<ref name=longtime/><ref name=snapup/>  The same year MLSE was internally valued at over $1 billion by Teachers' in its annual report.  In 2008 the Toronto Star reported that a valuation commissioned by the company concluded that the company was worth US$1.5 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2008/01/05/toronto_billionaire_eyes_leafs_empire.html|title=Toronto billionaire eyes Leafs empire|date=January 5, 2008|accessdate=January 11, 2014|work=Toronto Star|last=Westhead|first=Rick}}</ref>  On December 5, 2008 CTVglobemedia (the renamed Bell Globemedia) sold half of its 15.4% stake to Tanenbaum for $100 million, making Tanenbaum the second-largest stakeholder with 20.7%.<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=longtime/>  The transaction valued the company at $1.2 billion.  On August 20, 2009 Teachers' announced that it had agreed to purchase the remaining 7.7% stake in MLSE owned by CTVglobemedia, bumping their stake to 66%.<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=longtime/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2009/08/20/teachers_pension_plan_boosting_stake_in_mlse.html|title=Teachers' Pension Plan boosting stake in MLSE|date=August 20, 2009|accessdate=April 5, 2014|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref>\n\n===Bell and Rogers===\nIn December 2010 it was reported that Rogers Communications, owner of the Toronto Blue Jays, was in negotiations to purchase the Teachers' 66% stake in MLSE, with the asking price set at $1.3 billion,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/hockey/2010/12/01/rogers_in_13b_talks_to_buy_majority_stake_in_leafs_empire.html|title=Rogers in $1.3B talks to buy majority stake in Leafs empire|date=December 1, 2010|accessdate=April 5, 2014|last1=Cribb|first1=Robert|last2=Van Alphen|first2=Tony|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/rogers-leafs-sale/|title=Report: Rogers bids $1.3 billion for MLSE|date=December 1, 2010|accessdate=April 5, 2014|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]}}</ref> and in March 2011 Teachers' confirmed that their share in the company was up for sale.<ref name=snapup/><ref name=notforsale>{{cite web|url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2011/11/25/mlse-not-for-sale-teachers/|title=MLSE no longer for sale: Teachers' Pension Plan|first=Sean|last=Fitz-Gerald|date=November 25, 2011|accessdate=March 9, 2014|newspaper=[[National Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140310004314/http://sports.nationalpost.com/2011/11/25/mlse-not-for-sale-teachers/|archive-date=March 10, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Tanenbaum's right of first refusal on the shares gave him control over any sale by Teachers'.<ref name=longtime/><ref name=snapup/> In May 2011 Teachers' announced that they had reached an agreement to purchase TD Capital's 13.5% ownership share, giving them 79.5% of the company and leaving Tanenbaum as the only minority partner with 20.5%, simplifying a sale of their shares.<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=snapup>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/teachers-snaps-up-tds-maple-leaf-sports-stake/article591372/|title= Teachers snaps up TD's Maple Leaf Sports stake|date=May 10, 2011|accessdate=March 9, 2014|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|last=Perkins|first=Tara|location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011 Teachers' announced that they were taking the company off the market.<ref name=notforsale/> However, only a couple of weeks later, on December 9, 2011, Teachers' announced the sale of its entire stake in MLSE to a partnership between [[BCE Inc.]] and Rogers Communications, in a deal valued at [[Canadian dollar|$]]1.32 billion,<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=sportsempire>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/12/09/us-mapleleaf-rogers-bce-idUSTRE7B80VN20111209|title=Toronto sports empire sold to Rogers and BCE|first=Euan|last=Rocha|date=December 9, 2011|accessdate=March 16, 2014|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> giving the company an [[equity value]] of $1.66 billion and an [[enterprise value]] of $2 billion<ref name=value>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/rogers-bce-on-verge-of-deal-for-mlse/article4247367/|title= Rogers, BCE on verge of deal for MLSE|last1=Robertson|first1=Grant|last2=Perkins|first2=Tara|work=The Globe and Mail|date=December 8, 2011|accessdate=April 6, 2014|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlse.com/news/otppmlse_120911.aspx|title=OTPP announces sale of MLSE majority interest|date=September 9, 2011|accessdate=January 6, 2014|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106211058/http://www.mlse.com/news/otppmlse_120911.aspx|archive-date=January 6, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> due to the assumption of their share of MLSE's $372 million in debt and $66 million in leases.<ref name=\"crtc-mlse2\"/>  As part of the deal, Tanenbaum increased his stake in the company by 5%, valued at $109 million, to 25% to secure his approval.<ref name=sportsempire/><ref name=\"crtc-mlse2\"/><ref name=tsn-mlsepurchase>{{cite web|url=http://www2.tsn.ca/toronto/story/?id=382315|title=BCE and Rogers team up to buy 75 percent of MLSE|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]|date=December 10, 2011|accessdate=April 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otpp.com/news/article/-/article/21045|title=Teachers' completes $1.32-billion sale of MLSE|date=August 22, 2012|accessdate=December 27, 2013|publisher=[[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]]}}</ref> The deal required the approval of Canada's [[Competition Bureau]], the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission (with regards to MLSE's TV channels), as well as the NHL, the AHL, the NBA, and MLS (with regards to each of MLSE's main sports franchises).\n\nThe Competition Bureau announced in May 2012 that it would not challenge the transaction, but that it will \"actively review\" the situation in light of \"serious concerns\" expressed by various parties, reserving the right to take action at a later date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.competitionbureau.gc.ca/eic/site/cb-bc.nsf/eng/03464.html|title=Competition Bureau Statement on Bell and Rogers' Acquisition of Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment|author=[[Competition Bureau]]|date=May 2, 2012|accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref> The NHL Board of Governors approved the sale at a meeting in Las Vegas on June 19, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.tsn.ca/toronto/story/?id=398779|title=NHL board approves sale of MLSE to BCE-Rogers|date=June 20, 2012|accessdate=January 11, 2014|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref> The final approval, that of the CRTC, was granted on August 16, with the commission noting that it only had jurisdiction over the TV channels owned by MLSE (the transfer of ownership from MLSE to Bell, Rogers and Kilmer directly, it decided, posed no major concerns), and not the broadcast rights associated with MLSE's teams.<ref name=\"crtc-mlse2\"/><ref name=\"crtc-mlse\">{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2012/2012-443.htm|title=Broadcasting Decision CRTC 2012-443|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]|date=August 16, 2012|accessdate=August 25, 2012}}</ref> The transaction closed on August 22, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/bell-rogers-now-official-owners-of-mlse/article4493958/|title=Bell, Rogers now official owners of MLSE|work=The Globe and Mail|date=August 22, 2012|accessdate=August 25, 2012|location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\n{{chart top|width=100%|Ownership structure since August 2012 under Rogers and Bell}}\n{{chart/start|align=center|}}\n{{chart| | | | |MLSE | | | | |MLSE=MLSE<br/>100%}}\n{{chart| | | |,|-|^|-|-|-|.| }}\n{{chart| | | ROGBELL | | | | KILMER | ROGBELL=Rogers/Bell holding company<br/>75%|KILMER=Kilmer Sports<br/>25%}}\n{{chart| |,|-|^|-|.| | | |!| }}\n{{chart| ROGERS | | BELL | | LT | ROGERS=Rogers Communications<br/>50%|BELL=Bell holding company<br/>50%|LT=Larry Tanenbaum<br/>100%}}\n{{chart| | | |,|-|^|-|.| | | }}\n{{chart| | | BCE | | BMT | | | BCE=BCE Inc.<br/>74.67%|BMT=BCE Master Trust Fund<br/>25.33%}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\nAs part of the sale, two [[numbered companies]] were created to jointly hold stock.  Following the restructuring, the ownership hierarchy of MLSE was:<ref name=\"crtc-mlse\" />\n* 8047286 Canada Inc. (Rogers/Bell [[joint venture|joint]] holding company) \u2013 75%\n** [[Rogers Communications]] \u2013 50% (net ownership 37.5%)\n** 7680147 Canada Inc. (Bell holding company) \u2013 50%\n*** [[BCE Inc.]] \u2013 74.67% (net ownership 28%)\n*** BCE Master Trust Fund (investment fund of Bell's pension plan) \u2013 25.33% (net ownership 9.5%)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/892971/bell-acquires-ownership-position-in-maple-leaf-sports-and-entertainment-mlse|title=Bell acquires ownership position in Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment - MLSE|author=[[BCE Inc.]]|date=December 9, 2011|accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n* Kilmer Sports (holding company of [[Larry Tanenbaum]]) \u2013 25%\n\nThis ownership structure ensures that, at the shareholder level, Rogers and Bell vote their overall 75% interest in the company together and thus decisions on the management of the company must be made by consensus of the two. (If Rogers and Bell owned their interests directly, either Rogers or Bell could be overruled by its competitor in combination with Tanenbaum.) As such, Rogers and Bell have agreed that their previously four of six (now six of eight) directors on the MLSE board will always vote together, and thus that any disagreements between the two companies will be settled privately without the involvement of Tanenbaum.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/leafs-beat/mlse-board-expected-to-undergo-major-change-after-sale-is-finalized/article4426208/|title=MLSE board expected to undergo major change after sale is finalized|first=David|last=Shoalts|work=The Globe and Mail|date=July 18, 2012|accessdate=March 6, 2013|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref name=board />  Bell has indicated that the involvement of Bell's pension fund is, at least in part, intended to ensure Bell can retain its existing 18% interest in the Montreal Canadiens, as NHL rules prevent any shareholder that owns more than 30% of a team from holding an ownership position in any other team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/bell-to-keep-canadiens-stake-1.997652|title=Bell to keep Canadiens stake|author=[[The Canadian Press]]|work=[[CBC.ca]]|date=December 9, 2011|accessdate=December 10, 2011}}</ref> As a result of Bell and Rogers having co-ownership in MLSE, the regional broadcasts of Maple Leafs and Toronto FC games are split between Bell's TSN and Rogers' Sportsnet; the national rights to the Raptors and the NBA overall are also split between TSN and Sportsnet.\n\nIn 2015 MLSE initiated a corporate restructuring, with the plan to transfer most of its assets to another holding company, named \"Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Partnership\" (MLSEP), which would be wholly owned, directly and indirectly, by MLSE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2015/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-83489.pdf|title=Consent to Assignment of Agreements with Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Ltd (\"MLSEL\")|date=September 2, 2015|accessdate=October 1, 2015|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref>\n\n==Assets==\n\n===Sports teams===\n* [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] ([[National Hockey League]]) \u2013 Valued at US$1.50 billion in 2019, 2nd in the NHL<ref name=forbestml>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/teams/toronto-maple-leafs/|title=Toronto Maple Leafs|work=Forbes|publisher=Forbes Media LLC.|year=2017|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n** [[Toronto Marlies]] ([[American Hockey League]])\n* [[Toronto Raptors]]  ([[National Basketball Association]]) \u2013 Valued at US$2.1 billion in 2020, 10th in the NBA<ref name=forbestr>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/teams/toronto-raptors/|title=Toronto Raptors|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n** [[Raptors 905]] ([[NBA G League]])\n** Raptors Uprising GC ([[NBA 2K League]])\n* [[Toronto FC]] ([[Major League Soccer]]) \u2013 Valued at US$395 million in 2019, 5th in MLS<ref name=forbesmls>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrissmith/2019/11/04/major-league-soccers-most-valuable-teams-2019-atlanta-stays-on-top-as-expansion-fees-sale-prices-surge/#72d3b3b051b5|title=Major League Soccer\u2019s Most Valuable Teams 2019: Atlanta Stays On Top As Expansion Fees, Sale Prices Surge|work=[[Forbes]]|date=November 4, 2019|accessdate=November 6, 2019|last=Smith|first=Chris}}</ref>\n** [[Toronto FC II]] ([[USL League One]])\n** [[Toronto FC III]] ([[U.S. Soccer Development Academy]])\n** Toronto FC eSports ([[eMLS Cup]])\n* [[Toronto Argonauts]] ([[Canadian Football League]])\n\n{{side box|metadate=no|position=left|above='''Valuations of MLSE franchises since 1991<br>(in US dollars)'''|abovestyle=text-align:center\n|text=\n{{Graph:Chart\n| width = 700\n| height = 350\n| xAxisTitle = Year valuation reported<!--Note that the NBA reporting date was switched from December->January and this seems to have been applied retroactively by Forbes-->\n| x = 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1995, 1996, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019, 2020\n| yAxisTitle = Valuation (USD)\n| yAxisFormat = $,.10\n| colors = blue, red, green\n| y1 = 45000000, 54000000, 63000000, 77000000, 90000000, 96000000, 105000000, 119000000, 151000000, 203000000, 216000000, 241000000, 263000000, 280000000, ,332000000, 413000000, 448000000, 470000000, 505000000, 521000000, 1000000000, 1150000000, 1300000000, 1150000000, 1100000000, 1400000000, 1450000000, 1500000000\n| y2 = {{repeat|6| ,}} 138000000, ,121000000, 138000000, 148000000, 172000000, 217000000, 249000000, 297000000, 278000000, 315000000, 373000000, 400000000, 386000000, 399000000, 382000000, 405000000, 520000000, 920000000, 980000000, 1125000000, 1400000000, 1675000000, 2100000000\n| y3 = {{repeat|17| ,}} 44000000 {{repeat|5| ,}} 121000000, , 175000000, 245000000, 280000000, 290000000, 395000000\n| showSymbols = \n}}\n|below=\n1991\u20131997: [[Financial World]]<ref>Data from the following annual reports:\n* {{Cite journal|title=Secrets of the front office: What America's pro teams are worth|date=July 9, 1991|last1=Baldo|first1=Anthony|last2=Biesada|first2=Alexandra|last3=Hackney|first3=Holt|last4=Ozanian|first4=Michael K|last5=Taub|first5=Stephen|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=28}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=Big leagues, bad business|date=July 7, 1992|last1=Ozanian|first1=Michael K|last2=Taub|first2=Stephen|last3=Morris|first3=Kathleen|last4=Fink|first4=Ronald|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=34}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=Foul ball|date=May 25, 1993|last1=Ozanian|first1=Michael K|last2=Taub|first2=Stephen|last3=Fink|first3=Ronald|last4=Kimelman|first4=John|last5=Reingold|first5=Jennifer|last6=Starr|first6=Jason|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=50}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=The $11 billion pastime: Why sports franchise values are soaring even as team profits fall|date=May 10, 1994|last1=Ozanian|first1=Michael K|last2=Fink|first2=Ronald|last3=Kimelman|first3=John|last4=Reingold|first4=Jennifer|last5=Osterland|first5=Andrew|last6=Starr|first6=Jason|last7=Grabarek|first7=Brooke|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=50}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=Suite deals: Why new stadiums are shaking up the pecking order of sports franchises|date=May 9, 1995|last1=Ozanian|first1=Michael K|last2=Atre|first2=Tushar|last3=Fink|first3=Ronald|last4=Reingold|first4=Jennifer|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=42}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=The high-stakes game of team ownership|date=May 20, 1996|last1=Atre|first1=Tushar|last2=Auns|first2=Kristine|last3=Badenhausen|first3=Kurt|last4=McAuliffe|first4=Kevin|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=49}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=More than a game: An in-depth look at the raging bull market in sports franchises|date=June 17, 1997|last1=Badenhausen|first1=Kurt|last2=Nikolov|first2=Christopher|magazine=[[Financial World]]|pages=40}}</ref>{{spaces|2|em}}1998\u2013present: [[Forbes]]\n\n{{legend inline|blue|Maple Leafs<ref name=forbestml/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/31/biz_07nhl_Toronto-Maple-Leafs_312012.html|title=#1 Toronto Maple Leafs|date=November 8, 2007|accessdate=May 8, 2014|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>}}{{spaces|2|em}}{{legend inline|red|Raptors<ref name=forbestr/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/32/biz_07nba_Toronto-Raptors_321933.html|title=#14 Toronto Raptors|date=December 6, 2007|accessdate=May 8, 2014|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>}}{{spaces|2|em}}{{legend inline|green|TFC<ref name=forbesmls/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrissmith/2016/09/07/major-league-soccers-most-valuable-teams-2016-new-york-orlando-thrive-in-first-seasons/#79dbd7a2266a|title=Major League Soccer's Most Valuable Teams 2016: New York, Orlando Thrive In First Seasons|work=[[Forbes]]|date=September 7, 2016|accessdate=September 7, 2016|last=Smith|first=Chris}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrissmith/2015/08/19/major-league-soccers-most-valuable-teams-2015-2/|title=Major League Soccer's Most Valuable Teams 2015|work=[[Forbes]]|date=August 19, 2015|accessdate=August 19, 2015|last=Smith|first=Chris}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrissmith/2013/11/20/major-league-soccers-most-valuable-teams/|title=Major League Soccer's Most Valuable Teams|work=[[Forbes]]|date=November 20, 2013|accessdate=January 22, 2014|last=Smith|first=Chris}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/09/09/mls-soccer-beckham-biz-sports-cz_kb_0909mlsvalues.html|title=Major League Soccer's Most Valuable Teams|date=September 9, 2008|last1=Schwartz|first1=Peter|last2=Badenhausen|first2=Kurt|accessdate=May 8, 2014|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>}}\n}}\n\nNote that the valuations are estimates done by ''[[Forbes]]'', and are not based on numbers provided by MLSE. MLSE has refuted past valuations made by ''Forbes''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2012/11/29/nhl_lockout_maple_leafs_worth_a_billion_says_forbes.html|title=NHL lockout: Maple Leafs worth a billion says Forbes|last=McGran|first=Kevin|date=November 29, 2012|accessdate=March 3, 2020|work=Toronto Star|publisher=Torstar Corporation}}</ref>\n\n===Facilities and properties===\n\n====Owns====\n* [[Scotiabank Arena]] \u2013 a multi-purpose [[indoor arena]] in [[downtown Toronto]] home to the Maple Leafs and Raptors which was constructed at a cost of $265 million\n* [[OVO Athletic Centre]] \u2013 practice facility for the Raptors\n* [[Maple Leaf Square]] (37.5%<ref name=notforsale/>) \u2013 a real estate development adjacent to the Scotiabank Arena, developed in partnership with fellow OTPP subsidiary [[Cadillac Fairview]], which includes, among other tenants, the following businesses operated by MLSE:\n** Real Sports Bar & Grill \u2013 a sports-themed restaurant\n** Real Sports Apparel \u2013 a sports clothing store\n** e11even \u2013 an upscale restaurant on the corner of Bremner and York streets<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/life/food_wine/2011/01/28/e11even_slams_diners_into_boards.html | location=Toronto | work=The Star | first=Amy | last=Pataki | title=E11even Slams Diners Into Boards | date=January 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Invested in and operates (owned by the City of Toronto)====\n* [[BMO Field]] \u2013 home of Toronto FC, the Argonauts and [[Canada men's national soccer team]] ([[CONCACAF]])\n* [[Coca-Cola Coliseum]] \u2013 home of the Marlies\n\n====Invested in====\n* [[Ford Performance Centre]] \u2013 practice facility for the Maple Leafs and Marlies\n* [[BMO Training Ground]] \u2013 practice facility for Toronto FC, and home of Toronto FC II and the TFC Academy\n* [[Lamport Stadium]] \u2013 former home of Toronto FC II and the TFC Academy; practice facility for the Argonauts.\n\n===Television channels===\n* [[Leafs Nation Network]] \u2013 a specialty channel devoted to the Maple Leafs and Marlies (valued at $19 million on behalf of the CRTC in 2012<ref name=\"crtc-mlse2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2012/2012-443.htm|title=Broadcasting Decision CRTC 2012-443|date=August 16, 2012|accessdate=September 3, 2015|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]}}</ref>)\n* [[NBA TV Canada]] \u2013 a localized version of [[NBA TV]], a US basketball channel, which also devotes part of its schedule to specific coverage of the Raptors (valued at $21 million on behalf of the CRTC in 2012<ref name=\"crtc-mlse2\"/>)\n\n==Staff==\n{|style=\"float: right\"\n|[[File:Edward RogersIII.jpg|thumb|Edward Rogers III, Deputy Chairman of Rogers Communications and member of the board of directors of MLSE]]\n|\n|[[File:Shanahan.png|thumb|Brendan Shanahan, President and Alternate Governor, Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n|}\n\n===Board of directors===\n* [[Larry Tanenbaum]] \u2013 Kilmer Sports (non-executive chairman of the board)<ref name=board>{{cite web|url=http://mlse.com/our-company/board-of-directors/|title=Board of Directors|accessdate=March 9, 2014|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment}}</ref>\n* [[George A. Cope]] \u2013 BCE and [[Bell Canada]]<ref name=board/>\n* [[Dale Lastman]] \u2013 [[Goodmans LLP]]<ref name=board/>\n* Guy Laurence \u2013 [[Rogers Communications]]<ref name=board/>\n* [[Edward Rogers III]] \u2013 Rogers Communications<ref name=board/>\n* Anthony Staffieri \u2013 Rogers Communications<ref name=board/>\n* Bernard Le Duc \u2013 Bell Canada<ref name=board/>\n* Siim Vanaselja \u2013 Bell Canada<ref name=board/>\n\n===Executive team===\n* [[Michael Friisdahl]] \u2013 president and CEO<ref name=Friisdahl>{{cite web|url=http://mlse.com/news/mlse-names-michael-friisdahl-president-ceo/|title=MLSE NAMES MICHAEL FRIISDAHL PRESIDENT & CEO|date=October 29, 2015|accessdate=October 29, 2015|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment}}</ref>\n* [[Brendan Shanahan]] \u2013 president and alternate governor, Toronto Maple Leafs<ref name=leaders>{{cite web|url=http://mlse.com/our-company/leaders-at-mlse/|title=Leaders at MLSE|accessdate=March 30, 2014|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment}}</ref>\n* [[Masai Ujiri]] \u2013 president, Toronto Raptors<ref name=leaders/>\n* Bill Manning \u2013 president, Toronto FC and Toronto Argonauts<ref name=leaders/><ref name=ArgosApprove/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Toronto Maple Leafs}}\n{{Toronto Raptors}}\n{{Toronto FC}}\n{{Toronto Argonauts}}\n{{Toronto Marlies}}\n{{NHLOwners}}\n{{NBAOwners}}\n{{Toronto Argonauts owner navbox}}\n{{Rogers Communications}}\n{{Bell Canada}}\n}}\n\n{{portalbar|Canada|Companies|Ontario}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment}}\n[[Category:Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment| ]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Sports management companies]]\n[[Category:Television broadcasting companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer owners]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association owners]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League owners]]\n[[Category:Toronto Argonauts owners]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 1931]]\n[[Category:1931 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Bell Canada]]\n[[Category:Rogers Communications]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maple_Leaf_Sports_%26_Entertainment"}
